    {
      "contentTypeKey": "216ea22b-01af-4645-8972-5766bbd75b6c",
      "udi": "umb://element/bb15d80d88f2468fab6f96698358a0f3",
      "title": "15 April 2022",
      "content": "<p style=\"font-weight: 400;\"><strong>Changes to government guidance regarding face coverings </strong></p>\n<p style=\"font-weight: 400;\">From next Monday, 18 April, the legal requirement to wear a face covering on public transport, in shops and in other indoor settings will be removed in Scotland. Please note, however, that <a href=\"https://www.gov.scot/publications/coronavirus-covid-19-universities-colleges-and-community-learning-and-development-providers/pages/overview/\">the Scottish Government has published guidance for universities, colleges and community learning</a>, which suggests that face coverings continue to be encouraged, even when not mandatory, in settings where the risk of transmission might be considered higher. In line with this advice, we ask those who are able to do so to continue to wear a face covering when moving around our campus buildings and in busy spaces.  </p>\n<p style=\"font-weight: 400;\"><strong>Changes to testing arrangements and to reporting a positive test result to the University </strong></p>\n<p style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Also, from Monday 18 April, the Scottish Government guidance on Covid testing will change, which means that people are no longer being asked to test twice weekly. After this date, only those who have symptoms, are a close contact of someone with Covid, or are visiting a hospital or care home will be asked to undertake a test. The guidance on this can be found <a href=\"https://www.gov.scot/publications/test-protect-transition-plan/pages/1/\">on the Scottish Government's website</a>.</p>\n<p style=\"font-weight: 400;\">To reflect this change, the LFD Collect scheme which has operated in universities has now stopped, and LFD test kits will no longer be available on campus for routine testing from Monday, 18 April.  </p>\n<p style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Students and staff are no longer required to report a positive COVID test result to Campus Operations from Monday, 18 April, nor to inform the School Office and Accommodation Office (students) nor the Head of HR (staff).  </p>\n<p style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Testing will continue for those with symptoms and will be available up to the end of April, with PCR tests available to anyone with symptoms. PCR tests will be accessible at test sites and by post until the end of April. Positive cases will continue to be advised to isolate (though can continue to shorten their isolation period if negative on lateral flow tests on day 6 and day 7). Those who test positive during this period should continue to stay at home for the duration of the self-isolation period. </p>\n<p style=\"font-weight: 400;\"><strong>QMU Business Continuity Group meetings to be replaced by COVID Response Group </strong></p>\n<p style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Since the beginning of the pandemic, representatives from across the University and the Students' Union have attended regular Business Continuity Group meetings to analyse the latest government guidance and put in place measures to keep our community safe. In light of the recent changes to COVID restrictions in place in Scotland, we have decided to replace that group with a COVID Response Group, which will meet every two months. Please be assured that we will continue to be vigilant, to promote positive behaviours and to monitor the position closely, responding as required to any future emerging situation to ensure the safety of all QMU students and staff. </p>\n<p style=\"font-weight: 400;\"><strong>Protecting yourself and others from COVID </strong></p>\n<p style=\"font-weight: 400;\">In line with our commitment to promoting positive behaviours, we ask that our university community continues to act in accordance with the Scottish Government’s COVID Sense guidance, which suggests that, as members of the general public, we: </p>\n<ol style=\"font-weight: 400;\">\n<li>Open windows when socialising indoors. </li>\n<li>Wear a face covering in indoor public places or on public transport (even though this is no longer a legal requirement). </li>\n<li>Wash our hands to protect ourselves and others. </li>\n<li>Get the vaccine when offered. </li>\n</ol>\n<p style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Also, if you are feeling unwell, <strong>please stay at home. </strong></p>\n<p style=\"font-weight: 400;\">If you are on the highest risk list, you can get further support from Student Services or the Human Resources and Health and Safety Team. </p>\n<p style=\"font-weight: 400;\">For <a href=\"https://www.nhsinform.scot/illnesses-and-conditions/infections-and-poisoning/coronavirus-covid-19/coronavirus-covid-19-general-advice\">advice on symptoms and what to do if you think you have coronavirus, visit NHS Inform</a>. </p>\n<p style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> </p>\n<p style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Malcolm G Cutt </p>\n<p style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Director of Finance &amp; Corporate Strategic Development </p>"
    },
