      "title": "7 March 2022",
      "content": "<p>7 March 2022</p>\n<p>Dear students and staff</p>\n<h2>The latest advice from government, and continuing precautions we should all continue to take</h2>\n<p>From listening to <a href=\"https://www.gov.scot/collections/first-ministers-speeches/\">recent statements from the First Minister</a>, I know that you will be aware that some COVID restrictions have now ended, and that there are due to be further relaxations from 21 March.</p>\n<p>As yet, the relaxation of the rules does not change the way in which the University operates.  We will let you know as and when there are any changes.  Our approach is, of course, informed by risk assessments and by our regular meetings with government officials, and is in line with the approach taken by other universities.</p>\n<p>So, please continue:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>to self-isolate when you need to (<a href=\"https://www.nhsinform.scot/illnesses-and-conditions/infections-and-poisoning/coronavirus-covid-19/test-and-protect/coronavirus-covid-19-guidance-for-individuals-with-possible-coronavirus-infection\">guidance available on the NHS Inform website</a>);</li>\n<li>to report self-isolation/a positive COVID test result to the University (see our <a href=\"/coronavirus/faqs/staff/\">staff</a> and <a href=\"/coronavirus/faqs/students/\">student</a> FAQs for details of the process);</li>\n<li>to participate in twice weekly COVID testing (you can still collect testing kits on campus);</li>\n<li>to wear a face covering when required;</li>\n<li>to ventilate rooms by opening windows where possible.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>If you need a reminder of the details of these points, and the rest of our 11 steps to protect yourself and others, please see the <a href=\"/coronavirus/applicants/campus-life/\">campus life and health and safety</a> section of our COVID website. </p>\n<h2>Warning about fraudulent COVID related emails</h2>\n<p>I have one final point to highlight: the Scottish Government has asked us to warn our community of the prevalence of fraudulent e-mails purporting to be from the NHS and asking for personal details or payment information for a ‘COVID-19 passport.’ There is guidance on spotting and avoiding COVID passport fraud on the Trading Standards Scotland website: <a href=\"https://www.tsscot.co.uk/covid-passport-scams/\">COVID Passport Scams - Trading Standards Scotland (tsscot.co.uk)</a>. The main guidance is that the NHS will not:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>ask you for any payment to receive a copy of your vaccination status;</li>\n<li>ask you for bank details;</li>\n<li>ask you to prove your identity by sending copies of personal documents such as passports;</li>\n<li>tell you that you only have a limited time in which to apply to receive your status.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Thank you for your continued support.</p>\n<p>Malcolm G Cutt</p>\n<p>Director of Finance and Corporate Strategic Development</p>"
    },
