      "title": "14 January 2022",
      "content": "<p><span class=\"lead\">For students:</span></p>\n<p>Dear students</p>\n<p>Happy new year. </p>\n<p>As you will know, the new semester starts next week (17 January) and our plans to maintain levels of on-campus teaching activity remain unchanged from the position set out before the break, with students able to access face to face on-campus activity as usual for all of their small group work (seminars, workshops, studio work, clinics etc.), but with lectures primarily delivered online.  We look forward to welcoming you back, and to welcoming those students joining us for the first time this year.</p>\n<p><strong>Things to remember</strong></p>\n<p>See below for some important things to remember at this time:</p>\n<p><strong>Test before travel: </strong>students changing household for the start of the semester should follow ‘Test Before Travel’ advice. This means taking an LFD test three days before travel and on the day of travel.</p>\n<p><strong>Test regularly:</strong> we should all continue to test ourselves regularly for COVID, particularly before meeting others, and <a href=\"https://www.gov.uk/report-covid19-result\" title=\"UK Government website - Report Negative COVID Test result\">report the test result</a> every time, whether it's positive, negative or void, as that helps to give a better picture of the level of coronavirus in the community. The University is continuing to provide access to lateral flow device (LFD) testing kits at various collection points on campus, including the main reception, the Students’ Union and within student accommodation.  LFD testing kits are also available across Scotland <a href=\"https://www.nhsinform.scot/illnesses-and-conditions/infections-and-poisoning/coronavirus-covid-19/test-and-protect/coronavirus-covid-19-get-a-test-if-you-do-not-have-symptoms\" title=\"NHS Inform\">through home delivery, and at community testing centres and local pharmacies</a>.  </p>\n<p><strong>Changes to testing and self-isolation rules (effective from 5 January): (</strong>1) If you get a positive LFD result but have no COVID symptoms, changes to testing arrangements mean that you do not need to take a PCR test to confirm this, <u>but you should still seek a PCR text if you have symptoms. </u>(2) If you test positive, while the standard self-isolation period remains at ten days, you now have the option to end isolation after seven days if you have no fever and record two negative lateral flow tests. The first test must be taken no earlier than six days after testing positive, while the second must be at least 24 hours after that.  (3) Rather than quarantining, you must now take an LFD test every day for seven days if a close contact tests positive, if you are fully vaccinated.  If you are not yet fully vaccinated, you must isolate for ten days and take a PCR test.   More guidance is available on the <a href=\"https://www.gov.scot/coronavirus-covid-19/\" title=\"Scottish Government website\">Scottish Government website</a>.</p>\n<p><strong>Who to tell at QMU if you are self-isolating, or have a positive COVID test (LFD or PCR test): </strong>If you are self-isolating, or suspect you have coronavirus, or have coronavirus, please remember to: (1) tell Security (0131 474 0000 ext 2222) - and Accommodation (0131 474 0000 x 4902) if you live on campus; (2) Contact the School Office - <a href=\"mailto:schooloffice@qmu.ac.uk\" title=\"Contact the School Office\"><strong>schooloffice@qmu.ac.uk</strong></a><strong>.</strong></p>\n<p><strong>G</strong><strong>et boosted if you are not already:</strong> we are all being strongly encouraged to get a COVID booster if we have not done so already to protect ourselves and others. You can find out more about booking your booster on the <a href=\"https://www.nhsinform.scot/covid-19-vaccine/the-vaccines/coronavirus-covid-19-booster-vaccination/\" title=\"NHS Inform\">NHS Inform website</a>, or on the NHS Lothian website, which provides <a href=\"https://www.nhslothian.scot/Coronavirus/Vaccine/Pages/Drop-in-Clinics.aspx\" title=\"NHS Lothian website\">details of drop-in clinics</a>.  If you haven’t been vaccinated at all, please note that the NHS Inform site also provides information on getting your first and second dose. <strong><u>NHS Lothian are running a COVID Booster Vaccination Station for QMU students on campus on Monday (17<sup>th</sup> <sup>) </sup>January </u><u>from 10am to 4pm, in room 66 on Level 0 of the main academic building. </u><u> </u><u>No prior booking is required. Just go to the registration desk in 1875.</u></strong></p>\n<p><strong>Socialise carefully:</strong> the First Minister is asking us to limit the number of social contacts at the time, and, until further notice, to limit indoor gatherings to no more than three households. When meeting indoors, please keep the space well ventilated.</p>\n<p>The Scottish Government has launched an <a href=\"https://bit.ly/covid-safety2022\" title=\"COVID safety e-module\">updated version of its COVID safety e-learning module</a> for students to take account of Omicron. We encourage students to complete this module.  In addition, students and staff can find a summary of the steps we can all take to keep one another safe on the <a href=\"/{localLink:umb://document/e3a1cc188042429781c78bab7ff95416}\" title=\"Campus Life\">Campus Life and Health and Safety section of our coronavirus website</a>. </p>\n<p>Wishing you all the best for 2022.</p>\n<p>Malcolm G Cutt</p>\n<p>Director of Finance and Corporate Strategic Development</p>\n<p><span class=\"lead\">For staff:</span></p>\n<p>Dear colleagues</p>\n<p>Happy new year. </p>\n<p>As you will know, the new semester starts next week (17 January) and our plans to maintain levels of on-campus teaching activity remain unchanged from the position set out before the break, with students able to access face to face on-campus activity as usual for all of their small group work (seminars, workshops, studio work, clinics etc.), but with lectures primarily delivered online.  We look forward to welcoming students back, and to welcoming those students joining us for the first time this year.</p>\n<p><strong>Latest advice on home versus on-campus working</strong></p>\n<p>While on-campus teaching will continue as planned, we are not quite yet returning to the interim hybrid working model that we were operating before the Scottish Government increased the emphasis on working from home in December. This reflects the advice from the First Minister in her <a href=\"https://www.gov.scot/publications/coronavirus-covid-19-update-first-ministers-statement-11-january-2022/\" title=\"Scottish Government - First Minister Statement 11th Jan\">statement to the Scottish Parliament on Tuesday</a>.</p>\n<p>This means that, although the hybrid working model for the start of this semester will be a lot like that for last semester, for the short term staff should continue to consider working from home if their presence on campus is not necessary.  Meetings should generally be held online at this time.</p>\n<p>We still expect those members of staff whose role involves face-to-face interaction with students, and those members of staff whose presence on campus is required to enable that interaction, to be present on campus when that presence is required. This applies to all members of academic staff involved in in-person teaching. It also applies to members of staff in professional services areas who provide a face-to-face service to students, and to those staff whose role is such that their presence on campus is required for them to perform it. Similarly, there are professional services staff who need to provide in-person support to other staff.  </p>\n<p>By way of contrast, those members of staff whose role does not involve any direct face-to-face contact with students, and who do not provide essential in-person services for colleagues, should continue to work from home in the short-term if they are able to carry out their duties remotely.</p>\n<p>If you are not sure whether your presence is required on campus, please ask your Head of Division or Service for advice. In turn, and if required, they can seek advice from their SLT member as appropriate.</p>\n<p>We recognise that some staff may wish to continue working on campus simply for reasons of wellbeing, and that is allowed.</p>\n<p>We hope that we can soon return to the interim model of hybrid working that was operational for most of the last semester. The Business Continuity Group will be reviewing the situation frequently.</p>\n<p><strong>Things we are telling students to remember</strong></p>\n<p>See below for some important things we are telling students to remember at this time:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Test before travel: </strong>students changing household for the start of the semester should follow ‘Test Before Travel’ advice. This means taking an LFD test three days before travel and on the day of travel.</li>\n<li><strong>Test regularly:</strong> we should all continue to test ourselves regularly for COVID, particularly before meeting others, and <a href=\"https://www.gov.uk/report-covid19-result\" title=\"UK Government website - Report a negative COVID test\">report the test result</a> every time, whether it's positive, negative or void, as that helps to give a better picture of the level of coronavirus in the community. The University is continuing to provide access to lateral flow device (LFD) testing kits at various collection points on campus, including the main reception, the Students’ Union and within student accommodation.  LFD testing kits are also available across Scotland <a href=\"https://www.nhsinform.scot/illnesses-and-conditions/infections-and-poisoning/coronavirus-covid-19/test-and-protect/coronavirus-covid-19-get-a-test-if-you-do-not-have-symptoms\" title=\"NHS Inform\">through home delivery, and at community testing centres and local pharmacies</a>.  </li>\n<li><strong>Changes to testing and self-isolation rules (effective from 5 January): (</strong>1) If you get a positive LFD result but have no COVID symptoms, changes to testing arrangements mean that you do not need to take a PCR test to confirm this, <u>but you should still seek a PCR text if you have symptoms. </u>(2) If you test positive, while the standard self-isolation period remains at ten days, you now have the option to end isolation after seven days if you have no fever and record two negative lateral flow tests. The first test must be taken no earlier than six days after testing positive, while the second must be at least 24 hours after that. (3) Rather than quarantining, you must now take an LFD test every day for seven days if a close contact tests positive, if you are fully vaccinated.  If you are not yet fully vaccinated, you must isolate for ten days and take a PCR test.   More guidance is available on the <a href=\"https://www.gov.scot/coronavirus-covid-19/\" title=\"Scottish Government website\">Scottish Government website</a>.</li>\n<li><strong>Get boosted if you are not already:</strong> we are all being strongly encouraged to get a COVID booster if we have not done so already to protect ourselves and others. You can find out more about booking your booster on the <a href=\"https://www.nhsinform.scot/covid-19-vaccine/the-vaccines/coronavirus-covid-19-booster-vaccination/\" title=\"NHS Inform\">NHS Inform website</a>, or on the NHS Lothian website, which provides <a href=\"https://www.nhslothian.scot/Coronavirus/Vaccine/Pages/Drop-in-Clinics.aspx\" title=\"NHS Lothian website\">details of drop-in clinics</a>.  If you haven’t been vaccinated at all, please note that the NHS Inform site also provides information on getting your first and second dose. NHS Lothian are running a COVID Booster Vaccination Station for QMU students on campus on Monday (17<sup>th</sup><sup>) </sup>January from  10am to 4pm, in room 66 on Level 0 of the main academic building.  No prior booking is required. Just go to the registration desk in 1875.</li>\n<li><strong>Socialise carefully:</strong> the First Minister is asking us to limit the number of social contacts at the time, and, until further notice, to limit indoor gatherings to no more than three households. When meeting indoors, please keep the space well ventilated.</li>\n</ul>\n<p><strong>Who to tell at QMU if you are self-isolating, or have a positive COVID test (LFD or PCR test)</strong></p>\n<p><strong> </strong><strong><em>Staff members</em></strong><strong> who are </strong>self-isolating, or suspect they have coronavirus, or have coronavirus, should: (1) tell Security (tel 0131 474 0000 ext 2222); (2) email the Head of Human Resources at <a href=\"mailto:ASmith2@qmu.ac.uk\" title=\"Email ASmith2@qmu.ac.uk for further information\"><strong>ASmith2@qmu.ac.uk</strong></a><strong>; </strong>(3) advise their line manager.<strong><em> Students</em></strong> who are self-isolating or a have a positive COVID test (LFD or PCR test) need to (1) tell Security (0131 474 0000 ext 2222) - and Accommodation (0131 474 0000 x 4902) if they live on campus; (2) Contact the School Office <strong>(</strong><a href=\"mailto:schooloffice@qmu.ac.uk\" title=\"Contact the School Office\"><strong>schooloffice@qmu.ac.uk</strong></a><strong>).</strong></p>\n<p><strong>Other information</strong></p>\n<p>The Scottish Government has launched an <a href=\"https://bit.ly/covid-safety2022\" title=\"COVID Safety 2022\">updated version of its COVID safety e-learning module</a> for students to take account of Omicron. We have encouraged students to complete this module.  In addition, students and staff can find a summary of the steps we can all take to keep one another safe on the <a href=\"/{localLink:umb://document/e3a1cc188042429781c78bab7ff95416}\" title=\"Campus Life\">Campus Life and Health and Safety section of our coronavirus website</a>. </p>\n<p>You might like to note that the University COVID risk assessment has been updated. You can find it on the <a href=\"https://myshare.qmu.ac.uk/services/campus-commercial-services/covid19/SitePages/Risk%20Assessments.aspx\" title=\"My Share QMU\">coronavirus section of the intranet</a>.</p>\n<p>Wishing you all the best for 2022.</p>\n<p>Malcolm G Cutt</p>\n<p>Director of Finance and Corporate Strategic Development</p>\n<p> </p>"
