      "content": "<p><span class=\"lead-big\">For students:</span></p>\n<p>Dear students</p>\n<p>Here is our final planned coronavirus update before the Christmas closure period.</p>\n<h2><span class=\"lead\">New advice from the Scottish Government</span></h2>\n<p><strong>No change to advice for Christmas but a request for us to limit our contacts for three weeks from 26 December:</strong> In her <a href=\"https://www.gov.scot/publications/coronavirus-covid-19-update-first-ministers-statement-21-december-2021/\">statement to the Scottish Parliament yesterday</a>, the First Minister advised there are no changes in the advice for Christmas.  She made a new request which is that as we come out of the Christmas weekend -  and at least until the end of the first week in January – we go back to limiting our contacts as much as we possibly can, staying at home as much as possible. This includes Hogmanay and New Year.  As you will remember, in the run up to Christmas we have been asked to minimise socialising, limiting any gathering to three households, and to test before meeting up with others. </p>\n<p><strong>Restrictions on size of live public events and on sport: </strong>The First Minister also announced the government’s intention to place limits on the size of live public events from 26 December for a period of three weeks, including spectator sports and Hogmanay events.  In addition, she advised that non-professional indoor contact sports for adults should not take place during the three week period from 26 December. </p>\n<h2><span class=\"lead\">Reminder to take important papers home</span></h2>\n<p>If you are a student changing household over Christmas, we suggest that take with you any important papers and other possessions that you think you might need early next year, in light of the current uncertainties arising from the Omicron COVID variant. Similarly, we encourage staff to ensure that they have any essential work-related items with them at home before Christmas.</p>\n<h2><span class=\"lead\">Reminder of other pre-existing key guidance from the Scottish Government</span></h2>\n<p><strong>COVID boosters: </strong>We are all being strongly encouraged to take up the opportunity of a COVID booster as soon as we are eligible. You can <a href=\"https://www.nhsinform.scot/flu-vaccine/invitations-and-appointments/book-a-flu-or-coronavirus-booster-vaccination\">find out more about booking your booster on the NHS Inform website</a>.  If you haven’t been vaccinated at all, please note that the NHS Inform site also provides information on getting your first and second dose.</p>\n<p><strong>Importance of regular testing:</strong> We should all continue to test ourselves regularly for COVID, particularly before meeting others. We are continuing to provide access to lateral flow device (LFD) testing kits at various collection points on campus, including the main reception, the Students’ Union and within student accommodation.  LFD testing kits are also available across Scotland <a href=\"https://www.nhsinform.scot/illnesses-and-conditions/infections-and-poisoning/coronavirus-covid-19/test-and-protect/coronavirus-covid-19-get-a-test-if-you-do-not-have-symptoms\">through home delivery, and at community testing centres and local pharmacies</a>.</p>\n<p><strong>New rules on self-isolation:</strong> The rules on self-isolation changed earlier this month. Now, all household contacts of a positive case need to isolate for 10 days irrespective of vaccine status and even following a negative test.  If you are a student who is self-isolating, please tell us so that we can offer you appropriate advice and pastoral support, and note that our <a href=\"/coronavirus/faqs/accommodation/\">Accommodation coronavirus FAQs</a> provide information on the support we can offer self-isolating students living on campus.</p>\n<p><strong>International travel:</strong> anyone planning travel between Scotland and countries outside the common travel area should check the <a href=\"https://www.gov.scot/publications/coronavirus-covid-19-international-travel-quarantine/\">Scottish Government website</a> for detailed guidance; and you should also check the requirements of the country you are travelling to, because the requirements there may well be different to those in force here. All travel rules and guidance are, of course, subject to frequent change at the moment.  International students with any questions about travel should contact our International Office for support (<a href=\"mailto:international@qmu.ac.uk\">international@qmu.ac.uk</a>).</p>\n<p><strong>Test before travel within the UK</strong>: We remind students planning to travel between households within the UK over the festive period to follow the latest ‘Test Before Travel’ advice. This means taking an LFD test three days before travel and on the day of travel. It also means taking an LFD test three days before travel and on the day of travel before returning to your original or term-time household.</p>\n<h2><span class=\"lead\">Planning for the festive season and next semester</span></h2>\n<p>We have published on our website <a href=\"/news-and-events/christmas-closure-dates/\">information on the services available during the campus ‘closure’ period</a> of 23 December to 4 January inclusive.  </p>\n<p>Looking forward to 2022, at this point we still anticipate maintaining levels of on-campus teaching activity as previously planned, with the semester starting on 17 January in accordance with the published academic calendar.  Our Senior Leadership Team will continue to monitor the situation over the Christmas closure period. During the closure period, if we need to update you on any significant coronavirus developments affecting QMU, we will do so via Moderator, our <a href=\"/coronavirus/updates/\">coronavirus website</a> and on social media<strong>.   </strong>In addition, of course, we have well establishing processes in place for cascading key information from the senior leadership team through to divisions and professional service areas.</p>\n<h2><span class=\"lead\">Call for volunteers to assist the booster programme</span></h2>\n<p>The Scottish Government has asked us to communicate that any student or staff member who would like to volunteer to assist the booster programme in a non-clinical capacity can register with the National Volunteer Co-ordination Hub. Volunteers are likely to be needed at different times and locations around Scotland, so will only be deployed as and when there is a real need for volunteers in their area.  Anyone who wishes to volunteer can register their interest with the National Volunteer Coordination Hub by emailing <a href=\"mailto:Covid_19ResponseScotland@redcross.org.uk\">Covid_19ResponseScotland@redcross.org.uk</a></p>\n<p>Wishing you a happy festive season.</p>\n<p>Malcolm G Cutt</p>\n<p>Director of Finance and Corporate Strategic Development</p>\n<p><span class=\"lead\">For staff:</span></p>\n<p>Dear colleagues</p>\n<p>Here is our final planned coronavirus update before the Christmas closure period.</p>\n<h2><span class=\"lead\">New advice from the Scottish Government</span></h2>\n<p><strong>No change to advice for Christmas but a request for us to limit our contacts for three weeks from 26 December:</strong> In her <a href=\"https://www.gov.scot/publications/coronavirus-covid-19-update-first-ministers-statement-21-december-2021/\">statement to the Scottish Parliament yesterday</a>, the First Minister advised there are no changes in the advice for Christmas.  She made a new request which is that as we come out of the Christmas weekend -  and at least until the end of the first week in January – we go back to limiting our contacts as much as we possibly can, staying at home as much as possible. This includes Hogmanay and New Year.  As you will remember, in the run up to Christmas we have been asked to minimise socialising, limiting any gathering to three households, and to test before meeting up with others. </p>\n<p><strong>Restrictions on size of live public events and on sport: </strong>The First Minister also announced the government’s intention to place limits on the size of live public events from 26 December for a period of three weeks, including spectator sports and Hogmanay events.  In addition, she advised that non-professional indoor contact sports for adults should not take place during the three week period from 26 December. </p>\n<h2><span class=\"lead\">Reminder to take important papers home</span></h2>\n<p>For students changing household over Christmas, we have suggested that they take with them any important papers and other possessions that they think they might need early next year, in light of the current uncertainties arising from the Omicron COVID variant. Similarly, we encourage staff to ensure that they have any essential work-related items with them at home before Christmas.</p>\n<h2><span class=\"lead\">Reminder of other pre-existing key guidance from the Scottish Government</span></h2>\n<p><strong>COVID boosters: </strong>We are all being strongly encouraged to take up the opportunity of a COVID booster as soon as we are eligible. You can <a href=\"https://www.nhsinform.scot/flu-vaccine/invitations-and-appointments/book-a-flu-or-coronavirus-booster-vaccination\">find out more about booking your booster on the NHS Inform website</a>.  If you haven’t been vaccinated at all, please note that the NHS Inform site also provides information on getting your first and second dose.</p>\n<p><strong>Importance of regular testing:</strong> We should all continue to test ourselves regularly for COVID, particularly before meeting others. We are continuing to provide access to lateral flow device (LFD) testing kits at various collection points on campus, including the main reception, the Students’ Union and within student accommodation.  LFD testing kits are also available across Scotland <a href=\"https://www.nhsinform.scot/illnesses-and-conditions/infections-and-poisoning/coronavirus-covid-19/test-and-protect/coronavirus-covid-19-get-a-test-if-you-do-not-have-symptoms\">through home delivery, and at community testing centres and local pharmacies</a>.</p>\n<p><strong>New rules on self-isolation:</strong> The rules on self-isolation changed earlier this month. Now, all household contacts of a positive case need to isolate for 10 days irrespective of vaccine status and even following a negative test.  We have asked students who are self-isolating to tell us so that we can offer them appropriate advice and pastoral support, and to note that our <a href=\"/coronavirus/faqs/accommodation/\">Accommodation coronavirus FAQs</a> provide information on the support we can offer self-isolating students living on campus.</p>\n<p><strong>International travel:</strong> anyone planning travel between Scotland and countries outside the common travel area should check the <a href=\"https://www.gov.scot/publications/coronavirus-covid-19-international-travel-quarantine/\">Scottish Government website</a> for detailed guidance; and you should also check the requirements of the country you are travelling to, because the requirements there may well be different to those in force here. All travel rules and guidance are, of course, subject to frequent change at the moment.  International students with any questions about travel should contact our International Office for support (<a href=\"mailto:international@qmu.ac.uk\">international@qmu.ac.uk</a>).</p>\n<p><strong>Test before travel within the UK</strong>: We remind students planning to travel between households within the UK over the festive period to follow the latest ‘Test Before Travel’ advice. This means taking an LFD test three days before travel and on the day of travel. It also means taking an LFD test three days before travel and on the day of travel before returning to your original or term-time household.</p>\n<h2><span class=\"lead\">Planning for the festive season and next semester</span></h2>\n<p>We have published on our website <a href=\"/news-and-events/christmas-closure-dates/\">information on the services available during the campus ‘closure’ period</a> of 23 December to 4 January inclusive.  </p>\n<p>Looking forward to 2022, at this point we still anticipate maintaining levels of on-campus teaching activity as previously planned, with the semester starting on 17 January in accordance with the published academic calendar.  Our Senior Leadership Team will continue to monitor the situation over the Christmas closure period. During the closure period, if we need to update you on any significant coronavirus developments affecting QMU, we will do so via Moderator, our <a href=\"/coronavirus/updates/\">coronavirus website</a> and on social media<strong>.   </strong>In addition, of course, we have well establishing processes in place for cascading key information from the senior leadership team through to divisions and professional service areas.</p>\n<p>As you know, we are <a href=\"https://myshare.qmu.ac.uk/news/Lists/Posts/Post.aspx?ID=2307\">asking staff to consider working from home until 14 January except where their presence on campus is necessary</a>. The campus remains open for those who need to access it (but without access to the staff offices during the Christmas closure period).</p>\n<h2><span class=\"lead\">Call for volunteers to assist the booster programme</span></h2>\n<p>The Scottish Government has asked us to communicate that any student or staff member who would like to volunteer to assist the booster programme in a non-clinical capacity can register with the National Volunteer Co-ordination Hub. Volunteers are likely to be needed at different times and locations around Scotland, so will only be deployed as and when there is a real need for volunteers in their area.  Anyone who wishes to volunteer can register their interest with the National Volunteer Coordination Hub by emailing <a href=\"mailto:Covid_19ResponseScotland@redcross.org.uk\">Covid_19ResponseScotland@redcross.org.uk</a></p>\n<p>Wishing you a happy festive season.</p>\n<p>Malcolm G Cutt</p>\n<p>Director of Finance and Corporate Strategic Development</p>"
