      "contentTypeKey": "216ea22b-01af-4645-8972-5766bbd75b6c",
      "udi": "umb://element/6970f75243594575b82bd1ca83183a24",
      "title": "17 December 2021",
      "content": "<p>Dear students and staff</p>\n<h2>Further COVID advice from government</h2>\n<p>At the request of the Scottish Government, we are communicating with you now to flag up a couple of important points:</p>\n<ol>\n<li>If you are a student changing household over Christmas, we suggest that you take with you any important papers and other possessions that you think you might need early next year. This is in case travel restrictions are brought in early next year, in light of the current uncertainties arising from the Omicron COVID variant. Similarly, we encourage staff to ensure that they have any essential work-related items with them at home before Christmas.</li>\n<li>We have been asked to advise that there should be no staff social gatherings of any size, on or off campus, until further notice.</li>\n</ol>\n<p>In addition, please note that there is specific travel guidance from government for students travelling to Northern Ireland over Christmas.  This guidance is set out in on the <a href=\"https://www.studentinformation.gov.scot/coronavirus/students-returning-to-northern-ireland\">Student Information Scotland website</a>. (Travel advice for the University community as a whole appears in our <a href=\"/{localLink:umb://document/b673e3c08a21451691ec92f364641f89}\" title=\"Coronavirus\">last (14 December) regular COVID update</a>.)</p>\n<p>We will issue our usual regular COVID update next week.</p>\n<p>Malcolm G Cutt</p>\n<p>Director of Finance and Corporate Strategic Development</p>\n<p> </p>\n<p> </p>\n<p> </p>\n<p> </p>"
    },
    {
      "contentTypeKey": "216ea22b-01af-4645-8972-5766bbd75b6c",
      "udi": "umb://element/a1839993b9064804af09fc833692f28d",
      "title": "14 December 2021",
      "content": "<p><strong>Tuesday 14 December</strong></p>\n<p><strong>For students:</strong></p>\n<p>Dear students</p>\n<p>Here is the latest information on COVID as it affects life at QMU, focusing on the things we can do to help protect ourselves and our communities from the Omicron variant.</p>\n<h2>Latest guidance from the Scottish Government</h2>\n<p><strong>COVID boosters: </strong>We are all being strongly encouraged to take up the opportunity of a COVID booster as soon as we are eligible. 18-29 year olds can book their booster from tomorrow (15 December). You can <a href=\"https://www.nhsinform.scot/flu-vaccine/invitations-and-appointments/book-a-flu-or-coronavirus-booster-vaccination\">find out more about booking your booster on the NHS Inform website</a>.  If you haven’t been vaccinated at all, please note that the NHS Inform site also provides information on getting your first and second dose.</p>\n<p><strong>Importance of regular testing:</strong> The First Minister has emphasised the importance of us all testing ourselves regularly for COVID, particularly before meeting others.</p>\n<p><strong>Restricting social interactions:</strong> In her statement to the Scottish Parliament today, the First Minister has asked us to cut back interactions with other households as much as we can. If we do socialise, we are asked to limit any gathering to three households and test before meeting.  </p>\n<p><strong>New rules on self-isolation:</strong> The rules on self-isolation have changed. Now, all household contacts of a positive case need to isolate for 10 days irrespective of vaccine status and even following a negative test.  If you are a student who is self-isolating, please tell us so that we can offer you appropriate advice and pastoral support, and note that our <a href=\"/{localLink:umb://document/31e6aefad28e4c1db319b74906363b59}\" title=\"Accommodation\">Accommodation coronavirus FAQs</a> provide information on the support we can offer self-isolating students living on campus.</p>\n<h2>Latest information on international travel</h2>\n<p>The First Minister has reminded us that anyone planning travel between Scotland and countries outside the common travel area should check the <a href=\"https://www.gov.scot/publications/coronavirus-covid-19-international-travel-quarantine/\"><strong>Scottish Government website</strong></a> for detailed guidance; and you should also check the requirements of the country you are travelling to, because the requirements there may well be different to those in force here International students with any questions about travel should contact our International Office for support (<a href=\"mailto:international@qmu.ac.uk\">international@qmu.ac.uk</a>).</p>\n<h2>Advice for students planning to travel between households over the festive period</h2>\n<p>We remind students planning to travel between households within the UK over the festive period to follow the latest ‘Test Before Travel’ advice. This means taking an LFD test three days before travel and on the day of travel. It also means taking an LFD test three days before travel and on the day of travel before returning to your original or term-time household.</p>\n<h2>Campus remains fully open for those who need to access it</h2>\n<p>The campus remains fully open though more staff are working from home, in line with the latest Government guidance. All student services remain available.</p>\n<h2>Planning for the festive season and beyond</h2>\n<p>We have published on our website information on the services available during the campus ‘closure’ period of 23 December to 4 January inclusive.  Between now and the closure period, we will scale back our catering services as footfall reduces, while ensuring that there is always catering provision in Maggie’s. Over the closure period, if we we needed to update you on any significant coronavirus developments affecting QMU, we would do so via our <a href=\"/{localLink:umb://document/b673e3c08a21451691ec92f364641f89}\" title=\"Coronavirus\">coronavirus website</a> and on social media<strong>.   </strong></p>\n<p>I hope that you find this update useful.</p>\n<p>Malcolm G Cutt</p>\n<p>Director of Finance and Corporate Strategic Development</p>\n<p> </p>\n<p>For staff:</p>\n<p>Dear colleagues</p>\n<p>Here is the latest information on COVID as it affects life at QMU, focusing on the things we can do to help protect ourselves and our communities from the Omicron variant.</p>\n<h2>Latest guidance from the Scottish Government</h2>\n<p><strong>COVID boosters: </strong>We are all being strongly encouraged to take up the opportunity of a COVID booster as soon as we are eligible. 18-29 year olds can book their booster from tomorrow (15 December). You can <a href=\"https://www.nhsinform.scot/flu-vaccine/invitations-and-appointments/book-a-flu-or-coronavirus-booster-vaccination\">find out more about booking your booster on the NHS Inform website</a>.  If you haven’t been vaccinated at all, please note that the NHS Inform site also provides information on getting your first and second dose.</p>\n<p><strong>Importance of regular testing:</strong> The First Minister has emphasised the importance of us all testing ourselves regularly for COVID, particularly before meeting others.</p>\n<p><strong>Restricting social interactions:</strong> In her statement to the Scottish Parliament today, the First Minister has asked us to cut back interactions with other households as much as we can. If we do socialise, we are asked to limit any gathering to three households and test before meeting.  </p>\n<p><strong>New rules on self-isolation:</strong> The rules on self-isolation have changed. Now, all household contacts of a positive case need to isolate for 10 days irrespective of vaccine status and even following a negative test.  We have asked students who are self-isolating to tell us so that we can offer them appropriate advice and pastoral support, and to note that our <a href=\"/coronavirus/faqs/accommodation/\">Accommodation coronavirus FAQs</a> provide information on the support we can offer self-isolating students living on campus.</p>\n<h2>Latest information on international travel</h2>\n<p>The First Minister has reminded us that anyone planning travel between Scotland and countries outside the common travel area should check the <a href=\"https://www.gov.scot/publications/coronavirus-covid-19-international-travel-quarantine/\"><strong>Scottish Government website</strong></a> for detailed guidance; and you should also check the requirements of the country you are travelling to, because the requirements there may well be different to those in force here. International students with any questions about travel should contact our International Office for support (<a href=\"mailto:international@qmu.ac.uk\">international@qmu.ac.uk</a>). Staff planning any University-related travel should note that we have changed our guidance, and that you will find this updated guidance on our <a href=\"/coronavirus/faqs/staff/\">coronavirus FAQs for staff</a>.</p>\n<h2>Advice for students planning to travel between households over the festive period</h2>\n<p>We have reminded students planning to travel between households within the UK over the festive period to follow the latest ‘Test Before Travel’ advice. This means taking an LFD test three days before travel and on the day of travel. It also means taking an LFD test three days before travel and on the day of travel before returning to their original or term-time household.</p>\n<h2>Campus remains fully open for those who need to access it</h2>\n<p>As you will know, we are <a href=\"https://myshare.qmu.ac.uk/news/Lists/Posts/Post.aspx?ID=2307\">asking staff to consider working from home until 14 January except where their presence on campus is necessary</a>.  We believe that our approach is in line with Government policy as communicated in the First Minister’s parliamentary statement today (14 December) but we will, of course, carefully review and act on new guidance should it come in.    </p>\n<p>The campus remains fully open.   If you need to attend campus, you might be trying to reduce your use of public transport given the concern about Omicron. If so, please rest assured that there is plenty of parking space in our car park on campus at this time, and a range of flexible parking tickets.  You can find more information on the <a href=\"/location-and-getting-here/parking-on-campus/\">Parking section</a> of our website.</p>\n<h2>Planning for the festive season and beyond</h2>\n<p>We have published on our website <a href=\"/news-and-events/christmas-closure-dates/\">i</a>nformation on the services available during the campus ‘closure’ period of 23 December to 4 January inclusive.  Between now and the closure period, we will scale back our catering services as footfall reduces, while ensuring that there is always catering provision in Maggie’s. Over the closure period, if we we needed to update you on any significant coronavirus developments affecting QMU, we would do so via our <a href=\"/coronavirus/updates/\">coronavirus website</a> and on social media<strong>.   </strong>In addition, of course, we have well establishing processes in place for cascading key information from the senior leadership team through to divisions and professional service areas.</p>\n<p>I hope that you find this update useful.</p>\n<p>Malcolm G Cutt</p>\n<p>Director of Finance and Corporate Strategic Development</p>\n<p> </p>\n<p> </p>\n<p> </p>\n<p> </p>\n<p> </p>\n<p> </p>"
    },
