      "title": "2 December 2021",
      "content": "<p><strong>Coronavirus (COVID-19) update (focused on Omicron): Thursday 2 December</strong></p>\n<p><strong>For students:</strong></p>\n<p>Dear students</p>\n<p>You will be aware from media reports of the emergence of the new Omicron COVID variant, and we appreciate that you may have some questions around this.</p>\n<p>This message is to reassure you that we are monitoring the situation closely, and considering the potential impact on the QMU community. We hope that the information set out below provides some initial answers to questions you may have at this time.</p>\n<p><strong>Current </strong><strong>guidance </strong><strong>and </strong><strong>important advice to control the spread of the virus</strong></p>\n<p>Our key message to you is that the Scottish Government has not changed its advice to universities, and, at this stage, has indicated that it does not intend to introduce restrictions that would alter our current and planned teaching activity. Like all universities, we exceed the requirements of the current COVID guidance for higher education in our current operations at QMU. </p>\n<p>Nevertheless, in response to the new variant, the Scottish Government is <a href=\"https://www.gov.scot/collections/first-ministers-speeches/\">asking us all step up and continue to do our part in complying with existing protections</a> (face coverings, ventilation, regular testing etc).</p>\n<p>All members of our community are therefore reminded of the steps they can take to control the spread of the virus.</p>\n<p>In particular, we are all asked to ensure that we take a lateral flow test <em>whenever we are planning to socialise</em> or plan to be in a place where there are a lot of people. This is alongside, and in addition to, the recommendation that we all take a lateral flow test at least twice a week. We encourage you to continue to test for COVID twice weekly, and also before socialising, whether that is going out for drinks or dinner, visiting someone at home or even going shopping somewhere that might be crowded.</p>\n<p>To assist you in this, we are continuing to provide access to lateral flow device (LFD) testing kits at various collections points on campus, including the main reception, the Students’ Union and within student accommodation.  LFD testing kits are also available in Scotland through home delivery, at community testing centres and local pharmacies. Details are available at the <a href=\"https://www.nhsinform.scot/illnesses-and-conditions/infections-and-poisoning/coronavirus-covid-19/test-and-protect/coronavirus-covid-19-get-a-test-if-you-do-not-have-symptoms\">NHS Inform website</a>.</p>\n<p>For a reminder of the steps you can take to protect our campus community and society more generally, please see the <a href=\"/coronavirus/applicants/campus-life/\">campus life and health and safety section of our coronavirus website</a>.   Also, do note that local health boards are now putting arrangements in place to make booster COVID vaccines available from 12 weeks after your second dose. See the <a href=\"https://www.nhsinform.scot/covid-19-vaccine/the-vaccines/coronavirus-covid-19-booster-vaccination/\">NHS Inform website</a> for more information.</p>\n<p><strong>Advice on travel</strong></p>\n<p>Students planning to travel abroad around the Christmas period should regularly check the latest advice on travel from the <a href=\"https://www.gov.uk/foreign-travel-advice\">UK Government’s Foreign Office website</a>. The advice is changing frequently, sometimes at short notice. Most countries require proof of vaccination and/or a negative PCR test before entry is permitted.  Please also check the <a href=\"https://www.gov.scot/publications/coronavirus-covid-19-international-travel-quarantine/\">Scottish Government website</a> regularly for guidance and rules on booking and planning travel to Scotland.</p>\n<p>If you have any concerns about travel, whether you be an international student or a student going out on an exchange, please contact our International Office (international@qmu.ac.uk).</p>\n<p>We remind students planning to travel between households over the festive period within the UK to follow the latest ‘Test Before Travel’ advice. This means taking an LFD test three days before travel and on the day of travel. It also means taking an LFD test three days before travel and on the day of travel before returning to their original or term-time household.</p>\n<p><strong>Further updates and advice</strong></p>\n<p>We continue to manage our response to COVID through our Business Continuity Group, which meets regularly, and indeed met earlier today. The University Secretary attends weekly meetings of the Scottish Government’s higher education ‘COVID Leads’ group, which means that we receive up-to-date intelligence and information on government policy and guidance, and are able to provide feedback and data to influence such policy.</p>\n<p>Rest assured that we will communicate promptly if there are any significant developments or changes to travel or other COVID related guidance.</p>\n<p>Malcolm G Cutt</p>\n<p>Director of Finance and Corporate Strategic Development</p>\n<p> </p>\n<p><strong>For staff:</strong></p>\n<p>Dear colleagues</p>\n<p>You will be aware from media reports of the emergence of the new Omicron COVID variant, and we appreciate that you may have some questions around this.</p>\n<p>This message is to reassure you that we are monitoring the situation closely, and considering the potential impact on the QMU community. We hope that the information set out below provides some initial answers to questions you may have at this time.</p>\n<p><strong>Current </strong><strong>guidance </strong><strong>and </strong><strong>important advice to control the spread of the virus</strong></p>\n<p>Our key message to you is that the Scottish Government has not changed its advice to universities, and, at this stage, has indicated that it does not intend to introduce restrictions that would alter our current and planned teaching activity. Like all universities, we exceed the requirements of the current COVID guidance for higher education in our current operations at QMU. </p>\n<p>Nevertheless, in response to the new variant, the Scottish Government is <a href=\"https://www.gov.scot/collections/first-ministers-speeches/\">asking us all step up and continue to do our part in complying with existing protections</a> (face coverings, ventilation, regular testing etc).</p>\n<p>All members of our community are therefore reminded of the steps they can take to control the spread of the virus.</p>\n<p>In particular, we are all asked to ensure that we take a lateral flow test <em>whenever we are planning to socialise</em> or plan to be in a place where there are a lot of people. This is alongside, and in addition to, the recommendation that we all take a lateral flow test at least twice a week. We encourage you to continue to test for COVID twice weekly, and also before socialising, whether that is going out for drinks or dinner, visiting someone at home or even going shopping somewhere that might be crowded.</p>\n<p>To assist you in this, we are continuing to provide access to lateral flow device (LFD) testing kits at various collections points on campus, including the main reception, the Students’ Union and within student accommodation.  LFD testing kits are also available in Scotland through home delivery, at community testing centres and local pharmacies. Details are available at the <a href=\"https://www.nhsinform.scot/illnesses-and-conditions/infections-and-poisoning/coronavirus-covid-19/test-and-protect/coronavirus-covid-19-get-a-test-if-you-do-not-have-symptoms\">NHS Inform website</a>.</p>\n<p>For a reminder of the steps you can take to protect our campus community and society more generally, please see the <a href=\"/coronavirus/applicants/campus-life/\">campus life and health and safety section of our coronavirus website</a>.   Also, do note that local health boards are now putting arrangements in place to make booster COVID vaccines available from 12 weeks after your second dose. See the <a href=\"https://www.nhsinform.scot/covid-19-vaccine/the-vaccines/coronavirus-covid-19-booster-vaccination/\">NHS Inform website</a> for more information.</p>\n<p><strong>Hybrid working</strong></p>\n<p>We are aware that the First Minister has reminded people to work from home where possible, and has asked employers to make sure they are maximising the potential of home working.  We are, of course, already supporting a good degree of home working, balancing that with the needs of our students and service delivery, both to students and between colleagues.  So, if you are working from home some of the time just now, we would ask you to continue to attend campus as per your agreed hybrid working arrangements.</p>\n<p><strong>Advice on travel</strong></p>\n<p>Students planning to travel abroad around the Christmas period should regularly check the latest advice on travel from the <a href=\"https://www.gov.uk/foreign-travel-advice\">UK Government’s Foreign Office website</a>. The advice is changing frequently, sometimes at short notice. Most countries require proof of vaccination and/or a negative PCR test before entry is permitted.  They should also check the <a href=\"https://www.gov.scot/publications/coronavirus-covid-19-international-travel-quarantine/\">Scottish Government website</a> regularly for guidance and rules on booking and planning travel to Scotland. We have reminded students of this today.</p>\n<p>If students have any concerns about travel, whether they be an international student or a student going out on an exchange,  they should contact our International Office (international@qmu.ac.uk).</p>\n<p>We have also reminded students planning to travel between households over the festive period within the UK to follow the latest ‘Test Before Travel’ advice. This means taking an LFD test three days before travel and on the day of travel. It also means taking an LFD test three days before travel and on the day of travel before returning to their original or term-time household.</p>\n<p><strong>Further updates and advice</strong></p>\n<p>We continue to manage our response to COVID through our Business Continuity Group, which meets regularly, and indeed met earlier today. The University Secretary attends weekly meetings of the Scottish Government’s higher education ‘COVID Leads’ group, which means that we receive up-to-date intelligence and information on government policy and guidance, and are able to provide feedback and data to influence such policy.</p>\n<p>Rest assured that we will communicate promptly if there are any significant developments or changes to travel or other COVID related guidance.</p>\n<p>Malcolm G Cutt</p>\n<p>Director of Finance and Corporate Strategic Development</p>\n<p> </p>"
