      "contentTypeKey": "216ea22b-01af-4645-8972-5766bbd75b6c",
      "udi": "umb://element/defa1d92e6d04f798305a6ab096510c9",
      "title": "26 November 2021",
      "content": "<p>For students and staff:</p>\n<p>This is a brief coronavirus update, but it features some important information on the latest guidance on regular testing, and on testing before travel between semester one and two.</p>\n<h2>Latest advice from government on regular testing, and testing when planning to meet people socially</h2>\n<p>In a <a href=\"https://www.parliament.scot/chamber-and-committees/official-report/what-was-said-in-parliament/meeting-of-parliament-23-11-2021?meeting=13424&amp;iob=121848#orscontributions_M1848E394P731C2358895\">statement</a> to the Scottish Parliament on COVID this week, the First Minister emphasised the importance of us all continuing to test ourselves regularly.  She also asked that we all take a lateral flow (LFD) test on any occasion when we are socialising, whether that is going out for drinks or dinner, visiting someone at home or even going shopping somewhere that might be crowded.</p>\n<p>You can collect LFD test kits on campus from the Main Reception, the Accommodation Reception, and the Students’ Union. Kits are also available free of charge <a href=\"https://www.nhsinform.scot/illnesses-and-conditions/infections-and-poisoning/coronavirus-covid-19/test-and-protect/coronavirus-covid-19-get-a-test-if-you-do-not-have-symptoms\">from pharmacies, community testing centres or online.</a></p>\n<p>The First Minister also announced that people attending venues covered by Scotland's COVID certification scheme are to be given the <a href=\"https://www.gov.scot/news/negative-test-becomes-part-of-certification-scheme/\">option of providing a recent negative lateral flow test for the virus, as an alternative to proof of vaccination</a>.  As you will perhaps know, our Students’ Union has been working very hard to ensure that government knows the difficulties that the vaccine certification scheme has posed for those students who have received a vaccine not recognised by the MHRA (Medicines and Healthcare Products Regulatory Agency) or who have had other issues accessing their vaccine certification. We hope that this amendment to the scheme will make things much easier for students in this situation.</p>\n<h2>‘Test Before Travel’ advice</h2>\n<p>The Scottish Government has asked students planning to travel home at Christmas to follow the latest ‘Test Before Travel’ advice for domestic travel at the end of Semester One and for the return for Semester Two. This means taking an LFD test three days before travel and on the day of travel. It also means taking an LFD test three days before travel and on the day of travel before returning to term-time accommodation.</p>\n<p>The Scottish Government has also just announced a decision for <a href=\"https://www.gov.scot/news/self-isolation-for-all-travellers-returning-from-six-african-countries/\">travellers returning from six African countries</a> to protect public health in Scotland in light of an emerging variant.</p>\n<h2>Thinking ahead to semester two</h2>\n<p>We have updated our statement on our approach to teaching and learning this year very slightly, to reflect the position for semester two.  You can find this updated statement on our <a href=\"/coronavirus/applicants/campus-life/\">coronavirus website</a>.  In short, we do not anticipate significant changes to our approach in semester 1, and the semester 2 timetable has been published.</p>\n<p>Wishing you a good weekend.</p>\n<p>Malcolm G Cutt</p>\n<p>Director of Finance and Corporate Strategic Development</p>"
    },
    {
      "contentTypeKey": "216ea22b-01af-4645-8972-5766bbd75b6c",
      "udi": "umb://element/a42ce20876cf478aa51a395dcdd3d960",
      "title": "14 November 2021",
      "content": "<p>Monday 14 November</p>\n<p>For students:</p>\n<p>Dear students</p>\n<p>This is a short update on matters relating to COVID.</p>\n<p><strong>LFD Collection Points:</strong> The system for collecting LFD kits on campus has changed. You can now collect test kits from the Main Reception, the Accommodation Reception, and the Students’ Union. Because of this, the LFD Collection Point opposite the Main Reception is no longer operational.  We strongly encourage all students and staff to test themselves twice weekly and thank you for your support.</p>\n<p><strong>Thinking ahead to next semester:</strong> Work is well underway on planning our approach to teaching and learning next semester.  We do not anticipate significant changes to our approach in semester 1, and the semester 2 timetable has been published.</p>\n<p><strong>Resolving tech issues:</strong> Thank you to everyone with your patience managing hybrid home/campus working while we have been experiencing problems with voice and chat services on campus, and with access to the Horizon Desktop suspended.  Thank you very much to the IT team for their great work on resolving the problem with voice and chat (see Moderator for the latest information).   Thank you to that team also for their ongoing work to make the Horizon Desktop available again soon.  Please see Moderator for important information on setting yourself up with multi factor authentication, a pre-requisite for access to the Horizon desktop, when it becomes available again.</p>\n<p><strong>Staying home if you are unwell:</strong> If you do feel unwell, please stay at home to avoid spreading viruses and other germs, even if you think you just have a cold. </p>\n<p>Students should report any absence via the online form on the Student Portal. Absences of up to five days can be self-certified and absences of six days or more should be accompanied by relevant evidence. If you are self-isolating, or suspect you have coronavirus, or have been diagnosed with coronavirus, you also need to: (1) tell Security (0131 474 0000 ext 2222) - and Accommodation (0131 474 0000 x 4902) if you live on campus; (2) Contact the School Office - <a href=\"mailto:schooloffice@qmu.ac.uk\"><strong>schooloffice@qmu.ac.uk</strong></a><strong>.</strong></p>\n<p><strong>Face coverings:  As promised, the Business Continuity Group reviewed our approach to face coverings mid-semester.  Taking into account the context nationally, the Group has decided that we should continue with our existing policy on face coverings. </strong>This means that anyone on campus is required to use face coverings when inside the buildings. This includes in classrooms, in the atrium and LRC and other indoor spaces.  The very few exceptions to this policy are set out on our <a href=\"/coronavirus/coronavirus-levels/coronavirus-beyond-level-0-how-the-university-works/\"><strong>Coronavirus beyond level 0: how the University works</strong></a> page, along with a range of other useful information.</p>\n<p>Thank you for your continued support.</p>\n<p>Malcolm Cutt</p>\n<p>Director of Operations and Finance</p>\n<p>For staff:</p>\n<p>Dear colleagues</p>\n<p>This is a short update on matters relating to COVID.</p>\n<p><strong>LFD Collection Points:</strong> The system for collecting LFD kits on campus has changed. You can now collect test kits from the Main Reception, the Accommodation Reception, and the Students’ Union. Because of this, the LFD Collection Point opposite the Main Reception is no longer operational.  We strongly encourage all students and staff to test themselves twice weekly and thank you for your support.</p>\n<p><strong>Thinking ahead to next semester:</strong> Work is well underway on planning our approach to teaching and learning next semester.  We do not anticipate significant changes to our approach in semester 1, and the semester 2 timetable has been published.</p>\n<p><strong>Resolving tech issues:</strong> Thank you to everyone with your patience managing hybrid home/campus working while we have been experiencing problems with voice and chat services on campus, and with access to the Horizon Desktop suspended.  Thank you very much to the IT team for their great work on resolving the problem with voice and chat (see Moderator for the latest information).   Thank you to that team also for their ongoing work to make the Horizon Desktop available again soon.  Please see Moderator for important information on setting yourself up with multi factor authentication, a pre-requisite for access to the Horizon desktop, when it becomes available again.</p>\n<p><strong>Staying home if you are unwell:</strong> Thank you to all staff who have taken up the opportunity to have a flu jab. The service has been very popular. If you do feel unwell, please stay at home to avoid spreading viruses and other germs, even if you think you just have a cold. </p>\n<p>If you are absent for any reason, you should tell your line manager.  If you are self-isolating, or suspect you have coronavirus, or have been diagnosed with coronavirus, please also: (1) tell Security (tel 0131 474 0000 ext 2222); (2) email the Head of Human Resources at <a href=\"mailto:ASmith2@qmu.ac.uk\"><strong>ASmith2@qmu.ac.uk</strong></a>.</p>\n<p><strong>Face coverings:  As promised, the Business Continuity Group reviewed our approach to face coverings mid-semester.  Taking into account the context nationally, the Group has decided that we should continue with our existing policy on face coverings. </strong>This means that anyone on campus is required to use face coverings when inside the buildings. This includes in classrooms, in the atrium and LRC and other indoor spaces.  The very few exceptions to this policy are set out on our <a href=\"/coronavirus/coronavirus-levels/coronavirus-beyond-level-0-how-the-university-works/\"><strong>Coronavirus beyond level 0: how the University works</strong></a> page, along with a range of other useful information.</p>\n<p>Thank you for your continued support.</p>\n<p>Malcolm Cutt</p>\n<p>Director of Operations and Finance</p>\n<p> </p>\n<p> </p>"
    },
    {
      "contentTypeKey": "216ea22b-01af-4645-8972-5766bbd75b6c",
      "udi": "umb://element/8eeeee7542974a508b7e57d1fa5b9c49",
      "title": "29 October 2021",
      "content": "<p>Friday 29 October </p>\n<p>For students:</p>\n<p>Dear students, </p>\n<p>LFD test kit collection </p>\n<p>We're pleased to announce that our LFD Collect service, which makes lateral flow devices (LFDs) available on campus for routine twice weekly testing at home, is being extended until 31 December. LFD test kits are available for collection at the desk opposite the reception desk in the main academic building. Students and staff can find further information on our website.  </p>\n<p>Students and staff are reminded that, should their LFD test show a positive result, they must take a follow-up confirmatory PCR test. Follow-up PCR tests should be taken within two days of a positive LFD result. </p>\n<p>COVID-safe travel to COP26 events in Glasgow </p>\n<p>We realise some students and members of staff may be planning to attend events during the COP26 climate change conference in Glasgow between 31 October and 12 November. Please be aware that COVID-19 safety guidance still applies during this time. Unless exempt, face coverings remain mandatory in indoor public places, including train and bus services, and are also advised for large gatherings in outdoor public areas. Up to date information about rules and measures designed to protect public health and minimise the risk of a COVID-19 outbreak are available on the <a href=\"https://www.gov.scot/publications/coronavirus-covid-19-staying-safe-and-protecting-others/\">Scottish Government website</a>. </p>\n<p>For staff: </p>\n<p>Dear colleagues, </p>\n<p>LFD test kit collection </p>\n<p>We're pleased to announce that our LFD Collect service, which makes lateral flow devices (LFDs) available on campus for routine twice weekly testing at home, is being extended until 31 December. LFD test kits are available for collection at the desk opposite the reception desk in the main academic building. Students and staff can find further information on our website.  </p>\n<p>Students and staff are reminded that, should their LFD test show a positive result, they must take a follow-up confirmatory PCR test. Follow-up PCR tests should be taken within two days of a positive LFD result. </p>\n<p>Avoid coming on to campus if you are feeling unwell </p>\n<p>Staff members who feel unwell or are experiencing cold or flu-like symptoms should stay at home to avoid spreading viruses and other germs, even if they think it is just a cold.   </p>\n<p>If you are absent for any reason, you should tell your line manager. If you are self-isolating, or suspect you have coronavirus, or have been diagnosed with coronavirus, please also: (1) tell Security (tel 0131 474 0000 ext 2222); (2) email the Head of Human Resources at <a href=\"mailto:ASmith2@qmu.ac.uk\">ASmith2@qmu.ac.uk</a>. </p>\n<p>Access to the Horizon remote desktop </p>\n<p>Please note that an update regarding the remote desktop will be issued later today. </p>\n<p>Flu vaccination programme   </p>\n<p>As previously announced by Moderator, we are pleased to be providing a seasonal flu vaccination programme in partnership with our Occupational Health Provider, PAM Group. We have arranged campus clinics to administer these vaccines and would actively encourage all staff to attend. Clinics will take place in room 2108 on the following dates:  </p>\n<p>Friday 5 November  </p>\n<p>Monday 8 November  </p>\n<p>Wednesday 10 November  </p>\n<p>Friday 12 November  </p>\n<p>Staff wishing to book their appointment can do so using our <a href=\"https://outlook.office365.com/owa/calendar/QMUStaffFluVaccination@qmu.onmicrosoft.com/bookings/s/mne22fCXfkuWQYJksRNcvg2\">online form</a>. Any QMU staff member can get a flu vaccination, but those over the age of 65 and under 18 are advised to obtain an alternate vaccine from their GP. </p>\n<p>Further information on the flu vaccine can be found on the NHS Inform <a href=\"https://www.nhsinform.scot/flu-vaccine\">website</a>. Please email the Health and Safety team – <a href=\"mailto:hs-staff@qmu.ac.uk\">hs-staff@qmu.ac.uk</a> – with any questions or problems about booking an appointment. </p>\n<p>COVID-safe travel to COP26 events in Glasgow </p>\n<p>We realise some students and members of staff may be planning to attend events during the COP26 climate change conference in Glasgow between 31 October and 12 November. Please be aware that COVID-19 safety guidance still applies during this time. Unless exempt, face coverings remain mandatory in indoor public places, including train and bus services, and are also advised for large gatherings in outdoor public areas. Up to date information about rules and measures designed to protect public health and minimise the risk of a COVID-19 outbreak are available on the <a href=\"https://www.gov.scot/publications/coronavirus-covid-19-staying-safe-and-protecting-others/\">Scottish Government website</a>. </p>\n<p> </p>\n<p> </p>"
    },
    {
      "contentTypeKey": "216ea22b-01af-4645-8972-5766bbd75b6c",
      "udi": "umb://element/b369268e9fe94ec7a64930bbb25d6261",
      "title": "18 October 2021",
      "content": "<h1>Monday 18 October</h1>\n<p> </p>\n<p>For students:</p>\n<p>Dear students</p>\n<h2>LFD Collection Point opening hours</h2>\n<p>As you will know from other communications, the on-campus LFD Collection point is open from 10am to 4pm every Monday, Wednesday and Friday throughout October. We encourage all students and staff to test themselves for COVID twice a week, whether you obtain test kits on campus or <a href=\"https://www.nhsinform.scot/illnesses-and-conditions/infections-and-poisoning/coronavirus-covid-19/test-and-protect/coronavirus-covid-19-get-a-test-if-you-do-not-have-symptoms\">from pharmacies, community testing centres or online.</a></p>\n<h2>Avoiding coming on campus if you are unwell</h2>\n<p>If you do feel unwell, please stay at home to avoid spreading viruses and other germs, even if you think you just have a cold. </p>\n<p>Students should report any absence via the online form on the Student Portal. Absences of up to five days can be self-certified and absences of six days or more should be accompanied by relevant evidence. If you are self-isolating, or suspect you have coronavirus, or have been diagnosed with coronavirus, you also need to: (1) tell Security (0131 474 0000 ext 2222) - and Accommodation (0131 474 0000 x 4902) if you live on campus; (2) Contact the School Office - <a href=\"mailto:schooloffice@qmu.ac.uk\"><strong>schooloffice@qmu.ac.uk</strong></a><strong>.</strong></p>\n<h2>Further information sources</h2>\n<p>Thank you again for your support in taking <a href=\"/coronavirus/applicants/campus-life/\">steps to keep our community safe from COVID</a>.  Do remember that our <a href=\"/coronavirus/\">coronavirus website</a> provides a great deal of information about COVID and QMU, including <a href=\"/coronavirus/faqs/\">FAQs</a>. Within that site, you will find our <a href=\"/coronavirus/coronavirus-levels/coronavirus-beyond-level-0-how-the-university-works/\">Coronavirus beyond level 0: how the University works</a> page, which summarises all the most relevant information, including, for example, our full policy on face coverings.</p>\n<p>Malcolm G Cutt, Director of Operations and Finance</p>\n<p> </p>\n<h1>For staff:</h1>\n<p>Dear colleagues</p>\n<h2>LFD Collection Point opening hours</h2>\n<p>As you will know from other communications, the on-campus LFD Collection point is open from 10am to 4pm every Monday, Wednesday and Friday throughout October. We encourage all students and staff to test themselves for COVID twice a week, whether you obtain test kits on campus or <a href=\"https://www.nhsinform.scot/illnesses-and-conditions/infections-and-poisoning/coronavirus-covid-19/test-and-protect/coronavirus-covid-19-get-a-test-if-you-do-not-have-symptoms\">from pharmacies, community testing centres or online.</a></p>\n<p>It has been encouraging to see so many colleagues being around more frequently on campus. This is so helpful in enabling us to re-build relationships, support one another, and share ideas. Thank you.  </p>\n<h2>Avoiding coming on campus if you are unwell</h2>\n<p>If you do feel unwell, please stay at home to avoid spreading viruses and other germs, even if you think you just have a cold. </p>\n<p>If you are absent for any reason, you should tell your line manager.  If you are self-isolating, or suspect you have coronavirus, or have been diagnosed with coronavirus, please also: (1) tell Security (tel 0131 474 0000 ext 2222); (2) email the Head of Human Resources at <a href=\"mailto:ASmith2@qmu.ac.uk\">ASmith2@qmu.ac.uk</a>;</p>\n<h2>Flu vaccinations for staff</h2>\n<p>This year, we are offering a free flu vaccination to all staff<em>. </em>HR/Health and Safety will issue information on this as soon very soon.</p>\n<h2>Further information sources</h2>\n<p>Thank you again for your support in taking <a href=\"/coronavirus/applicants/campus-life/\">steps to keep our community safe from COVID</a>.  Do remember that our <a href=\"/coronavirus/\">coronavirus website</a> provides a great deal of information about COVID and QMU, including <a href=\"/coronavirus/faqs/\">FAQs</a>. Within that site, you will find our <a href=\"/coronavirus/coronavirus-levels/coronavirus-beyond-level-0-how-the-university-works/\">Coronavirus beyond level 0: how the University works</a> page, which summarises all the most relevant information, including, for example, our full policy on face coverings.</p>\n<p> </p>\n<p>Malcolm G Cutt, Director of Operations and Finance</p>"
    },
    {
      "contentTypeKey": "216ea22b-01af-4645-8972-5766bbd75b6c",
      "udi": "umb://element/2e4b171f5731478a83cd84d8440ec315",
      "title": "5 October 2021",
      "content": "<p>Thank you everyone for following the<a href=\"/{localLink:umb://document/e3a1cc188042429781c78bab7ff95416}\" title=\"Campus Life\"> ten steps to help keep us all safe on campus</a>, particularly the requirement that we wear face coverings when inside campus buildings. This includes in classrooms, in the atrium and LRC, and in other indoor spaces. It is clear too how everyone is supporting one another as we adjust or re-adjust to campus life, which is great to see. </p>\n<h2>Extension of LFD Collect until the end of October</h2>\n<p>The LFD Collect service has been extended into October and so the collection point on campus will staffed again very soon.  Opening times will be confirmed as soon as possible.</p>\n<h2>Update on the ‘vaccine passport’ scheme</h2>\n<p>Though the Scottish Government’s “vaccine passport” scheme came into effect on Friday 1 October, legal enforcement will not come into effect until Monday 18 October. Students who have been vaccinated or part vaccinated outside Scotland might like to note that the university sector continues its engagement with the Scottish Government about provision of “vaccine passports” for people in such a situation. In addition, our SU, along with the other student associations, continues to seek government reassurances that vaccine passports will not introduce inequalities in access to student union venues across Scotland. (And I can confirm again that no planned on-campus QMU events or venues will require vaccine passports.)</p>\n<h2>Future coronavirus updates</h2>\n<p>Now that we have settled into the new semester, and conscious of the volume of emails that so many of you will be receiving just now, I will not issue another COVID update until there is news that we need to share. In the meantime, do remember that our <a href=\"/{localLink:umb://document/b673e3c08a21451691ec92f364641f89}\" title=\"Coronavirus\">coronavirus website</a> provides a great deal of information about COVID and QMU, including <a href=\"/{localLink:umb://document/2903c860f28b4ce5a34a763573cd0783}\" title=\"FAQs\">FAQs</a>. Within that site, you will find our <a href=\"/{localLink:umb://document/2e57b5cdfac54b14916a32cb577ab931}\" title=\"Coronavirus level 0: how the University works\">Coronavirus beyond level 0: how the University works</a> page, which summarises all the most relevant information, including, for example, our full policy on face coverings.</p>\n<p> </p>\n<p> </p>\n<p> </p>\n<p> </p>\n<p> </p>"
    },
    {
      "contentTypeKey": "216ea22b-01af-4645-8972-5766bbd75b6c",
      "udi": "umb://element/061047fba4d14c41b22334bc0fe4a4a5",
      "title": "27 September 2021",
      "content": "<p>For students and staff:</p>\n<p>A fairly short update this week:</p>\n<p><strong>Vaccination</strong>: The on-campus vaccination clinic is now closed, but there are still drop-in clinics across Edinburgh and the Lothians, and the rest of Scotland.   You can find details of drop-in clinics in this area on the <a href=\"https://www.nhslothian.scot/Coronavirus/Vaccine/Pages/Drop-in-Clinics.aspx\"><strong>NHS Lothian website</strong></a>. You can find information on clinics across all of Scotland on the <a href=\"https://www.nhsinform.scot/vaccinedropinclinics\"><strong>NHS Inform website</strong></a>. </p>\n<p><strong>LFD Collect</strong>: the collection point is open this week on Monday, Wednesday and Friday from 9.00am - 4pm.  In addition, you can <a href=\"https://www.nhsinform.scot/illnesses-and-conditions/infections-and-poisoning/coronavirus-covid-19/test-and-protect/coronavirus-covid-19-get-a-test-if-you-do-not-have-symptoms\"><strong>obtain free LFD testing kits for regular testing at home through pharmacies, community testing sites and online</strong></a>.  </p>\n<p><strong>Ten steps to keep all safe on campus</strong>: thank you to everyone for following the <strong><a href=\"/{localLink:umb://document/e3a1cc188042429781c78bab7ff95416}\" title=\"Campus Life\">ten steps</a></strong><strong>,</strong> particularly the requirement that we wear face coverings when inside campus buildings. This includes in classrooms, in the atrium and LRC and other indoor spaces. </p>\n<p><strong>Vaccine passports:</strong> students who have been vaccinated or part vaccinated outside Scotland might like to note that the university sector continues its engagement with the Scottish Government about provision of “vaccine passports” for people in such a situation.   In addition, our SU is, along with the other student associations, seeking government reassurances that vaccine passports will not introduce inequalities in access to student union venues across Scotland.  (The “vaccine passport” scheme is due to be implemented on 1 October. As I said in the last COVID update, no planned on-campus QMU events or venues will require vaccine passports.)</p>\n<p><strong>Scottish Government research on student attitudes to the COVID vaccination and vaccination marketing activity:</strong>  the Scottish Government is inviting students to participate in an <a href=\"https://response.questback.com/isa/qbv.dll/bylink?p=8VZbmGWK5eUsszXq_u5lqf5Rpv_fqBoAVxMKO8gKk8DHkuDg2QekeKO1oRpj-cE7fATDRs-4IpucKxYt1GsDuw2\" data-anchor=\"?p=8VZbmGWK5eUsszXq_u5lqf5Rpv_fqBoAVxMKO8gKk8DHkuDg2QekeKO1oRpj-cE7fATDRs-4IpucKxYt1GsDuw2\">online survey</a> about the COVID-19 vaccine.  They are conducting research to understand attitudes towards the COVID-19 vaccine and marketing activity about this. All answers will be completely anonymous. It should take less than 5 minutes to complete. </p>\n<p>Thank you for continued support. Do remember that our <strong><a href=\"/{localLink:umb://document/b673e3c08a21451691ec92f364641f89}\" title=\"Coronavirus\">coronavirus website</a></strong> provides a great deal of information about COVID and QMU, including FAQs.  Within that site, you will find our <strong><a href=\"/{localLink:umb://document/2e57b5cdfac54b14916a32cb577ab931}\" title=\"Coronavirus level 0: how the University works\">Coronavirus beyond level 0: how the University works</a></strong> page, which summarises all the most relevant information, including, for example, our full policy on face coverings.</p>\n<p> </p>\n<p>Malcolm G Cutt</p>\n<p>Director of Operations and Finance</p>\n<p> </p>"
    },
    {
      "contentTypeKey": "216ea22b-01af-4645-8972-5766bbd75b6c",
      "udi": "umb://element/08ed75cf06634a52bef61304a98cf001",
      "title": "20 September 2021",
      "content": "<p>Dear students,</p>\n<p>Welcome to the new semester. </p>\n<p>This COVID update reminds you of ten steps you can take to help keep us all safe on campus. New information appears in italics.</p>\n<p>Please do note in particular point 10, which sets out who you need to tell in the University if you have COVID or COVID symptoms. <strong>This is relevant to all students (not just those living on campus), and all staff. </strong></p>\n<p>The ten steps below are more important than ever at a time when the Scottish Government has just launched a ‘Let’s Stop the Spike’ campaign encouraging us to adopt many of the behaviours set out in the ten steps below.  </p>\n<ol>\n<li data-leveltext=\"%1.\" data-font=\"Arial\" data-listid=\"1\" aria-setsize=\"-1\" data-aria-posinset=\"1\" data-aria-level=\"1\"><strong>Please wear a face covering:</strong> in line with Scottish Government guidance, everyone on campus is required to use a face covering when inside the buildings. This includes in classrooms, in the atrium and LRC and in other indoor spaces.  For exemptions, see the more detailed statement on our <a href=\"/coronavirus/coronavirus-levels/coronavirus-beyond-level-0-how-the-university-works/\">website</a>. </li>\n<li data-leveltext=\"%1.\" data-font=\"Arial\" data-listid=\"1\" aria-setsize=\"-1\" data-aria-posinset=\"1\" data-aria-level=\"1\"><strong>Vaccination:</strong> this week, there is a drop-in vaccination clinic on campus for students and staff, and we strongly encourage you to use that service if you are not yet vaccinated or double vaccinated (you can have your second vaccine eight weeks after your first). After this week, you would need to use other local drop-in vaccination clinics off campus. <a href=\"/coronavirus/test/\">More information is available on our drop-in vaccination clinic and vaccination generally</a>.  <em>Although vaccine passports are expected to be required in Scotland for some events and higher risk venues from 1st</em><em> October, rest assured that no planned on-campus QMU events or venues will require vaccine passports. Students who have been vaccinated or part vaccinated outside Scotland might like to note that the university sector has asked the Scottish Government about provision of “vaccine passports” for people in such a situation. </em>   </li>\n<li data-leveltext=\"%1.\" data-font=\"Arial\" data-listid=\"1\" aria-setsize=\"-1\" data-aria-posinset=\"1\" data-aria-level=\"1\"><strong>Participate in twice weekly LFD testing:</strong> everyone who does not have symptoms should <a href=\"https://www.gov.scot/publications/coronavirus-covid-19-getting-tested/pages/no-covid-symptoms/\">take regular LFD tests</a>. LFD test kits are available for collection on campus during the first few weeks of the semester, from participating chemists and from COVID test centres. <em>For the next two weeks, the collection point on campus will be open on Monday, Wednesday and Friday, from 9.30am until 4.00pm.</em>  <a href=\"/coronavirus/test/\">More information on regular testing facilities.</a> </li>\n<li data-leveltext=\"%1.\" data-font=\"Arial\" data-listid=\"1\" aria-setsize=\"-1\" data-aria-posinset=\"1\" data-aria-level=\"1\"><strong>Keep your distance and keep left</strong> when moving around the campus: please don’t congregate in tight spaces, follow the signage, and try to avoid crowded spaces generally.   </li>\n<li data-leveltext=\"%1.\" data-font=\"Arial\" data-listid=\"1\" aria-setsize=\"-1\" data-aria-posinset=\"1\" data-aria-level=\"1\"><strong>Keep your hands clean</strong> by washing them regularly and thoroughly throughout the day and using the hand gel at sanitiser stations on campus. </li>\n<li data-leveltext=\"%1.\" data-font=\"Arial\" data-listid=\"1\" aria-setsize=\"-1\" data-aria-posinset=\"1\" data-aria-level=\"1\"><strong>Go cashless:</strong><strong> </strong>where possible, please use contactless to pay for food and drink with the Round app, your QMU smartcard or another form of contactless payment.</li>\n<li data-leveltext=\"%1.\" data-font=\"Arial\" data-listid=\"1\" aria-setsize=\"-1\" data-aria-posinset=\"1\" data-aria-level=\"1\"><strong>Take advantage of fresh air</strong><strong>:</strong> try to keep windows open, and where you can, socialise outside.  We have appropriate mechanical ventilation that provides 100% fresh air in areas where opening windows is not an option.  In-room signage will provide you with guidance on ventilation in each space.</li>\n<li data-leveltext=\"%1.\" data-font=\"Arial\" data-listid=\"1\" aria-setsize=\"-1\" data-aria-posinset=\"1\" data-aria-level=\"1\">Watch our <a href=\"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=jsB6AmckyZI\">Keeping Safe on Campus video</a>.  <em>We also encourage you to complete the </em> <a href=\"https://rise.articulate.com/share/-8JQhsegFdUYU-k_aMzDvUa1JujFX7X0%22%20/l%20%22/\">Scottish Government’s online short course on COVID safety on campus.</a> </li>\n<li data-leveltext=\"%1.\" data-font=\"Arial\" data-listid=\"1\" aria-setsize=\"-1\" data-aria-posinset=\"1\" data-aria-level=\"1\"><strong>Download the </strong><a href=\"https://protect.scot/\">Protect Scotland app</a> <strong>and self-isolate immediately if you are asked to do so. </strong>See the <a href=\"https://www.nhsinform.scot/self-help-guides/self-help-guide-when-and-how-long-to-self-isolate-due-to-coronavirus\">NHS Inform website</a> for a clear guide on when you need to self isolate.  </li>\n<li data-leveltext=\"%1.\" data-font=\"Arial\" data-listid=\"1\" aria-setsize=\"-1\" data-aria-posinset=\"1\" data-aria-level=\"1\"><strong>Tell us if you are self-isolating or suspect you have coronavirus or have been diagnosed with coronavirus</strong><strong>.</strong> Isolate, Test and Tell following the guidance in our FAQs for<a href=\"/coronavirus/faqs/staff/\"> staff</a> and for <a href=\"/coronavirus/faqs/students/\">students</a>. For students, this means (1) telling Security (0131 474 0000 ext 2222) - and also Accommodation (0131 474 0000 x 4902) if you live on campus; (2) Contacting the School Office - <a href=\"mailto:schooloffice@qmu.ac.uk\">schooloffice@qmu.ac.uk</a>. If you are participating in the LFD Collect scheme, please note that you still have to tell us if you test positive as we don’t get this information from Test and Protect. </li>\n</ol>\n<p>See our <a href=\"/{localLink:umb://document/b673e3c08a21451691ec92f364641f89}\" title=\"Coronavirus\">Coronavirus beyond level 0: how the University works</a> webpage for more detailed guidance and links to further sources of information, including our <a href=\"/{localLink:umb://document/2903c860f28b4ce5a34a763573cd0783}\" title=\"FAQs\">coronavirus FAQS</a>,    </p>\n<p>If you have any COVID-related questions that are not addressed on our website, do remember you can email our dedicated COVID email address for advice,. (<a href=\"mailto:CovidHelp@qmu.ac.uk\">CovidHelp@qmu.ac.uk</a>). </p>\n<p>Wishing you all the best for the new semester. </p>\n<p> </p>\n<p>Malcolm G Cutt </p>\n<p>Director of Operations and Finance </p>\n<p> </p>\n<p> </p>\n<p>Dear colleagues, </p>\n<p>Welcome to the official start of semester. </p>\n<p>This COVID update reminds you of ten steps you can take to help keep us all safe on campus. New information appears in italics.</p>\n<p>Please do note in particular point 10, which sets out who you need to tell in the University if you have COVID or COVID symptoms. <strong>This is relevant to all staff, and all students (not just those living on campus). </strong></p>\n<p>The ten steps below are more important than ever at a time when the Scottish Government has just launched a ‘Let’s Stop the Spike’ campaign encouraging us to adopt many of the behaviours set out in the ten steps below.</p>\n<ol>\n<li data-leveltext=\"%1\" data-font=\"Arial\" data-listid=\"2\" aria-setsize=\"-1\" data-aria-posinset=\"1\" data-aria-level=\"1\"><strong>Please wear a face covering:</strong> in line with Scottish Government guidance, everyone on campus is required to use a face covering when inside the buildings. This includes in classrooms, in the atrium and LRC and in other indoor spaces.  For exemptions, see the more detailed statement on our <a href=\"/coronavirus/coronavirus-levels/coronavirus-beyond-level-0-how-the-university-works/\">website</a>.</li>\n<li data-leveltext=\"%1\" data-font=\"Arial\" data-listid=\"2\" aria-setsize=\"-1\" data-aria-posinset=\"1\" data-aria-level=\"1\"><strong>Vaccination:</strong> this week, there is a drop-in vaccination clinic on campus for students and staff, and we strongly encourage you to use that service if you are not yet vaccinated or double vaccinated (you can have your second vaccine eight weeks after your first). After this week, you would need to use other local drop-in vaccination clinics off campus. <a href=\"/coronavirus/test/\">More information is available on our drop-in vaccination clinic and vaccination generally</a>.  <em>Although vaccine passports are expected to be required in Scotland for some events and higher risk venues from 1st October, rest assured that no planned on-campus QMU events or venues will require vaccine passports. Staff or students who have been vaccinated or part vaccinated outside Scotland might like to note that the university sector has asked the Scottish Government about provision of “vaccine passports” for people in such a situation.    </em></li>\n<li data-leveltext=\"%1\" data-font=\"Arial\" data-listid=\"2\" aria-setsize=\"-1\" data-aria-posinset=\"1\" data-aria-level=\"1\"><strong>Participate in twice weekly LFD testing:</strong> everyone who does not have symptoms should <a href=\"https://www.gov.scot/publications/coronavirus-covid-19-getting-tested/pages/no-covid-symptoms/\">take regular LFD tests</a>. LFD test kits are available for collection on campus during the first few weeks of the semester, from participating chemists and from COVID test centres. <em>For the next two weeks, the collection point on campus will be open on Monday, Wednesday and Friday, from 9.30am until 4.00pm.</em>  <a href=\"/coronavirus/test/\">More information on regular testing facilities.</a> </li>\n<li data-leveltext=\"%1\" data-font=\"Arial\" data-listid=\"2\" aria-setsize=\"-1\" data-aria-posinset=\"1\" data-aria-level=\"1\"><strong>Keep your distance and keep left</strong> when moving around the campus: please don’t congregate in tight spaces, follow the signage, and try to avoid crowded spaces generally.   <em>We have issued staff with guidance on how to manage close contact and keep an appropriate distance in office spaces and classrooms</em> (see <a href=\"/coronavirus/faqs/staff/\">coronavirus FAQs</a>).</li>\n<li data-leveltext=\"%1\" data-font=\"Arial\" data-listid=\"2\" aria-setsize=\"-1\" data-aria-posinset=\"1\" data-aria-level=\"1\"><strong>Keep your hands clean</strong> by washing them regularly and thoroughly throughout the day and using the hand gel at sanitiser stations on campus. </li>\n<li data-leveltext=\"%1\" data-font=\"Arial\" data-listid=\"2\" aria-setsize=\"-1\" data-aria-posinset=\"1\" data-aria-level=\"1\"><strong>Go cashless:</strong><strong> </strong>where possible, please use contactless to pay for food and drink with the Round app, your QMU smartcard or another form of contactless payment.</li>\n<li data-leveltext=\"%1\" data-font=\"Arial\" data-listid=\"2\" aria-setsize=\"-1\" data-aria-posinset=\"1\" data-aria-level=\"1\"><strong>Take advantage of fresh air</strong><strong>:</strong> try to keep windows open, and where you can, socialise outside.  We have appropriate mechanical ventilation that provides 100% fresh air in areas where opening windows is not an option.  In-room signage will provide you with guidance on ventilation in each space.</li>\n<li data-leveltext=\"%1\" data-font=\"Arial\" data-listid=\"2\" aria-setsize=\"-1\" data-aria-posinset=\"1\" data-aria-level=\"1\"><em>Please complete the updated </em><a href=\"https://myshare.qmu.ac.uk/services/campus-commercial-services/covid19/SitePages/Campus%20Induction.aspx\">“Keeping Safe on Campus” e-learning module</a> <em>if you haven’t done so already (remembering to sign the online form at the end of the module), and familiarise yourself with the </em><a href=\"https://myshare.qmu.ac.uk/services/campus-commercial-services/covid19/SitePages/Campus%20Induction.aspx\">Staff Return to Campus Guide</a><em>, and refreshed</em> <a href=\"https://myshare.qmu.ac.uk/services/campus-commercial-services/covid19/SitePages/Campus%20Induction.aspx\">Health and Wellbeing Staff Guide</a>,<em> recently issued by the HR team. Research and technical staff might want to check out the </em><em>Scottish</em> <em>Government's</em> <a href=\"https://www.gov.scot/publications/coronavirus-covid-19-general-guidance-for-safer-workplaces/documents/\">updated COVID checklist for labs and research facilities</a>,<em> which has just been published.</em></li>\n<li data-leveltext=\"%1\" data-font=\"Arial\" data-listid=\"2\" aria-setsize=\"-1\" data-aria-posinset=\"1\" data-aria-level=\"1\"><strong>Download the</strong> <a href=\"https://protect.scot/\">Protect Scotland app</a> <strong>and self-isolate immediately if you are asked to do so.</strong> See the <a href=\"https://www.nhsinform.scot/self-help-guides/self-help-guide-when-and-how-long-to-self-isolate-due-to-coronavirus\">NHS Inform website</a> for a clear guide on when you need to self isolate.  </li>\n<li data-leveltext=\"%1\" data-font=\"Arial\" data-listid=\"2\" aria-setsize=\"-1\" data-aria-posinset=\"1\" data-aria-level=\"1\"><strong>Tell us if you are self-isolating or suspect you have coronavirus or have been diagnosed with coronavirus</strong><strong>.</strong> Isolate, Test and Tell following the guidance in our FAQs for<a href=\"/coronavirus/faqs/staff/\"> staff</a> and for <a href=\"/coronavirus/faqs/students/\">students</a>. For staff, this means (1) telling Security (tel 0131 474 0000 ext 2222); (2) emailing the Head of Human Resources at <a href=\"mailto:ASmith2@qmu.ac.uk\">ASmith2@qmu.ac.uk</a>; (3) advising your line manager. <em>(The corresponding procedure for students means (1) telling Security (0131 474 0000 ext 2222) - and also Accommodation (0131 474 0000 x 4902) if they live on campus; (2) Contacting the School Office - <a href=\"mailto:schooloffice@qmu.ac.uk\">schooloffice@qmu.ac.uk</a>).</em> If you are participating in the LFD Collect scheme, please note that you still have to tell us if you test positive as we don’t get this information from Test and Protect. </li>\n</ol>\n<p>See our <a href=\"/{localLink:umb://document/2e57b5cdfac54b14916a32cb577ab931}\" title=\"Coronavirus level 0: how the University works\">Coronavirus beyond level 0: how the University works</a> webpage for more detailed guidance and links to further sources of information, including our <a href=\"/{localLink:umb://document/714af0d103b241688645c034d14baa75}\" title=\"Coronavirus levels\">route map</a> to normal operations, <a href=\"https://myshare.qmu.ac.uk/services/campus-commercial-services/covid19/SitePages/Risk%20Assessments.aspx\">risk assessment</a> and <a href=\"/coronavirus/faqs/\">coronavirus FAQS</a>,   If you would like to know more about the University’s plans for dealing with any COVID outbreak, you can also find our COVID incident management plan on our <a href=\"/{localLink:umb://document/f1cfc0dcfb5f4dbb8b2875046b046cb1}\" title=\"COVID-19 Incident Management Plan\">website</a>.  </p>\n<p>Wishing you all the best for the new semester. </p>\n<p> </p>\n<p>Malcolm G Cutt </p>\n<p>Director of Operations and Finance </p>"
    },
