      "contentTypeKey": "216ea22b-01af-4645-8972-5766bbd75b6c",
      "udi": "umb://element/f4249fb1f0e64979be7ef67bd8f8a7a4",
      "title": "10 September 2021",
      "content": "<p>Covid Update: 10 September 2021</p>\n<p> </p>\n<p>Dear students,</p>\n<p>COVID-19 (coronavirus) update: 10 September 2021 - steps you can take to help us all keep safe on campus</p>\n<p>With induction week beginning on Monday, in today’s COVID update I am focusing on the key steps you can take to help keep us all safe on campus.</p>\n<ol>\n<li><strong>Please wear a face covering:</strong> we are updating our policy on face coverings with immediate effect, based on the latest advice from the Scottish Government.  In line with Scottish Government guidance, everyone on campus will be required to use face coverings when inside the buildings. This includes in classrooms, in the atrium and LRC and in other indoor spaces.  For exemptions, see the more detailed statement at the foot of this message.</li>\n<li><strong>Vaccination:</strong> from Monday, there will be a drop-in vaccination clinic on campus for students and staff, open for two weeks, and we encourage you strongly to use that service if you are not yet vaccinated or double vaccinated (you can have your second vaccine eight weeks after your first). After that two week period, you would need to use other local drop-in vaccination clinics off campus. <a href=\"/coronavirus/test/\">More information on our drop in vaccination clinic and vaccination generally</a>.</li>\n<li><strong>Participate in twice weekly LFD testing</strong> (and test before travelling to term-time accommodation). Everyone who does not have symptoms should <a href=\"https://www.gov.scot/publications/coronavirus-covid-19-getting-tested/pages/no-covid-symptoms/\">take regular LFD tests</a>. LFD tests kits are available for collection on campus during the first few weeks of the semester, from participating chemists and from COVID test centres. In its first week of operation (beginning 13 September) the collection point on campus will be open on Monday, Tuesday, Wednesday and Friday, from 11.00 am and 4.00 pm.  <a href=\"/coronavirus/test/\">More information on regular testing facilities.</a></li>\n<li><strong>Keep your distance and keep left</strong> when moving around the campus: please don’t congregate in tight spaces, and try to avoid crowded spaces generally.</li>\n<li><strong>Keep your hands clean</strong> by washing them regularly throughout the day and using the hand gel at sanitiser stations on campus.</li>\n<li><strong>Go cashless:</strong> where possible, please use contactless to pay for food and drink with the Round app, your QMU smartcard or another form of contactless payment.</li>\n<li><strong>Take advantage of fresh air:</strong> try to keep windows open, and where you can, socialise outside.  And rest assured that we have appropriate mechanical ventilation where opening windows is not an option.  In-room signage will provide you with guidance on ventilation in each space.</li>\n<li>Watch our <a href=\"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=jsB6AmckyZI\">Keeping Safe on Campus video</a>.</li>\n<li>Download the <a href=\"https://protect.scot/\">Protect Scotland app</a> and self-isolate immediately if you are asked to do so. See the <a href=\"https://www.nhsinform.scot/self-help-guides/self-help-guide-when-and-how-long-to-self-isolate-due-to-coronavirus\">NHS Inform website</a> for a clear guide on when you need to self isolate.</li>\n<li>Feeling unwell? <strong>If you have symptoms of coronavirus Isolate, Test and Tell</strong> following the guidance in our FAQs for<a href=\"/coronavirus/faqs/staff/\"> staff</a> and for <a href=\"/coronavirus/faqs/students/\">students</a>. For students, this means (1) telling Security (0131 474 0000 ext 2222) - and also Accommodation (0131 474 0000 x 4902) if you live on campus; (2) Contacting the School Office - <a href=\"mailto:schooloffice@qmu.ac.uk\">schooloffice@qmu.ac.uk</a>. If you are participating in the LFD Collect scheme, please note that you still have to tell us if you test positive as we don’t get this information from Track and Trace.</li>\n</ol>\n<p>See our <a href=\"/coronavirus/coronavirus-levels/coronavirus-beyond-level-0-how-the-university-works/\">Coronavirus beyond level 0: how the University works</a> webpage for more detailed guidance and links to further sources of information</p>\n<p>Wishing you all the very best for the new semester.</p>\n<p>Professor Richard Butt</p>\n<p>Deputy Principal</p>\n<p> </p>\n<p>Updated Policy on Face Coverings</p>\n<p>We are updating our policy on face coverings with immediate effect, based on the latest advice from the Scottish Government.  </p>\n<p>In line with Scottish Government guidance, anyone on campus will be required to use face coverings when inside the buildings. This includes in classrooms, in the atrium and LRC and other indoor spaces. </p>\n<p>Exceptions are as follows:</p>\n<p>- Residents within their flats in student accommodation.</p>\n<p>- When seated in the open plan staff offices, where a minimum distance of 1m is maintained.</p>\n<p>- Staff who are delivering a class, where a minimum distance of 1m from their students is maintained.  </p>\n<p>- Staff in meetings where they are keeping at least 1m apart from others in the room.</p>\n<p>- When eating or drinking.</p>\n<p>- Where you have a legal exemption. The government have outlined a number of <a href=\"https://www.gov.scot/publications/coronavirus-covid-19-public-use-of-face-coverings/\">'reasonable' reasons for not wearing a face covering</a>.  If you need advice on exemptions (eg if you think you cannot deliver a particular specialist class with students wearing face coverings) please email Health and Safety (<a href=\"mailto:hs-staff@qmu.ac.uk\">hs-staff@qmu.ac.uk</a>).</p>\n<p>The requirement to wear a face coverings on campus will be reviewed mid-semester and will take account of government guidance prevailing at that time.</p>\n<p><img src=\"?width=500&amp;height=241.7893544733862\" alt=\"Advice from QMU regarding Covid 19\" width=\"500\" height=\"241.7893544733862\" data-udi=\"umb://media/8985ebcba2fa4240beb09f632cd6b268\" /></p>\n<p>Dear colleagues,</p>\n<p>COVID-19 (coronavirus update): steps you can take to help us all keep safe on campus</p>\n<p>With induction week beginning on Monday, in today’s COVID update I am focusing on the key steps you can take to help keep us all safe on campus.</p>\n<ol>\n<li><strong>Please wear a face covering:</strong> we are updating our policy on face coverings with immediate effect, based on the latest advice from the Scottish Government.  In line with Scottish Government guidance, everyone on campus will be required to use face coverings when inside the buildings. This includes in classrooms, in the atrium and LRC and in other indoor spaces.  For exemptions, see the more detailed statement at the foot of this message.</li>\n<li><strong>Vaccination:</strong> from Monday, there will be a drop-in vaccination clinic on campus for students and staff, open for two weeks, and we encourage you strongly to use that service if you are not yet vaccinated or double vaccinated (you can have your second vaccine eight weeks after your first). After that two week period, you would need to use other local drop-in vaccination clinics off campus. <a href=\"/coronavirus/test/\">More information on our drop in vaccination clinic and vaccination generally</a>.</li>\n<li><strong>Participate in twice weekly LFD testing:</strong> everyone who does not have symptoms should <a href=\"https://www.gov.scot/publications/coronavirus-covid-19-getting-tested/pages/no-covid-symptoms/\">take regular LFD tests</a>, LFD tests kits are available for collection on campus during the first few weeks of the semester, from participating chemists and from COVID test centres. In its first week of operation (beginning 13 September) the collection point on campus will be open on Monday, Tuesday, Wednesday and Friday, from 11.00 am and 4.00 pm.  <a href=\"/coronavirus/test/\">More information on regular testing facilities.</a></li>\n<li><strong>Keep your distance and keep left</strong> when moving around the campus: please don’t congregate in tight spaces, and try to avoid crowded spaces generally. Very soon, we will be issuing staff with guidance on how to manage close contact and keep an appropriate distance in office spaces and classrooms. In the meantime, we can confirm that it is fine to sit at an office desk even if someone is sitting directly beside you, as there is sufficient space between each desk chair.</li>\n<li><strong>Keep your hands clean</strong> by washing them regularly throughout the day and using the hand gel at sanitiser stations on campus.</li>\n<li><strong>Go cashless:</strong> where possible, please use contactless to pay for food and drink with the Round app, your QMU smartcard or another form of contactless payment.</li>\n<li><strong>Take advantage of fresh air:</strong> try to keep windows open, and where you can, socialise outside.  And rest assured that we have appropriate mechanical ventilation where opening windows is not an option.  In-room signage will provide you with guidance on ventilation in each space.</li>\n<li><strong>Complete the updated  “Working Safely on Campus” e-learning module.</strong> You should gain access to this updated module today. While you do not have to complete the module before you return to work on campus, we ask you to complete it as soon as you can.  Alongside this, the HR team will soon provide updated wellbeing guidance and updated open plan working etiquette.</li>\n<li>Download the <a href=\"https://protect.scot/\">Protect Scotland app</a> and self-isolate immediately if you are asked to do so. One question at Chat with the SLT was whether you need to avoid coming to work on campus if someone in your household has tested positive for COVID. We are following NHS/Scottish Government rules on self isolation, found on the <a href=\"https://www.nhsinform.scot/self-help-guides/self-help-guide-when-and-how-long-to-self-isolate-due-to-coronavirus\">NHS Inform website</a>.  Whatever your situation, you can check whether you need to self isolate on the NHS Inform website. If you don’t need to self isolate according to NHS Inform, you can come to work  As things stand, the rules state you don’t need to self isolate if a member of your household tests positive, provided (1) you have been double vaccinated for 14 days, and (2) you don’t have symptoms and (3) you have received a negative PCR test. But as the rules are complex and subject to change, we will continue to direct you to the NHS Inform website for advice on whether or not to self isolate in any given situation. In short, if NHS Inform advises you that don’t need to self isolate, you can come to work.</li>\n<li><strong>If you have symptoms of coronavirus Isolate, Test and Tell following</strong> the guidance in our FAQs for<a href=\"/coronavirus/faqs/staff/\"> staff</a> and for <a href=\"/coronavirus/faqs/students/\">students</a>. For staff, this means (1) telling Security (tel 0131 474 0000 ext 2222); (2) emailing the Head of Human Resources at <a href=\"mailto:ASmith2@qmu.ac.uk\">ASmith2@qmu.ac.uk</a>; (3) advising your line manager. If you are participating  in the LFD Collect scheme, please note that you still have to tell us if you test positive as we don’t get this information from Track and Trace,</li>\n</ol>\n<p>See our <a href=\"/coronavirus/coronavirus-levels/coronavirus-beyond-level-0-how-the-university-works/\">Coronavirus beyond level 0: how the University works</a> webpage for more detailed guidance and links to further sources of information</p>\n<p>One question raised at the recent Chat with the SLT session was about our contingency plans for large groups of students or staff needing to self isolate, and we understand this concern.  While we can’t plan for every eventuality, we hope you will find it reassuring that our Incident Management Group (IMG) will be meeting daily, with effect from Induction Week, and that the Business Continuity Group (BCG) is now meeting twice weekly, to enable a swift response to any emerging situation. The IMG includes senior professional services staff from Student Services, the School Office, Security, the residences, Human Resources and Health &amp; Safety, as well as Student Union (SU) representatives.  IMG reports in to BCG which includes the deans and senior staff across the University, as well as Trade Union and SU representatives.  We have detailed COVID incident plans, created with input from NHS Lothian and other partners, and our Incident Planning Group is meeting in the next few days to run through all our plans again. Our provision of on-campus COVID testing and vaccination facilities will also help reduce the risk of large numbers of students and staff needing to self-isolate and/or being required to self-isolate for the full quarantine period. </p>\n<p>Wishing you all the very best for the new semester.</p>\n<p>Professor Richard Butt</p>\n<p>Deputy Principal</p>\n<p> </p>\n<p>Updated Policy on Face Coverings</p>\n<p>We are updating our policy on face coverings with immediate effect, based on the latest advice from the Scottish Government.  </p>\n<p>In line with Scottish Government guidance, anyone on campus will be required to use face coverings when inside the buildings. This includes in classrooms, in the atrium and LRC and other indoor spaces. </p>\n<p>Exceptions are as follows:</p>\n<p>- Residents within their flats in student accommodation.</p>\n<p>- When seated in the open plan staff offices, where a minimum distance of 1m is maintained.</p>\n<p>- Staff who are delivering a class, where a minimum distance of 1m from their students is maintained.  </p>\n<p>- Staff in meetings where they are keeping at least 1m apart from others in the room.</p>\n<p>- When eating or drinking.</p>\n<p>- Where you have a legal exemption. The government have outlined a number of<a href=\"https://www.gov.scot/publications/coronavirus-covid-19-public-use-of-face-coverings/\"> 'reasonable' reasons for not wearing a face covering</a>.  If you need advice on exemptions (eg if you think you cannot deliver a particular specialist class with students wearing face coverings) please email Health and Safety (<a href=\"mailto:hs-staff@qmu.ac.uk\">hs-staff@qmu.ac.uk</a>).</p>\n<p>The requirement to wear a face coverings on campus will be reviewed mid-semester and will take account of government guidance prevailing at that time.</p>\n<p><img src=\"?width=500&amp;height=241\" alt=\"Image of advice from QMU regarding Coronavirus\" width=\"500\" height=\"241\" data-udi=\"umb://media/8985ebcba2fa4240beb09f632cd6b268\" /></p>"
    },
