      "contentTypeKey": "216ea22b-01af-4645-8972-5766bbd75b6c",
      "udi": "umb://element/2b5be7d426f0418989fca4c27d08b606",
      "title": "6 September 2021",
      "content": "<p>6 September 2021</p>\n<p> </p>\n<p>Dear students and staff</p>\n<p><strong>On-campus COVID vaccination and asymptomatic COVID testing kit collection</strong></p>\n<p>I am writing with details of two important services that will be available to students and to staff from the start of the semester.   </p>\n<p>From Monday, 13 September 2021, we will be hosting an NHS <strong>drop-in vaccination clinic</strong>, and providing access to <strong>COVID self-testing kits </strong>on campus to all students and staff without symptoms of COVID. We are providing these services as part of our ongoing commitment to reducing the risk of COVID infection amongst our University community and beyond.</p>\n<p><strong>Drop-in COVID vaccination clinic on campus for students and staff </strong></p>\n<p>We are hosting a drop-in COVID vaccination centre on campus from Monday, 13 September to Friday, 24 September. The clinic will be based at a cabin outside 1875 (our Food Court), and will be open Monday to Friday between 11.00 am and 6.00 pm daily. Access to the clinic for students and staff will be in 1875.</p>\n<p>The drop-in service is open to all students, including international students, and to all staff. You can come for your first or second jab, provided there has been an eight-week gap between your vaccination.  As it is a drop-in clinic, you will not need to register or to book an appointment in advance in order to get your vaccine – you just turn up during the advertised hours and days on which the clinic is open.  You don’t need to be registered with a GP, to bring a letter or any ID, to be vaccinated.</p>\n<p>The Pfizer, AstraZeneca and Moderna vaccines are being used but please note that there is no choice of vaccine. NHS Lothian, who are running the clinic, are following national guidance from the JCVI. For more information, see NHS Lothian’s <a href=\"https://www.nhslothian.scot/Coronavirus/Vaccine/Pages/Frequently-Asked-Questions.aspx\">FAQs.</a></p>\n<p>If you are a student and able to get vaccinated before the start of the semester, we would still urge you to do so. There are drop-in vaccine clinics operating across Scotland currently, details of which can be found on the <a href=\"https://www.nhsinform.scot/vaccinedropinclinics\">NHS Inform website</a>.  These are open to everyone, regardless of where they live. There is information on vaccines for international students on the <a href=\"https://www.studentinformation.gov.scot/coronavirus/international-students\">Student Information Scotland website</a>, and international students can find further guidance at our <a href=\"/{localLink:umb://document/2903c860f28b4ce5a34a763573cd0783}\" title=\"FAQs\">coronavirus FAQs</a> webpage. </p>\n<p>By getting the vaccine as soon as you can, you will help to reduce the risk of COVID and keep Scotland on track.</p>\n<p><strong>LFD Collect: a service enabling you to test for COVID twice weekly at home </strong></p>\n<p>Under arrangements agreed for Scottish universities, students and staff without COVID symptoms will be able to collect lateral flow devices (LFDs) on campus for routine twice weekly testing at home.  The service will be available from Monday, 13 September to Thursday, 30 September. </p>\n<p>It is quick and easy to do a self-administered lateral flow test, and the kits offered as part of this service require only a nasal swab ie a throat swab is not required.  Full instructions are provided in each kit.</p>\n<p>Testing is voluntary, but is an important part of the Scottish Government’s approach to containing the COVID virus. Around 1 in 3 people with coronavirus do not show symptoms, so can spread the virus to others without knowing. Regular testing helps to find positive cases in people who have no symptoms, but who are still infectious. If people who test positive self-isolate, we can break chain of transmission and help limit the spread of coronavirus.</p>\n<p>The LFD kit collection point will be just inside the main entrance to the University, at the desk opposite the main reception. You will be able to collect a box containing seven tests, which will allow you to test yourself twice a week over the three week period of the service.  The collection point will be open between 11.00 am and 4.00 pm on advertised dates (specific dates to be confirmed). Students living in on-campus accommodation are being provided with test kits in their rooms, and so will not need to visit the collection point for their kits.</p>\n<p>It is important that you report each test result online to NHS Test and Trace, whether positive, negative or void. Reporting takes only a minute or two, and Instructions for doing this come with the testing kits. Reporting results helps the NHS monitor the spread of the virus, combat the virus and save lives.  Please see the <a href=\"https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/coronavirus-covid-19-testing-privacy-information\">NHS Track and Trace Privacy Notice Summary</a> to find out how they use your personal data.</p>\n<p>It is important that all students and staff testing themselves twice-weekly at home arrange to self-isolate immediately in the event of a positive test, and order a confirmatory PCR test.  If you do register a positive result, please let us know, as per the instructions in our <a href=\"/{localLink:umb://document/dfe7ffd43654452ba70403e5181a48db}\" title=\"Staff\">staff</a> and <a href=\"/{localLink:umb://document/2d74bbbb94e34467ab39bb1f82a83b2e}\" title=\"Students\">student</a> coronavirus FAQs, so that we can provide pastoral support and further advice. Even if the test result is negative, you should continue to test yourself twice weekly.</p>\n<p>Please remember too that you do not need to travel to campus to obtain lateral flow devices.  Each of us can <a href=\"https://www.nhsinform.scot/illnesses-and-conditions/infections-and-poisoning/coronavirus-covid-19/test-and-protect/coronavirus-covid-19-get-a-test-if-you-do-not-have-symptoms\">obtain free LFD testing kits for use at home through pharmacies, community testing sites and online</a>.  </p>\n<p>As set out above, the LFD Collect service will be available to students returning to campus, and to student accommodation.  However, all students are strongly encouraged to take a test 48 hours before the date of travel, to help avoid spreading of the virus. Students living in Scotland or in Wales who are moving to take up term time accommodation should access free PCR testing <em>before</em> leaving their current address. English and Northern Irish domiciled students should access ‘LFD at home’ testing.  Further information can be found on the <a href=\"https://www.studentinformation.gov.scot/coronavirus/new-term\">Student Information Scotland website</a> (Test and Protect section of page).</p>\n<p>We do hope that you will participate in twice-weekly testing, whether you obtain test kits on campus or elsewhere, and that you act to get vaccinated as soon as possible, if you are not vaccinated currently.  Your actions will help to keep us all safe. Thank you for your support.</p>\n<p>All the information above is also found on our <a href=\"/{localLink:umb://document/ce8c5f4b067647529811fd507b9beadb}\" title=\"Test\">Testing and Vaccination</a> webpage which will be updated as appropriate.</p>\n<p>Irene Hynd</p>\n<p>University Secretary</p>"
    },
