      "title": "30 August 2021",
      "content": "<p>Dear students,</p>\n<p>Though this update is a little longer than usual, it includes important information regarding the start of the academic session, so please do take the time to read it carefully. Thank you. </p>\n<p aria-level=\"2\">Operating on campus at ‘Beyond Level 0’ </p>\n<p>As you will know, nationally we are at what the Scottish Government term ‘Beyond Level 0’. We are planning for the start of next semester based on this status, as described on our <a href=\"/{localLink:umb://document/5a7707786d114459a3af3db923be1e56}\" title=\"Coronavirus beyond level 0: how the University works\">coronavirus website.</a>  Our Senior Leadership Team continues to liaise directly with government, and in the event that any COVID restrictions were to be changed nationally or locally, we would be able to respond proportionately and speedily.</p>\n<p>We are currently updating campus signage, website and intranet information, room layouts etc to reflect Beyond Level 0. If you are on campus during this transitional phase, you may, for example, still come across signage relating to the situation before we moved into Beyond Level 0.  We plan to have everything up to date for the start of the semester.</p>\n<p aria-level=\"2\">Things we ask you to do to keep us all safe: new video launched </p>\n<p>We have launched a short video setting out the things that we are asking students to do to help keep us all safe. You can find our ‘Keeping You Safe’ video on <a href=\"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=jsB6AmckyZI&amp;t=3s\">YouTube</a> and on the <a href=\"/{localLink:umb://document/e3a1cc188042429781c78bab7ff95416}\" title=\"Campus Life\">Campus Life and Health and Safety page</a> on our COVID website. Staff are being asked to follow similar guidelines.</p>\n<p aria-level=\"2\">Additional social space on campus </p>\n<p>For the first few weeks of semester, we will have a marquee on campus (‘The Tent’) to provide additional social and event space, helping to avoid congestion, and our Students’ Union have announced their <a href=\"https://www.qmusu.org.uk/top-menu/events/welcome-to-qmu-2021\">Welcome to QMU 2021 Guide</a>. </p>\n<p aria-level=\"2\">Importance of regular COVID testing and of testing before travel  </p>\n<p>Within our Keeping You Safe video we refer to the importance of us all testing ourselves regularly and of students travelling to term-time accommodation taking a COVID test before they travel.  We are working with government to provide Lateral Flow Device (LFD) asymptomatic testing kits for student and staff collection on campus from the start of the semester, to allow twice weekly testing at home. In the meantime, all of us can <a href=\"https://www.nhsinform.scot/illnesses-and-conditions/infections-and-poisoning/coronavirus-covid-19/test-and-protect/coronavirus-covid-19-get-a-test-if-you-do-not-have-symptoms\">obtain free LFD testing kits for use at home through pharmacies, community testing sites and online</a>.</p>\n<p>Students travelling to term-time accommodation should either test themselves beforehand using an LFD kit or through the PCR Test Before Travel service, which is also free.  Students currently living in Scotland or in Wales who are returning to university, and who don’t have COVID symptoms, can access the PCR Test Before Travel service currently via a <a href=\"https://self-referral.test-for-coronavirus.service.gov.uk/antigen/essential-worker?direction=back\">UK Government self-referral online</a> form.   For more information, please see the instructions and FAQs on the <a href=\"http://ps//www.studentinformation.gov.scot/coronavirus/new-term\">Student Information Scotland website</a> (Test and Protect section). English and Northern Irish domiciled students should access LFD at home testing. Please note that <a href=\"https://www.gov.scot/publications/coronavirus-covid-19-international-travel-quarantine/\">different arrangements</a> are in place for students travelling from abroad.</p>\n<p aria-level=\"2\">Getting vaccinated </p>\n<p>Vaccination is also very important in keeping us safe.  The Scottish Government is running <a href=\"https://www.nhsinform.scot/vaccinedropinclinics\" title=\"Link to Vaccine Drop-In Centres\">a campaign urging students to get vaccinated before they travel to University</a> so that you are all ready for student life.   In addition to this, the University is working closely with NHS Lothian to provide an NHS vaccination site on campus for the start of Semester 1, to be available for all students and staff to access on a drop in basis. But we would urge you to get vaccinated before the start of semester if at all possible. </p>\n<p>Covering the cost of managed quarantine for international students </p>\n<p>We have let international students know that both new and returning international students who are coming to QMU for on-campus teaching in Semester 1 and are travelling from a <a href=\"https://www.gov.uk/guidance/red-amber-and-green-list-rules-for-entering-england#red-list\">UK travel red-list country</a> can have the cost of their managed quarantine reimbursed (to a maximum of £2,285). Please see our <a href=\"/{localLink:umb://document/4da50204dcaa4c608ee3d0a49f0438c5}\" title=\"International\">coronavirus FAQs for international students</a> for more information. </p>\n<p>Car parking on campus </p>\n<p>Over the next few weeks we will issue information on arrangements for car parking permits for the next academic year. As modelling shows that attendance on campus is likely to be fairly close to pre-pandemic levels, it is essential that we manage car park access in this way.  Reflecting that some working patterns may be different from the pre-COVID position, the permit system will be more flexible than previously, with the opportunity to pay for day permits by app or on your phone. We will be employing number plate recognition technology so that we will not need to use the exit barrier. </p>\n<p> </p>\n<p>Once again, apologies for the length of this update. I hope you find the information in it helpful. </p>\n<p>Professor Richard Butt </p>\n<p>Deputy Principal </p>\n<p> </p>\n<p> </p>\n<p>Dear colleagues,</p>\n<p>Though this update is a little longer than usual, it includes important information regarding the start of the academic session, so please do take the time to read it carefully. Thank you.</p>\n<p aria-level=\"2\">Operating on campus at ‘Beyond Level 0’ </p>\n<p>As you will know, nationally we are at what the Scottish Government term ‘Beyond Level 0’. We are planning for the start of next semester based on this status, as described on our <a href=\"/{localLink:umb://document/5a7707786d114459a3af3db923be1e56}\" title=\"Coronavirus beyond level 0: how the University works\">coronavirus website.</a>  Our Senior Leadership Team continues to liaise directly with government, and in the event that any COVID restrictions were to be changed nationally or locally, we would be able to respond proportionately and speedily.</p>\n<p>We are currently updating campus signage, website and intranet information, room layouts etc to reflect Beyond Level 0. If you are on campus during this transitional phase, you may, for example, still come across signage relating to the situation before we moved into Beyond Level 0.  We plan to have everything up to date for the start of the semester.</p>\n<p>Within teams across the University, discussions continue on preparation for working at Beyond Level 0. As you know, we are treating this as a transitional semester, during which we will be trialling approaches to service delivery and working patterns, including hybrid working, that accommodate the business needs of the University and its stakeholders.  </p>\n<p aria-level=\"2\">Risk assessments  </p>\n<p>In these discussions, one common question that has arisen is in relation to ventilation in areas without windows. The campus buildings have modern ventilation systems that have been designed to meet building standards and the fresh air provision is through natural ventilation (i.e. windows), mechanical ventilation or a combination of both. The mechanical ventilation is primarily supplied through floor grilles but can also be via high-level grilles. In line with Health and Safety Executive (HSE) recommendations, our ventilation systems are set to be fully operational from two hours before occupation and continue two hours post occupation to purge the buildings. The Estates team will continue to monitor the performance of the system via the Building Management System and will audit the air quality in spaces by deploying portable CO2 monitors, as appropriate.  </p>\n<p>We know there have been some questions about windows which cannot be opened (for example, because of blinds), and which windows should be opened. We are addressing these points and, as appropriate, will provide guidance in signage in the spaces concerned.  Colleagues have also asked if doors into teaching spaces should be left open.  Doors should be left shut to avoid unbalancing our ventilation systems.  Indeed fire doors must always be left closed and wedging them open breaches safety regulations. </p>\n<p>You can find the latest version of our University-Wide Risk Assessment (URA) on our <a href=\"https://myshare.qmu.ac.uk/services/campus-commercial-services/covid19/SitePages/Risk%20Assessments.aspx\">COVID intranet site</a>. This risk assessment is in line with HSE guidance and has been prepared in consultation with our trade unions, and is designed to ensure that we provide a safe working environment. </p>\n<p>Things we ask you to do to keep us all safe: new video launched </p>\n<p>We have launched a short video setting out the things that we are asking students to do to help keep us all safe. You can find our ‘Keeping You Safe’ video on <a href=\"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=jsB6AmckyZI&amp;t=3s\">YouTube</a> and on the <a href=\"/{localLink:umb://document/e3a1cc188042429781c78bab7ff95416}\" title=\"Campus Life\">Campus Life and Health and Safety page</a> on our COVID website.</p>\n<p>Our updated “Working Safely on Campus” e-learning module for staff is near completion, and will be in line with the guidance we are giving students. We also plan updated Open Plan Working Etiquette Guidance. In the meantime, we would ask staff to keep their desks and surrounding areas as clear as possible, to enable easy surface cleaning and to help create a healthy and pleasant working environment for us all.</p>\n<p aria-level=\"2\">Additional social space on campus </p>\n<p>For the first few weeks of semester, we will have a marquee on campus (‘The Tent’) to provide additional social and event space, helping to avoid congestion, and our Students’ Union have announced their <a href=\"https://www.qmusu.org.uk/top-menu/events/welcome-to-qmu-2021\">Welcome to QMU 2021 Guide</a>. </p>\n<p aria-level=\"2\">Importance of regular COVID testing and of testing before travel  </p>\n<p>Within our Keeping You Safe video we refer to the importance of us all testing ourselves regularly and of students travelling to term-time accommodation taking a COVID test before they travel.  We are working with government to provide Lateral Flow Device (LFD) asymptomatic testing kits for student and staff collection on campus from the start of the semester, to allow twice weekly testing at home. In the meantime, all of us can <a href=\"https://www.nhsinform.scot/illnesses-and-conditions/infections-and-poisoning/coronavirus-covid-19/test-and-protect/coronavirus-covid-19-get-a-test-if-you-do-not-have-symptoms\">obtain free LFD testing kits for use at home through pharmacies, community testing sites and online</a>.</p>\n<p>Students travelling to term-time accommodation should either test themselves beforehand using an LFD kit or through the PCR Test Before Travel service, which is also free.  Students currently living in Scotland or in Wales who are returning to university, and who don’t have COVID symptoms, can access the PCR Test Before Travel service currently via a <a href=\"https://self-referral.test-for-coronavirus.service.gov.uk/antigen/essential-worker?direction=back\">UK Government self-referral online</a> form.   For more information, please see the instructions and FAQS on the <a href=\"http://ps//www.studentinformation.gov.scot/coronavirus/new-term\">Student Information Scotland website</a> (Test and Protect section). English and Northern Irish domiciled students should access LFD at home testing. Please note that <a href=\"https://www.gov.scot/publications/coronavirus-covid-19-international-travel-quarantine/\">different arrangements</a> are in place for students travelling from abroad. </p>\n<p>Getting vaccinated </p>\n<p>Vaccination is also very important in keeping us safe.  The Scottish Government is running <a href=\"https://www.nhsinform.scot/vaccinedropinclinics\" title=\"Link to Vaccine Drop-In Centres\">a campaign urging students to get vaccinated before they travel to University</a> so that they are all ready for student life.   In addition to this, the University is working closely with NHS Lothian to provide an NHS vaccination site on campus for the start of Semester 1, to be available for all students and staff to access on a drop in basis. But we would urge you to get vaccinated before the start of semester if at all possible.</p>\n<p aria-level=\"2\">Covering the cost of managed quarantine for international students </p>\n<p>We have let international students know that both new and returning international students who are coming to QMU for on-campus teaching in Semester 1 and are travelling from a <a href=\"https://www.gov.uk/guidance/red-amber-and-green-list-rules-for-entering-england#red-list\">UK travel red-list country</a> can have the cost of their managed quarantine reimbursed (to a maximum of £2,285). Please see our <a href=\"/coronavirus/faqs/international/\">coronavirus FAQs for international students</a> for more information. </p>\n<p>Car parking on campus </p>\n<p>As was said in the last staff COVID update, over the next few weeks we will issue information on arrangements for car parking permits for the next academic year. As modelling shows that attendance on campus is likely to be fairly close to pre-pandemic levels, it is essential that we manage car park access in this way.  Reflecting that some working patterns may be different from the pre-COVID position, the permit system will be more flexible than previously, with the opportunity to pay for day permits by app or on your phone. We will be employing number plate recognition technology so that we will not need to use the exit barrier. </p>\n<p>Once again, apologies for the length of this update. I hope you find the information in it helpful.</p>\n<p>Professor Richard Butt </p>\n<p>Deputy Principal </p>"
    },
