      "title": "16 August 2021",
      "content": "<p>16 August (staff update only) - for latest student update see under 22 July)</p>\n<p>Dear colleagues</p>\n<p>I hope that you are managing to take some time off to relax over the summer.  This is a brief COVID update to let you know that:</p>\n<ol>\n<li>As promised in our message of <a href=\"https://myshare.qmu.ac.uk/news/Lists/Posts/Post.aspx?ID=2095\">22 July</a>,<strong> line managers have now been issued with guidance on preparing for the transitional “Beyond Level Zero” phase of the QMU’s route map</strong>. This guidance takes account of the fact that, with effect from the start of semester one in mid-September, the overwhelming majority of students will be back on campus, and that the working pattern for most staff will therefore more closely resemble the position which pertained pre-COVID. It includes advice on how managers should engage with their team members and obtain their feedback, using an informal, consultative approach. As we are conscious that some line managers will be on holiday right now, the HR team are keeping an eye on progress, to help ensure that, as far as possible, all staff members have an opportunity to participate in discussions.</li>\n<li>I am sure that many of you are taking advantage of the fact that, nationally, we are at Beyond Level 0. We are planning for the start of next semester based on this status, as described on our <a href=\"/{localLink:umb://document/b673e3c08a21451691ec92f364641f89}\" title=\"Coronavirus\">coronavirus website</a>. <strong>As you will appreciate, it will take time to get all campus signage, website and intranet information, room layouts, etc, configured for Beyond Level 0. This means that we are in a transitional phase during which you may, for example, still come across signage relating to the situation before we moved into Beyond Level 0.</strong>  Please be assured that everything will be up to date in advance of the start of induction week on 13 September. As part of this work, in due course you will be issued with an updated “Working Safely on Campus” e-learning module and updated Open Plan Working Etiquette Guidance.</li>\n<li><strong>Our University Wide </strong>and<strong> Learning and Teaching</strong> <strong>risk assessments </strong>have been<strong> updated </strong>to take account of the move to Beyond Level 0. You can find the updated versions on the <a href=\"https://myshare.qmu.ac.uk/services/campus-commercial-services/covid19/SitePages/Risk%20Assessments.aspx\">Risk Assessment section of the COVID intranet site</a>.</li>\n<li><strong>Over the next few weeks we will issue information on arrangements for car parking permits for the next academic year.</strong> As modelling shows that attendance on campus is likely to be fairly close to pre-pandemic levels, it is essential that we manage car park access in this way.  Reflecting that some working patterns may be different from the pre-COVID position, the permit system will be more flexible than previously, with the opportunity to pay for day permits by app or on your phone. We will be employing number plate recognition technology so that we will not need to use the exit barrier.</li>\n<li><strong>We have updated our policy on face coverings on campus</strong> to reflect the easing of COVID restrictions nationally. From now, face coverings only require to be worn when circulating across indoor campus spaces, except by those who are legally exempt for medical reasons.  You do not need to wear a face covering when seated, for example in the Learning Resource Centre, atrium, staff open plan offices, teaching and learning spaces etc, although you may of course continue to choose to do so.</li>\n</ol>\n<p>I hope that this update is helpful. Unless there is further news to report, our next COVID update will not be until after the end of August.  In the meantime, I hope we all enjoy some sunny weather over the remainder of the summer.</p>\n<p>Malcolm G Cutt</p>\n<p>Director of Operations and Finance</p>"
    },
    {
      "contentTypeKey": "216ea22b-01af-4645-8972-5766bbd75b6c",
      "udi": "umb://element/413b0bcb0fe6495f8c90c63e4fae7841",
      "title": "22 July 2021",
      "content": "<p>22 July 2021</p>\n<p> </p>\n<p>Dear students</p>\n<p><strong>Looking ahead to next semester</strong></p>\n<p>With the 2020/21 academic session ending and following the First Minister’s update to parliament last week, we are now able to provide an update on the University’s route map for return to campus in semester one of Session 2021-22.</p>\n<p>Although we will all still be living with COVID for some time to come, we can confirm that we expect that induction and academic programmes will start as scheduled this autumn.  The exact date of your first class (and your first face-to-face class) will depend on your programme. The semester starts on 20 September 2021, with induction for new students starting the week before that (from 13 September 2021).</p>\n<p><strong>Teaching and learning, and student support</strong></p>\n<p>Your safety and wellbeing continue to be our primary concern, but we want you to be able to enjoy, to the fullest extent possible, the social and educational benefits that an on-campus experience can provide.</p>\n<p>Our plan is that students will be able to access in-person on-campus activity as usual for all their small group work (seminars, workshops, studio work, clinics etc.).  However, we expect that there may continue to be some restrictions on maximum group sizes.  For that reason, we plan to deliver lectures online, allowing you to watch and review them when and where you want, this functionality and flexibility having received positive student feedback this academic year.</p>\n<p>There will be full access to library and study space facilities. All student support services will be available on campus, with some also available online.</p>\n<p>All the above is, of course, subject to Scottish Government guidelines. We will maintain the capacity to switch to a more blended mode of delivery (combination of on campus and online learning activity) if Scottish Government guidelines require it. </p>\n<p>Campus life</p>\n<p>We will continue to offer indoor and outdoor food and alcohol sales in Maggie’s and anticipate using a licenced marquee during peak periods of demand.  Starbucks and the 1875 food court will be open subject to demand. You will be encouraged to use the app to order food to avoid queues.  </p>\n<p>We expect that all sports will be permitted, but subject to some continuing mitigating actions.  We expect too that social activities will be possible for student societies, the Students’ Union, and ResLife, subject to events sector guidance.</p>\n<p>Our route map</p>\n<p>You can find all the above information in our route map for the return to campus, which you can now find on the coronavirus section of our website. Our route map mirrors the Scottish Government’s coronavirus protection levels and draws on current advice and guidance issued by the Scottish Government.</p>\n<p>For semester one of 2021/22, it is currently anticipated that we will be operating under the “beyond level zero” protection level. It should be noted that, in this level, there will no longer be a requirement for physical distancing. However, several other mitigations will remain in place, including continued use of face coverings, enhanced hygiene / cleaning in high volume traffic areas, attendance recording for outbreak management purposes, and enhanced ventilation with routine and regular monitoring. There will no longer be one-way systems on campus, except at the entry and exit points. Two-way circulation will be managed through signage advising you to keep to the left.</p>\n<p>Vaccinations and Testing</p>\n<p>The roll-out of the national vaccination programme continues, with all adults expected to have had their first dose by 18 July, and to have had their second dose by 12 September.</p>\n<p>Vaccinations are key to our way out of the pandemic, and while an individual choice, it is important that you take up the vaccine when invited to do so, as you can get seriously ill with coronavirus at any age. Although having the vaccine does not eliminate the risk of coronavirus, if you and your loved ones have it, it will reduce the impact of the virus and help us to get back to the things we’ve all missed.  You can find <a href=\"https://www.nhsinform.scot/covid-19-vaccine\">further information at NHS inform</a></p>\n<p>It is expected that, for the start of next academic session, the Scottish Government will support universities in providing Lateral Flow Device (LFD) asymptomatic testing kits for student and staff collection on campus. This would bring universities in line with the offer in other education settings.  Alongside this, the government is encouraging students, and indeed all of us without Covid symptoms to take advantage of LFD testing through a variety of routes. You can <a href=\"https://www.nhsinform.scot/illnesses-and-conditions/infections-and-poisoning/coronavirus-covid-19/test-and-protect/coronavirus-covid-19-get-a-test-if-you-do-not-have-symptoms\">order lateral flow tests online or collect them from a test site, for fast twice weekly testing at home</a>.</p>\n<p><br />Advice for international students – arrival, quarantine, visa, and vaccination</p>\n<p>We strongly encourage as many students as possible to return to campus in time for the start of the academic term in September where it is possible to do so. For those international students unable to make it here to Edinburgh for the start of semester due to travel restrictions or delays in the issuing of visas, we will do all we can to support you until you are able to return to the campus.  For those who can return, our expectation is that you do so. Your time at university will be significantly enhanced by an on-campus experience and many of our programmes have compulsory practical requirements that we cannot deliver remotely.</p>\n<p>Based on <a href=\"https://assets.publishing.service.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/998895/Student_Guidance-_Covid-19_response_01072021_FINAL.pdf\">current guidance issued by UK Visas and Immigration (UKVI),</a> new and returning international students who are initially <strong>unable</strong> to travel to the UK are permitted to undertake their course of study via distance learning but must travel to commence their study in person as soon as they are able and no later than 6<sup>th</sup> April 2022. Students will still need to demonstrate that they are fully engaging in their programme of study.  Students in this position should email <a href=\"mailto:registry@qmu.ac.uk\"><strong>registry@qmu.ac.uk </strong></a>as soon as possible.</p>\n<p>International students who hold a Tier 4/ Student Visa who are already in the UK will <strong>not</strong> be able to study via distance learning from Semester 1 under that guidance. They can continue existing courses or commence new courses of study by blended learning. Blended learning is currently permitted by UKVI until 6<sup>th</sup> April 2022. This means that students will be expected to attend all sessions in person on campus that are detailed by your chosen course of study at QMU.</p>\n<p>We also recommend visiting the <a href=\"https://www.ukcisa.org.uk/\">UK Council for International Student Affairs</a> website as a source of external advice.</p>\n<p>Meanwhile, the Scottish Government recently announced that the vaccination programme in Scotland has been <a href=\"https://www.gov.scot/news/expanding-the-national-vaccination-programme/\">expanded to include all international students</a>. You will find FAQs on this topic on the <a href=\"https://www.studentinformation.gov.scot/coronavirus/international-students\"><strong>Student Information Scotland</strong></a> website and the QMU FAQs for <a href=\"/{localLink:umb://document/4da50204dcaa4c608ee3d0a49f0438c5}\" title=\"International\">International Students</a> which will be regularly updated. </p>\n<p>Discussions are continuing with the Scottish Government on quarantine arrangements for overseas students, with the current understanding being that students from amber list countries observe quarantine in their home – whether that be University halls, purpose-built student accommodation, or private accommodation. </p>\n<p>How we will keep you updated</p>\n<p>Although we plan to pause our regular coronavirus email updates until the latter half of August, we will communicate any significant updates and guidance by email, social media, and the website, as necessary. Please remember that the coronavirus section on the University website will normally be the best place for you to find up-to-date information on our plans.</p>\n<p>We hope you are looking forward to the next academic year with optimism and excitement.  While things will still be ‘different’, we are confident that student life will be easier than it has been this last year. In the meantime, we wish you a happy and fulfilling summer.</p>\n<p><strong>Professor Richard Butt, Deputy Principal                                              <br /></strong><strong>Malcolm G Cutt, Director of Operations &amp; Finance</strong></p>\n<p><strong>-------------</strong></p>\n<p>Dear colleagues</p>\n<p>Update on staff return to campus “route map”</p>\n<p>Following the First Minister’s announcement to parliament last week, we are now able to provide an update on the University’s route map for staff return to campus in semester one. The <a href=\"/{localLink:umb://media/513ad49bbf3740ce9584ff3b5ab52981}\" title=\"Qm Route Map Simple Version 2021 V09 220721\" data-udi=\"umb://media/2f9c57c2b8cb4da48fa42e3ce6c34ba4\">route map</a>, which you can find on the coronavirus section of our website, mirrors the Scottish Government’s coronavirus protection levels and draws on current advice and guidance issued by the Scottish Government. It has been informed by the planning principles and assumptions agreed by Senate, and has also been informed by the University Risk Assessment, which may be viewed <a href=\"https://myshare.qmu.ac.uk/services/campus-commercial-services/covid19/SitePages/Risk%20Assessments.aspx\">on our COVID intranet site</a>.</p>\n<p>The route map will be hosted on the University website and will make clear what protection level is applicable to the University campus at any given time. It will also be adjusted as further iterations of government guidance are issued and updated. For semester one of 2021/22, it is currently anticipated that we will be operating under the “beyond level zero” protection level, and the route map identifies the implications arising from this level on the various University operations and activities</p>\n<p>In many respects, the “beyond level zero” level implies a return to operational activities comparable with those that existed pre-COVID, although in each case subject to ongoing, albeit reduced, levels of mitigation. All operations and activities will continue to be supported by relevant risk assessments, which will ensure that it is safe for staff to return to campus.  We see semester one, and potentially the whole of the 2021/22 academic year, as a period of transition, before we return to a more stable way of operating.</p>\n<p>What does this mean for staff working arrangements in semester one?</p>\n<p>The University route map sets out which activities will be permitted on campus from September. In line with the Scottish Government’s <a href=\"https://www.gov.scot/publications/coronavirus-covid-19-scotlands-strategic-framework-update-june-2021/\">Strategic Framework update</a>, issued in June, we will continue to support a greater degree of working from home than pre-COVID during this transitional period where that is possible and appropriate. How this applies to specific staff teams will depend on the nature of the service they offer and where they can most effectively deliver that service, mindful that students will be back on campus for most of their learning and teaching activities. Your manager will be in touch to discuss those working arrangements with you if they have not already done so.  Plans for learning and teaching remain as set out on the <a href=\"/{localLink:umb://document/84daaed5f3d04cd09566859f91fb8d90}\" title=\"Applicants\">coronavirus section of the website</a>, and recent Government announcements support our agreed approach to the timetable and learning and teaching delivery in the coming semester.</p>\n<p>Other aspects of campus life</p>\n<p><strong> </strong>We will continue to offer indoor and outdoor food and alcohol sales in Maggie’s and anticipate using a licenced marquee during peak periods of demand.  Starbucks and the 1875 food court will be open subject to demand. You will be encouraged to use the app to order food to avoid queues.  There will be full access to library and study space facilities. </p>\n<p>Providing you with the guidance you need</p>\n<p>Although we plan to pause our regular coronavirus email updates until the latter half of August, we will communicate any significant updates and guidance by email, social media, and the website, as necessary. Please remember that the coronavirus section on the University website will normally be the best place for you to find up-to-date information on our plans.</p>\n<p>Whilst we will be operating under these transitional arrangements during semester one, and possibly semester two of the next academic session, work is also taking place to support consideration of the future way we will work and operate as a university.  Our initial thoughts, and details of how you can be involved in any consequent change process, will be shared with staff in the coming months. Please be assured that any decisions in this area would only be taken following consultation with staff and trade union representatives.</p>\n<p>Listening to you</p>\n<p>We appreciate that your feelings about a return to a more 'normal' way of working will vary according to your personal circumstances and experiences of home/on-campus working over the last year. If you have questions or concerns about our route map, your line manager is your first port of call. They, or you, can call on your Senior Leadership Team (SLT) member as appropriate for further advice. SLT staff are all members of our Business Continuity Group that oversees our approach to managing COVID.</p>\n<p>We plan to arrange a ‘Meet the Principal’ Teams Live session prior to the start of the academic session which will provide an opportunity for you to ask any questions you may have about the return to campus, and university activities more generally.</p>\n<p><strong>Professor Richard Butt, Deputy Principal</strong><br /><strong>Malcolm G Cutt, Director of Operations &amp; Finance</strong></p>\n<p> </p>"
