      "content": "<p class=\"x_MsoNormal\">2 July 2021</p>\n<p class=\"x_MsoNormal\"> </p>\n<p>Dear students,</p>\n<p>Scottish Government review of physical distancing</p>\n<p class=\"x_MsoNormal\">As announced in the <a rel=\"noopener noreferrer\" href=\"https://www.gov.scot/publications/coronavirus-covid-19-update-first-ministers-statement-22-june-2021/\" target=\"_blank\" data-auth=\"NotApplicable\" data-linkindex=\"0\">First Minister’s update on 22 June</a>, the Scottish Government has recently published its <a name=\"x__Hlk76049154\" data-linkindex=\"1\"></a><a rel=\"noopener noreferrer\" href=\"https://www.gov.scot/publications/coronavirus-covid-19-review-physical-distancing-scotland-june-2021/\" target=\"_blank\" data-auth=\"NotApplicable\" data-linkindex=\"2\">review of physical distancing</a>.</p>\n<p class=\"x_MsoNormal\">In light of a decrease in hospital admissions resulting from the continued rollout of the vaccination programme, the Scottish Government hopes to move all parts of Scotland to level zero on 19 July, and to remove all restrictions on physical distancing on 9 August.  Under those relaxed restrictions, groups of any number will be able to meet up outdoors (except at organised outdoor events), while gatherings of up to ten people from four households will be permitted indoors.  Both of these relaxations will be conditional on a review of the epidemic ahead of the specific date.</p>\n<p class=\"x_MsoNormal\">What is not currently clear is what these relaxations mean for the current planning being undertaken in colleges and universities across Scotland. The First Minister stated in her update that the government would be working on the return of schools, colleges and universities over the summer. We appreciate that it is frustrating that we are unable to provide you with firm information at this point, but please be assured that we are working directly with the Scottish Government to ensure that we understand, and are able to influence, the guidance that it will issue to the sector. We will update you just as soon as such guidance is issued, and a route map towards a more normal learning experience is available.  </p>\n<p>Scottish Government Summer Safety campaign</p>\n<p>You may have already seen on our social media channels that the Scottish Government is currently <a rel=\"noopener noreferrer\" href=\"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=BuJ6eX4vGeA\" target=\"_blank\" data-auth=\"NotApplicable\" data-linkindex=\"3\">running a summer safety campaign</a> to remind members of the public of the importance of continuing to make safer choices while the vaccine continues to be rolled out across the country. This includes:</p>\n<ul>\n<li class=\"x_MsoNormal\">continuing to wear a face covering in crowded places</li>\n<li class=\"x_MsoListParagraph\">choosing to meet up outdoors where possible</li>\n<li class=\"x_MsoListParagraph\">remembering to wash your hands regularly</li>\n<li class=\"x_MsoListParagraph\">opening windows when meeting indoors</li>\n<li class=\"x_MsoListParagraph\">avoiding crowded places</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Online registration for vaccination appointments and drop-in vaccination clinics</p>\n<p class=\"x_MsoNormal\">Students and staff are reminded that anyone over the age of 18 in Scotland, as well as anyone who has not yet received their first dose, is eligible to <a rel=\"noopener noreferrer\" href=\"https://www.nhsinform.scot/covid-19-vaccine/invitations-and-appointments/registering-for-a-coronavirus-vaccine\" target=\"_blank\" data-auth=\"NotApplicable\" data-linkindex=\"4\">register for their COVID vaccine appointment online</a> without having to wait for their letter to come through.</p>\n<p class=\"x_MsoNormal\">Drop-in vaccination clinics are also in operation in the Lothians. These clinics are open to anyone over the age of 18 who has not yet had their first dose of the vaccine, and those who are still waiting on their second dose, providing their first injection of the COVID-19 vaccine took place at least eight weeks before. Please see the <a rel=\"noopener noreferrer\" href=\"https://www.nhslothian.scot/Coronavirus/Vaccine/Pages/Drop-in-Clinics.aspx\" target=\"_blank\" data-auth=\"NotApplicable\" data-linkindex=\"5\">NHS Lothian website</a> to find your nearest clinic, see their opening times and for information about how to get there.</p>\n<p>Vaccination information for international students</p>\n<p class=\"x_MsoNormal\">Although it is not a requirement for international students to be vaccinated before arriving in/returning to the UK, if possible, you are strongly encouraged to get vaccinated before you arrive.</p>\n<p class=\"x_MsoNormal\">We appreciate, however, that not every country will currently have a mature COVID-19 vaccination programme, and so it is essential that students arriving from overseas consider their vaccination needs and <a rel=\"noopener noreferrer\" href=\"https://www.nhsinform.scot/care-support-and-rights/nhs-services/doctors/registering-with-a-gp-practice\" target=\"_blank\" data-auth=\"NotApplicable\" data-linkindex=\"6\">register with a GP practice</a> after arriving in Scotland.</p>\n<p class=\"x_MsoNormal\">Further information can be found on the <a rel=\"noopener noreferrer\" href=\"https://www.studentinformation.gov.scot/coronavirus/international-students\" target=\"_blank\" data-auth=\"NotApplicable\" data-linkindex=\"7\">Student Information Scotland website</a>. This also includes information about testing and quarantine.</p>\n<p class=\"x_MsoNormal\"> </p>\n<p>Dear colleagues,</p>\n<p>Scottish Government review of physical distancing</p>\n<p class=\"x_MsoNormal\">As announced in the <a rel=\"noopener noreferrer\" href=\"https://www.gov.scot/publications/coronavirus-covid-19-update-first-ministers-statement-22-june-2021/\" target=\"_blank\" data-auth=\"NotApplicable\" data-linkindex=\"0\">First Minister’s update on 22 June</a>, the Scottish Government has recently published its <a name=\"x__Hlk76049154\" data-linkindex=\"1\"></a><a rel=\"noopener noreferrer\" href=\"https://www.gov.scot/publications/coronavirus-covid-19-review-physical-distancing-scotland-june-2021/\" target=\"_blank\" data-auth=\"NotApplicable\" data-linkindex=\"2\">review of physical distancing</a>.</p>\n<p class=\"x_MsoNormal\">In light of a decrease in hospital admissions resulting from the continued rollout of the vaccination programme, the Scottish Government hopes to move all parts of Scotland to level zero on 19 July, and to remove all restrictions on physical distancing on 9 August.  Under those relaxed restrictions, groups of any number will be able to meet up outdoors (except at organised outdoor events), while gatherings of up to ten people from four households will be permitted indoors.  Both of these relaxations will be conditional on a review of the epidemic ahead of the specific date.</p>\n<p class=\"x_MsoNormal\">What is not currently clear is what these relaxations mean for the current planning being undertaken in colleges and universities across Scotland. The First Minister stated in her update that the government would be working on the return of schools, colleges and universities over the summer. We appreciate that it is frustrating that we are unable to provide you with firm information at this point, but please be assured that we are working directly with the Scottish Government to ensure that we understand, and are able to influence, the guidance that it will issue to the sector. We will update you just as soon as such guidance is issued, and a route map towards a more normal learning experience is available.</p>\n<p>On campus teaching prior to Semester One Start Date</p>\n<p class=\"x_MsoNormal\">As colleagues will be aware, Semester One of the 2021/22 academic session is <a rel=\"noopener noreferrer\" href=\"/about-the-university/quality/committees-regulations-policies-and-procedures/academic-calendar/2021-22/\" target=\"_blank\" data-auth=\"NotApplicable\" data-linkindex=\"3\">scheduled to commence on 20th September</a> (aka ‘Week Three’). This slightly later than usual start date for teaching was agreed partly to enable as many of our younger students as possible to have had both their COVID vaccinations prior to their move back to Edinburgh/arrival on campus. As such, it is a key part of the University’s COVID Route Map, itself informed by the Scottish Government’s Route Map and guidelines.</p>\n<p class=\"x_MsoNormal\">Consequently, to ensure alignment with this Route Map, and to ensure consistency with our communications to students regarding the commencement of the academic year, any on campus learning and teaching activity scheduled prior to 20th September (i.e. in Week 1 and/or 2) will be tightly restricted to those activities that can only take place on campus and that must take place in those earlier two weeks (rather than online or later). Any such exceptional activity must be approved by the respective Dean of School and, given our duty of care towards our own staff and students, will only be approved if the Deans are confident it meets the conditions set out above.</p>\n<p>Scottish Government Summer Safety campaign</p>\n<p>You may have already seen on our social media channels that the Scottish Government is currently <a rel=\"noopener noreferrer\" href=\"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=BuJ6eX4vGeA\" target=\"_blank\" data-auth=\"NotApplicable\" data-linkindex=\"4\">running a summer safety campaign</a> to remind members of the public of the importance of continuing to make safer choices while the vaccine continues to be rolled out across the country. This includes:</p>\n<ul>\n<li class=\"x_MsoListParagraph\">continuing to wear a face covering in crowded places</li>\n<li class=\"x_MsoListParagraph\">choosing to meet up outdoors where possible</li>\n<li class=\"x_MsoListParagraph\">remembering to wash your hands regularly</li>\n<li class=\"x_MsoListParagraph\">opening windows when meeting indoors</li>\n<li class=\"x_MsoListParagraph\">avoiding crowded places </li>\n</ul>\n<p>Online registration for vaccination appointments and drop-in vaccination clinics</p>\n<p>Students and staff are reminded that anyone over the age of 18 in Scotland, as well as anyone who has not yet received their first dose, is eligible to <a rel=\"noopener noreferrer\" href=\"https://www.nhsinform.scot/covid-19-vaccine/invitations-and-appointments/registering-for-a-coronavirus-vaccine\" target=\"_blank\" data-auth=\"NotApplicable\" data-linkindex=\"5\">register for their COVID vaccine appointment online</a> without having to wait for their letter to come through.</p>\n<p class=\"x_MsoNormal\">Drop-in vaccination clinics are also in operation in the Lothians. These clinics are open to anyone over the age of 18 who has not yet had their first dose of the vaccine, and those who are still waiting on their second dose, providing their first injection of the COVID-19 vaccine took place at least eight weeks before. Please see the <a rel=\"noopener noreferrer\" href=\"https://www.nhslothian.scot/Coronavirus/Vaccine/Pages/Drop-in-Clinics.aspx\" target=\"_blank\" data-auth=\"NotApplicable\" data-linkindex=\"6\">NHS Lothian website</a> to find your nearest clinic, see their opening times and for information about how to get there.</p>\n<p>Vaccination information for international students</p>\n<p class=\"x_MsoNormal\">Although it is not a requirement for international students to be vaccinated before arriving in/returning to the UK, if possible, you are strongly encouraged to get vaccinated before you arrive.</p>\n<p class=\"x_MsoNormal\">We appreciate, however, that not every country will currently have a mature COVID-19 vaccination programme, and so it is essential that students arriving from overseas consider their vaccination needs and <a rel=\"noopener noreferrer\" href=\"https://www.nhsinform.scot/care-support-and-rights/nhs-services/doctors/registering-with-a-gp-practice\" target=\"_blank\" data-auth=\"NotApplicable\" data-linkindex=\"7\">register with a GP practice</a> after arriving in Scotland. </p>\n<p class=\"x_MsoNormal\">Further information can be found on the <a rel=\"noopener noreferrer\" href=\"https://www.studentinformation.gov.scot/coronavirus/international-students\" target=\"_blank\" data-auth=\"NotApplicable\" data-linkindex=\"8\">Student Information Scotland website</a>. This also includes information about testing and quarantine.</p>\n<p class=\"x_MsoNormal\"> </p>"
