      "title": "18 June 2021",
      "content": "<p class=\"x_MsoNormal\">18 June 2021</p>\n<p class=\"x_MsoNormal\"> </p>\n<p class=\"x_MsoNormal\">Dear students and staff,</p>\n<p class=\"x_MsoNormal\">Delay in further easing of COVID restrictions</p>\n<p class=\"x_MsoNormal\">At her next coronavirus update to parliament, planned for Tuesday, the First Minister is expected to announce at least a three week delay in any further easing of COVID restrictions. This is because of the prevalence in Scotland of the more transmissible Delta variant of the virus.</p>\n<p class=\"x_MsoNormal\">Testing arrangements for students and staff</p>\n<p class=\"x_MsoNormal\">Our asymptomatic COVID testing centre is being decommissioned, now that government is encouraging students, and indeed all of us, to take advantage of local testing. Currently, any student or staff member can order lateral flow tests online or collect them from a test site, for fast twice weekly testing at home (<a rel=\"noopener noreferrer\" href=\"https://www.nhsinform.scot/illnesses-and-conditions/infections-and-poisoning/coronavirus-covid-19/test-and-protect/coronavirus-covid-19-get-a-test-if-you-do-not-have-symptoms\" target=\"_blank\" data-auth=\"NotApplicable\" data-linkindex=\"0\"><strong>Find out how to obtain lateral flow test kits</strong></a>).</p>\n<p class=\"x_MsoNormal\">It is expected that, for the start of next academic session, the Scottish Government will support universities to provide an on-campus collection point for testing kits for students and staff to allow regular testing at home. This would bring universities in line with the offer in other education settings.</p>\n<p class=\"x_MsoNormal\">The vaccination centre hosted on campus is also now being decommissioned.</p>\n<p class=\"x_MsoNormal\">Planning for the next academic year</p>\n<p class=\"x_MsoNormal\">You might have seen media coverage of the <a rel=\"noopener noreferrer\" href=\"https://www.universities-scotland.ac.uk/in-person_learning_new_ay/\" target=\"_blank\" data-auth=\"NotApplicable\" data-linkindex=\"1\">call</a> from Universities Scotland, our representative body, for government to provide greater clarity on the planning arrangements for the next academic year, with the call drawing on a survey of students.  Alongside this, meetings continue between the higher education sector and government on plans for next semester, with topics of discussion including teaching and learning, vaccination, student and staff COVID testing, and managed quarantine.  We are working on our own routemap for planning for next semester, based on the best information available, and will share more information as soon as we can.  Our planned approach to teaching and learning remains as published on our <a rel=\"noopener\" href=\"/{localLink:umb://document/84daaed5f3d04cd09566859f91fb8d90}\" target=\"_blank\" title=\"Applicants\" data-auth=\"NotApplicable\" data-linkindex=\"2\">coronavirus website</a>.</p>\n<p class=\"x_MsoNormal\">Activities over the summer</p>\n<p class=\"x_MsoNormal\">As per the information published on Moderator and on the <a rel=\"noopener\" href=\"/{localLink:umb://document/7cfc8bb385d642359966cd749b4be41e}\" target=\"_blank\" title=\"Graduation Celebrations - July 2021\" data-auth=\"NotApplicable\" data-linkindex=\"3\" data-anchor=\"#\">Graduation website</a>, work continues to resolve the issues with graduation celebration booking. Thank you to everyone for their patience as we work through this step by step, with great support from our Students’ Union. </p>\n<p class=\"x_MsoNormal\">While the academic year is largely over for the majority of students and staff, a small number of programmes have a third semester that runs over the summer. Campus Services and other staff are set to support students and staff involved in semester 3 activities.  </p>\n<p class=\"x_MsoNormal\"> </p>\n<p class=\"x_MsoNormal\">Malcolm G Cutt</p>\n<p class=\"x_MsoNormal\">Director of Operations and Finance</p>"
