      "title": "4 June 2021",
      "content": "<p>Student message - 4 June 2021</p>\n<p>Dear students, </p>\n<p>East Lothian to move into Level 1 from Saturday 5 June</p>\n<p>As announced in the First Minister’s <a href=\"https://www.gov.scot/news/cautious-easing-of-restrictions/\">update on Tuesday 1 June</a>, East Lothian is one of fifteen Scottish mainland local authority areas to move down from Level 2 to Level 1 restrictions. The First Minister confirmed that this will take effect from 00:01 on Saturday 5 June.</p>\n<p>Some other local authority areas, including Edinburgh and Midlothian, will remain in Level 2 while the situation with the virus is monitored closely. Students are reminded that travelling between Level 1 and Level 2 areas is permitted.</p>\n<p>This move down to Level 1 means that Maggie’s Bar &amp; Café can now allow up to 8 people, from 3 different households, to sit together indoors, while up to 12 people can sit together outside. Please note that 1875, Starbucks and the main shop will remain closed for now. Further information can be found <a href=\"/{localLink:umb://document/7ac62a9a0ac442c78ae93816a9e60377}\" title=\"Eat and Shop on Campus\">on our website</a>.</p>\n<h2>It’s not too late! 18-29 year olds can still register for their vaccine appointment online</h2>\n<p>As previously mentioned in the Moderator messages dated 25 and 31 May, and on social media, those aged between 18 and 29 can still register to receive their COVID vaccination appointment online by visiting the <a href=\"https://www.nhsinform.scot/under30register\">NHS Inform website</a>.</p>\n<p>Today is the last day that those within that age group can participate, so we’d like to take this opportunity to remind you to register before the end of the day if you haven’t already done so.</p>\n<p>Further information can be found on the <a href=\"https://www.studentinformation.gov.scot/coronavirus/self-registration\">Student Information Scotland</a> website.</p>\n<h2>Availability of regular rapid COVID testing for all people in Scotland</h2>\n<p>Please also remember that everyone in Scotland can now order lateral flow tests online or collect them from a test site, for fast twice weekly testing at home (<a href=\"https://www.gov.scot/publications/coronavirus-covid-19-getting-tested/pages/no-covid-symptoms/\"><strong>Find out how to obtain lateral flow test kits</strong></a>). If you have symptoms of coronavirus, you should book a PCR test immediately rather than rely on a lateral flow test (<a href=\"https://www.gov.scot/publications/coronavirus-covid-19-getting-tested/pages/covid-symptoms/\"><strong>More information on how to book a test if you have symptoms</strong></a>).</p>\n<h2>Lonely Learning &amp; Learning to be Lonely: A study of student resilience and challenge during COVID-19 Lockdown</h2>\n<p>QMU’s Resilient Learning Communities Research Institutional Team is conducting research focused on loneliness and isolation across the student population, before and during COVID-19. They aim to explore the experience of loneliness and isolation amongst students and some strategies that may have been used to manage these.</p>\n<p>The team would like to hear from current QMU students, so if you’d like to take part in the study, you just need to fill out <a href=\"https://qmupsychology.eu.qualtrics.com/jfe/form/SV_4YZUvj5RQRkNLfg\">an online questionnaire</a>. Those who take part will also be entered into a £50 prize draw.</p>\n<h2>Graduation update</h2>\n<p>You will have seen further updates for our summer Graduation plans in an email from the Principal earlier this week.</p>\n<p>These celebrations will be for graduates of the Class of 2020, who missed out on the opportunity to attend their graduation ceremony in July last year, and for students of the Class of 2021 who are eligible to graduate this year. The events will provide the opportunity for students to wear their graduation gown; have their professional photo taken; celebrate with friends, family and staff; and enjoy some QMU hospitality.</p>\n<p>Eligible students/graduates and up to two guests can attend on either Tuesday 13 July or Wednesday 14 July depending on availability. However, places will be limited and bookings will be dealt with on a first come, first served basis. In order to manage the number of people on campus at any one time, and to comply with safety requirements, the event will run from 11.00 am to 7.00 pm over each of the two days. Graduates and their guests will be asked to book a specific timeslot. Graduation information and timeslots are available on the <a href=\"/{localLink:umb://document/cfd71ebad1404308898f173ad553c662}\" title=\"Graduation 2020\">graduation page of the QMU website</a>. <strong>Registration opens to graduating students on Tuesday 8<sup>th</sup> June</strong>.</p>\n<p> </p>\n<p>Malcolm G Cutt</p>\n<p>Director of Operations and Finance</p>\n<p> </p>\n<p>Staff message - 4 June 2021</p>\n<p>Dear colleagues, </p>\n<h2>East Lothian to move into Level 1 from Saturday 5 June</h2>\n<p>As announced in the First Minister’s <a href=\"https://www.gov.scot/news/cautious-easing-of-restrictions/\">update on Tuesday 1 June</a>, East Lothian is one of fifteen Scottish mainland local authority areas to move down from Level 2 to Level 1 restrictions. The First Minister confirmed that this will take effect from 00:01 on Saturday 5 June.</p>\n<p>Some other local authority areas, including Edinburgh and Midlothian, will remain in Level 2 while the situation with the virus is monitored closely. You are reminded that travelling between Level 1 and Level 2 areas is permitted.</p>\n<p>This move down to Level 1 means that Maggie’s Bar &amp; Café can now allow up to 8 people, from 3 different households, to sit together indoors, while up to 12 people can sit together outside. Please note that 1875, Starbucks and the main shop will remain closed for now. Further information can be found <a href=\"/{localLink:umb://document/7ac62a9a0ac442c78ae93816a9e60377}\" title=\"Eat and Shop on Campus\">on our website</a>.</p>\n<h2>It’s not too late! 18-29 year olds can still register for their vaccine appointment online</h2>\n<p>As previously mentioned in the Moderator messages dated 25 and 31 May, and on social media, those aged between 18 and 29 can still register to receive for their COVID vaccination appointment online by visiting the <a href=\"https://www.nhsinform.scot/under30register\">NHS Inform website</a>.</p>\n<p>Today is the last day that those within that age group can book their appointment online, so we’d like to take this opportunity to remind colleagues who fall within this age range to register before the end of the day if you haven’t already done so, and also to pass on this message to students.</p>\n<p>Further information can be found on the <a href=\"https://www.studentinformation.gov.scot/coronavirus/self-registration\">Student Information Scotland</a> website.</p>\n<h2>Availability of regular rapid COVID testing for all people in Scotland</h2>\n<p>Do also remember that everyone in Scotland can now order lateral flow tests online or collect them from a test site, for fast twice weekly testing at home (<a href=\"https://www.gov.scot/publications/coronavirus-covid-19-getting-tested/pages/no-covid-symptoms/\"><strong>Find out how to obtain lateral flow test kits</strong></a>). If you have symptoms of coronavirus, you should book a PCR test immediately rather than rely on a lateral flow test (<a href=\"https://www.gov.scot/publications/coronavirus-covid-19-getting-tested/pages/covid-symptoms/\"><strong>More information on how to book a test if you have symptoms</strong></a>).</p>\n<p>Staff Questionnaire on Student Loneliness and Isolation</p>\n<p>Next week will see the launch of our second questionnaire on loneliness and isolation across the student population before and during COVID-19.  While the first questionnaire was disseminated to students, this questionnaire is for staff, and is concerned with strategies and services that may have been deployed to manage students’ experience of loneliness and isolation.  Our key objectives are to raise awareness of the experience, to enhance understanding, and to develop resources to mitigate loneliness and isolation, where these are detrimental to the individual.  The research will contribute to and inform the University’s work under the <a href=\"https://myshare.qmu.ac.uk/academic/sitepages/enhancement%20themes.aspx\">Resilient Learning Communities QAA Enhancement Theme</a>.</p>\n<h2>Graduation update</h2>\n<p>You will have seen further updates for our summer Graduation plans in an email from the Principal earlier this week.</p>\n<p>There is no doubt that an important part of the graduation experience is the wonderful opportunity for families and graduates to connect and celebrate with academic staff who have been involved in their teaching and supported them throughout their learner journey. We would very much like to encourage academic staff to attend the event and, where possible, make arrangements to meet up with graduates and their cohorts. It will undoubtedly enhance the overall student experience and is a fitting way for new graduates to conclude their time at QMU. We can also make arrangements for academic staff to wear their gowns – please give your gown details when you book if Registry does not already hold these.</p>\n<p>In order to allow us to manage the number of people on campus at any one time, <strong>academic staff will need to book their place at the event via our Events team</strong>. We would therefore recommend that, if possible, academic staff liaise with their students/graduating cohorts in an attempt to confirm which timeslot would be most suitable to marry up the appropriate staff with their students. We very much appreciate staff involvement in graduation and wish to avoid a situation where academics attend the celebration but miss out on the opportunity to meet their students. We appreciate that there is no ideal system to facilitate the perfect coordination of staff and students this year, but we can all try to make it work as best we can by avoiding leaving booking until the last minute. We are aware that certain teams have chosen to split up attendance amongst their colleagues making sure that there is always one person from their subject area for the duration of the event on both days.</p>\n<p><strong>Choice of timeslots for graduates and guests on both days:</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>11am – 1pm</li>\n<li>2pm – 4pm</li>\n<li>5pm – 7pm</li>\n</ul>\n<p>It will be essential for all academic staff who plan to attend the graduation celebration to meet with their student groups, to book their place in advance.  We will open registration for academic staff a week after graduate registration has opened so you have time to find out what time slot your students will be attending. <strong>Registration for academic staff will open on Monday 14 June.</strong> Please email <a href=\"mailto:events@qmu.ac.uk\">events@qmu.ac.uk</a> to register. Bookings for academic staff will be dealt with on a first come first served basis. For those staff requiring an academic gown, bookings must be made by Friday 25 June at the very latest.</p>\n<p> </p>\n<p>Malcolm G Cutt</p>\n<p>Director of Operations and Finance</p>"
