      "title": "21 May 2021",
      "content": "<p class=\"x_MsoNormal\">21 May 2021</p>\n<p class=\"x_MsoNormal\"> </p>\n<p class=\"x_MsoNormal\">Dear students,</p>\n<h2>Testing on campus</h2>\n<p class=\"x_MsoNormal\">As you know, today (21<sup>st</sup> May) and on Tuesday (25<sup>th</sup> May) we are running asymptomatic COVID testing for students changing household at the end of semester.  Walk-up appointments are available as well as pre-booked appointments.  If you would like a walk-up appointment (i.e. without a booking), just go to the testing centre reception in 1875 during opening hours. We will be running sessions on both of the days between 12 noon and 2pm. <a rel=\"noopener\" href=\"/{localLink:umb://document/ce8c5f4b067647529811fd507b9beadb}\" target=\"_blank\" title=\"Test\" data-auth=\"NotApplicable\" data-linkindex=\"0\">More information is available on our website.</a> </p>\n<h2><span class=\"lead\">Availability of regular rapid COVID testing for all people in Scotland</span></h2>\n<p>Do also remember that everyone in Scotland can now order lateral flow tests online or collect them from a test site, for fast twice-weekly testing at home.  (<a rel=\"noopener noreferrer\" href=\"https://www.gov.scot/publications/coronavirus-covid-19-getting-tested/pages/no-covid-symptoms/\" target=\"_blank\" data-auth=\"NotApplicable\" data-linkindex=\"1\">Find out how to obtain lateral flow test kits</a>).  If you have symptoms of coronavirus, you should book a PCR test immediately rather than rely on a lateral flow test. (<a rel=\"noopener noreferrer\" href=\"https://www.gov.scot/publications/coronavirus-covid-19-getting-tested/pages/covid-symptoms/\" target=\"_blank\" data-auth=\"NotApplicable\" data-linkindex=\"2\">More information on how to book a test if you have symptoms</a>).</p>\n<h2>Moving into the summer</h2>\n<p>Semester 2 is, of course, now coming to an end, and semester 3 (relevant to a small number of programmes) is soon to begin. Campus Services staff are set to support staff and students involved in semester 3.  </p>\n<p>The Vaccination Centre on campus is expected to be decommissioned in early July. </p>\n<h2>Planning for next semester </h2>\n<p class=\"x_MsoNormal\">Following the Scottish Parliament election, there has been good progress in discussions between the higher education sector and the Scottish Government on planning for the next academic year.  We anticipate that the Scottish Government will publish guidance for universities and colleges on this topic very soon. </p>\n<h2>Graduation </h2>\n<p>There is continued progress on our plans for graduation celebrations, as you will have seen from the message from the Principal on the subject issued this week (on 19 May).</p>\n<p>In short, we have a team of colleagues from across the University who are working hard to shape up an outdoor celebration for both the Class of 2020 and the Class of 2021, which will be held on Tuesday 13<sup>th</sup> and Wednesday 14<sup>th</sup> July. As we do not yet know what restrictions will be placed on outdoor gatherings on these dates, we are currently unable to confirm all details for these events. If you are graduating this year, do keep an eye on the <a rel=\"noopener\" href=\"/{localLink:umb://document/7cfc8bb385d642359966cd749b4be41e}\" target=\"_blank\" title=\"Graduation Celebrations - July 2021\" data-auth=\"NotApplicable\" data-linkindex=\"3\">QMU Graduation</a> page on our website to keep-up-to-date.</p>\n<p>Please be assured that we are doing everything possible to create something memorable to mark the culmination of graduating students’ hard work. At the same time, we need to be mindful that, despite our best efforts, changing government restrictions could impact on our plans and result in us having to alter or scale them down or even, in the worst case, cancel the graduation celebratory event altogether. But we look to the future with positivity, and will focus on trying to make this graduation celebration a reality.</p>\n<p> </p>\n<p class=\"x_MsoNormal\">Malcolm G Cutt</p>\n<p class=\"x_MsoNormal\">Director of Operations and Finance</p>\n<p class=\"x_MsoNormal\"> </p>\n<p class=\"x_MsoNormal\">Dear staff,</p>\n<h2>Testing on campus </h2>\n<p class=\"x_MsoNormal\">As you know, today (21<sup>st</sup> May) and on Tuesday (25<sup>th</sup> May) we are running asymptomatic COVID testing for students changing household at the end of semester.  Walk-up appointments are available as well as pre-booked appointments.  Students seeking a walk-up appointment (i.e. without a booking), should just go to the testing centre reception in 1875 during opening hours. Please note that walk-up appointments are also available for staff. We will be running sessions on both of the days between 12 noon and 2pm. <a rel=\"noopener\" href=\"/{localLink:umb://document/ce8c5f4b067647529811fd507b9beadb}\" target=\"_blank\" title=\"Test\" data-auth=\"NotApplicable\" data-linkindex=\"0\">More information is available on our website</a>.</p>\n<h2><span class=\"lead\">Availability of regular rapid COVID testing for all people in Scotland </span></h2>\n<p>As a member of staff, do remember that you, and everyone else in Scotland, can now order lateral flow tests online or collect them from a test site, for fast twice weekly testing at home.  (<a rel=\"noopener noreferrer\" href=\"https://www.gov.scot/publications/coronavirus-covid-19-getting-tested/pages/no-covid-symptoms/\" target=\"_blank\" data-auth=\"NotApplicable\" data-linkindex=\"1\">Find out how to obtain lateral flow test kits</a>).  If you have symptoms of coronavirus, you should, of course, book a PCR test immediately rather than rely on a lateral flow test. (<a rel=\"noopener noreferrer\" href=\"https://www.gov.scot/publications/coronavirus-covid-19-getting-tested/pages/covid-symptoms/\" target=\"_blank\" data-auth=\"NotApplicable\" data-linkindex=\"2\">More information on how to book a test if you have symptoms</a>).</p>\n<p>Moving into the summer</p>\n<p>Semester 2 is, of course, now coming to an end, and semester 3 (relevant to a small number of programmes) is soon to begin. Campus Services staff are set to support staff and students involved in semester 3. </p>\n<p>Alongside this, there is continued progress on our plans for graduation celebrations, as you will have seen from the message from the Principal on the subject issued this week (on 19 May).</p>\n<p>The Vaccination Centre on campus is expected to be decommissioned in early July.</p>\n<p class=\"x_MsoNormal\">Planning for next semester</p>\n<p class=\"x_MsoNormal\">Following the Scottish Parliament election, there has been good progress in discussions between the higher education sector and the Scottish Government on planning for the next academic year.  We anticipate that the Scottish Government will publish guidance for universities and colleges on this topic very soon.</p>\n<p class=\"x_MsoNormal\">You will have seen the Moderator message yesterday (20 May) on staff return to campus. In that message, we advise that to prepare us for the upcoming academic year, we are putting together a roadmap setting out how the transition back to campus working will take place, and the implications of that for how teams and individuals work.</p>\n<h2>Meetings on Campus</h2>\n<p class=\"x_MsoNormal\">Now we are at Scottish Government’s coronavirus level 2, we can offer a slight relaxation of the rules on meetings on campus.  While staff meetings should continue to be held online wherever possible, you can now hold essential meetings on campus (e.g. one-off academic year review meetings and planning meetings for semester 3 and the 2021/22 academic session).  If you need to take advantage of this relaxation, you will need to:</p>\n<ul>\n<li class=\"x_MsoListParagraph\">Have your Head of Division or Department’s approval, and confirmation that it is essential that the meeting is held face-to-face;</li>\n<li class=\"x_MsoListParagraph\">Book the meeting room in advance (by 3.30pm the preceding working day);</li>\n<li class=\"x_MsoListParagraph\">Adhere to the reduced maximum occupancy limit for each meeting space, which is nine people for classrooms, and is specified in a poster in each meeting space. </li>\n</ul>\n<p class=\"x_MsoNormal\">If you are meeting on campus, you should not use this as an opportunity to gather at tea points or in the open plan work spaces.  If you want to socialise with colleagues, you can do so in groups of up to 8 households (8 people) in the seating outside Maggie’s and across the campus grounds. You can also meet indoors in Maggie’s, in groups of up to 3 households (up to 6 people).  Please do stick to the rules as it puts our Campus Services colleagues in an awkward position if we fail to comply. Thank you.</p>\n<p class=\"x_MsoNormal\"> </p>\n<p class=\"x_MsoNormal\">Malcolm G Cutt</p>\n<p class=\"x_MsoNormal\">Director of Operations and Finance</p>"
    },
