      "content": "<p><strong>14 May</strong></p>\n<p><strong>Students:</strong></p>\n<h2>Further easing of restrictions</h2>\n<p>On 11 May, the First Minister announced significant easing of restrictions across most of Scotland, including Edinburgh and East Lothian, effective from Monday (the 17<sup>th</sup>).</p>\n<p>People will be able to hug their loved ones and meet in private homes as most of mainland Scotland moves to Level 2, with eased restrictions on hospitality, entertainment, education and sport.</p>\n<p>In an acceleration of previous plans, the number of people and households that can meet inside homes in Level 2 has been increased to six people from three households.</p>\n<p>Also from 17 May, anyone entering Scotland from countries on a <a href=\"https://www.gov.scot/publications/coronavirus-covid-19-international-travel-quarantine/pages/red-amber-and-green-list-countries/\">new international travel ‘Green List’</a> will not be required to quarantine on arrival, but will have to take a PCR test for COVID-19. The Green List will initially be the same as that in place for England but will be subject to review based on Scotland’s specific needs.</p>\n<p>In her announcement, the First Minister encouraged us all to use judgment when taking advantage of the relaxations, as close physical contact still carries risk. We might, for example, want to limit the number of people with whom we choose to have close physical contact.</p>\n<p>You can find out more on the <a href=\"https://www.gov.scot/news/next-steps-out-of-lockdown/\">Scottish Government website.</a></p>\n<h2>What this means for QMU</h2>\n<p>This positive announcement has implications for our catering and sports facilities. Changes have been communicated separately by Moderator and social media. You will also find up to date information on the <a href=\"/{localLink:umb://document/7ac62a9a0ac442c78ae93816a9e60377}\" title=\"Eat and Shop on Campus\">Eat and Shop</a> on Campus and <a href=\"/{localLink:umb://document/854bacf0350b4399af7c7ec40cbea646}\" title=\"QMU Sports Centre\">Sports</a> pages on our website.</p>\n<p>In terms of planning for the autumn semester, we continue to work directly with senior Scottish government officials as part of sector-wide discussions on a safe resumption of in-person learning and research activity across the higher education sector.  These discussions include consideration of future arrangements for asymptomatic testing for students and staff, and for student access to vaccination. You can find our working planning assumptions for the 21/22 academic year at QMU on our <a href=\"/{localLink:umb://document/b673e3c08a21451691ec92f364641f89}\" title=\"Coronavirus\">coronavirus website</a>.</p>\n<h2>Booking open for COVID testing for students changing address at the end of semester</h2>\n<p>Earlier this week, booking opened for asymptomatic COVID testing for students changing household at the end of semester.</p>\n<p>We will be running COVID testing sessions on Friday 21 May and Tuesday 25 May, between 12 noon and 2pm. We encourage those participating to take two tests, one on each date, in line with the testing guidance. <strong> </strong>  </p>\n<p>Students living in central Edinburgh can be tested at a University of Edinburgh site, if that suits them better.  <a href=\"/coronavirus/test/student-covid-19-test-booking/\">Details available on our testing website</a>.</p>\n<p>Lateral flow tests are used for this fast testing service. <strong>Please note that if you are an international student returning home, with your airline requiring a PCR test, you will need to obtain such a test privately. </strong></p>\n<h2>Opportunity to participate in a study of student resilience and challenge during COVID-19 lockdown</h2>\n<p>Within QMU, we have a team conducting research focused on loneliness and isolation across the student population, before and during COVID-19. The aim is to explore the experience of loneliness and isolation amongst students and some strategies that may have been used to manage these experiences. The key objectives are to raise awareness of the experience, to enhance understanding, and to develop resources to mitigate loneliness and isolation, where these are detrimental to the individual.  The team would like to hear from you. You can share your experiences through the <a href=\"https://qmupsychology.eu.qualtrics.com/jfe/form/SV_4YZUvj5RQRkNLfg\">survey questionnaire</a> and there is a £50 prize draw to encourage your participation.</p>\n<h2>Thinking of our colleagues in India and Nepal</h2>\n<p>As we enjoy increased freedoms, our thoughts are with students and staff at our partner institutions in India and Nepal, with both countries affected by a devastating coronavirus surge.</p>\n<p> </p>\n<p><strong>Staff:</strong></p>\n<h2>Further easing of restrictions</h2>\n<p>On 11 May, the First Minister announced significant easing of restrictions across most of Scotland, including Edinburgh and East Lothian, effective from Monday (the 17<sup>th</sup>).</p>\n<p>People will be able to hug their loved ones and meet in private homes as most of mainland Scotland moves to Level 2, with eased restrictions on hospitality, entertainment, education and sport.</p>\n<p>In an acceleration of previous plans, the number of people and households that can meet inside homes in Level 2 has been increased to six people from three households.</p>\n<p>Also from 17 May, anyone entering Scotland from countries on a <a href=\"https://www.gov.scot/publications/coronavirus-covid-19-international-travel-quarantine/pages/red-amber-and-green-list-countries/\">new international travel ‘Green List’</a> will not be required to quarantine on arrival, but will have to take a PCR test for COVID-19. The Green List will initially be the same as that in place for England but will be subject to review based on Scotland’s specific needs.</p>\n<p>In her announcement, the First Minister encouraged us all to use judgment when taking advantage of the relaxations, as close physical contact still carries risk. We might, for example, want to limit the number of people with whom we choose to have close physical contact.</p>\n<p>You can find out more on the <a href=\"https://www.gov.scot/news/next-steps-out-of-lockdown/\">Scottish Government website.</a></p>\n<h2>What this means for QMU</h2>\n<p>This positive announcement has implications for our catering and sports facilities. Changes are being communicated by Moderator and social media. You will also find up to date information on the <a href=\"/{localLink:umb://document/7ac62a9a0ac442c78ae93816a9e60377}\" title=\"Eat and Shop on Campus\">Eat and Shop</a> and <a href=\"/{localLink:umb://document/854bacf0350b4399af7c7ec40cbea646}\" title=\"QMU Sports Centre\">Sports</a> pages on our website.</p>\n<p>Until advised otherwise, staff  should continue only to work on campus for essential reasons or if you are unable to do your job effectively from home, and working on campus should be agreed with your line manager. Even when staff need to be on campus, meetings should be held online rather than face to face except in exceptional circumstances. In addition, the need for cleaning etc means that meeting rooms need to be booked in advance.</p>\n<p>If staff, with their line manager’s approval, require to undertake an activity on campus over the next few weeks or months not covered by our <a href=\"https://myshare.qmu.ac.uk/services/campus-commercial-services/covid19/SitePages/Risk%20Assessments.aspx\">institutional risk assessment</a>, our Health and Safety Team (<a href=\"mailto:hs-staff@qmu.ac.uk\">hs-staff@qmu.ac.uk</a>) can provide advice and support.</p>\n<p>In terms of planning for the autumn semester, we continue to work directly with senior Scottish government officials as part of sector wide discussions on a safe resumption of in-person learning and research activity across the higher education sector.  These discussions include consideration of future arrangements for asymptomatic testing for students and staff, and for student access to vaccination. You can find our working planning assumptions for the 21/22 academic year at QMU on our <a href=\"/{localLink:umb://document/b673e3c08a21451691ec92f364641f89}\" title=\"Coronavirus\">coronavirus website</a>.</p>\n<h2>Booking open for COVID testing for students changing address at the end of semester</h2>\n<p>Earlier this week, <a href=\"/coronavirus/test/student-covid-19-test-booking/\">booking opened for asymptomatic COVID testing</a> for students changing household at the end of semester.</p>\n<p>We will be running COVID testing sessions on Friday 21 May and Tuesday 25 May, between 12 noon and 2pm. We encourage those participating to take two tests, one on each date, in line with the testing guidance. <strong> </strong>  </p>\n<p>Students living in central Edinburgh can be tested at a University of Edinburgh site, if that suits them better.  <a href=\"/coronavirus/test/student-covid-19-test-booking/\">Details available on our testing website</a>.</p>\n<p>Lateral flow tests are used for this fast testing service. <strong>Please note that any international student returning home, with their airline requiring a PCR test, will need to obtain such a test privately. </strong></p>\n<h2>Opportunity for students to participate in a study of student resilience and challenge during COVID-19 lockdown</h2>\n<p>Within QMU, we have a team conducting research focused on loneliness and isolation across the student population, before and during COVID-19. The aim is to explore the experience of loneliness and isolation amongst students and some strategies that may have been used to manage these experiences. The key objectives are to raise awareness of the experience, to enhance understanding, and to develop resources to mitigate loneliness and isolation, where these are detrimental to the individual.  If you feel able to, do encourage students to consider sharing their experiences through the <a href=\"https://qmupsychology.eu.qualtrics.com/jfe/form/SV_4YZUvj5RQRkNLfg\">survey questionnaire</a>. There is a £50 prize draw to encourage participation.</p>\n<h2>Thinking of our colleagues in India and Nepal</h2>\n<p>As we enjoy increased freedoms, our thoughts are with students and staff at our partner institutions in India and Nepal, with both countries affected by a devastating coronavirus surge.</p>\n<p> </p>"
