      "contentTypeKey": "216ea22b-01af-4645-8972-5766bbd75b6c",
      "udi": "umb://element/a9cdf3c6819a406994483aca20a19af1",
      "title": "30 April 2021",
      "content": "<p>30 April 2021</p>\n<p> </p>\n<p>Dear students, </p>\n<p aria-level=\"2\">Easing of restrictions </p>\n<p>With the easing of restrictions since Monday, it has been lovely to see people using the outdoor spaces around Maggie’s, while adhering the rules about socialising.  If you need a reminder on what you can and can’t do just now, please see the <a href=\"https://www.gov.scot/publications/coronavirus-covid-19-protection-levels/\">Scottish Government website</a>. </p>\n<p aria-level=\"2\">Availability of coronavirus testing </p>\n<p>With full information on community testing now published on the Scottish Government website, I will take this opportunity to summarise how you can arrange to get a coronavirus test. This information is also on the <a href=\"/{localLink:umb://document/b673e3c08a21451691ec92f364641f89}\" title=\"Coronavirus\">coronavirus FAQs</a> on our website.</p>\n<p><strong>If you have symptoms of c</strong><strong>oronavirus</strong>: you should book a PCR test immediately - you can choose either to have a test sent to your home or to attend a testing site, which are located across Scotland. (<a href=\"https://www.gov.scot/publications/coronavirus-covid-19-getting-tested/pages/covid-symptoms/\">More information on how to book a test if you have symptoms</a>) </p>\n<p><strong>If you do not have symptoms</strong>: everyone in Scotland can now order lateral flow tests online or collect them from a test site, for fast twice weekly testing at home. Around one in three people who have COVID-19 display no symptoms, which is one of the ways it can spread quickly to different people. That’s why being tested is so important. It protects everyone within your household and in our community. (<a href=\"https://www.gov.scot/publications/coronavirus-covid-19-getting-tested/pages/no-covid-symptoms/\">Find out how obtain lateral flow test kits</a>).  </p>\n<p>Alongside this, discussions continue between government and the higher education sector on the introduction of regular COVID testing for students and staff on campus.  We will provide more information on this as soon as we can. </p>\n<p><strong>If you are a student </strong><strong>changing households or addresses</strong>: If you need to return to your term-time address before the end of the academic year, please arrange to have a PCR test before you travel. These are free to arrange and you can find out <a href=\"https://www.nhsinform.scot/illnesses-and-conditions/infections-and-poisoning/coronavirus-covid-19/test-and-protect/coronavirus-covid-19-testing\">how to book a test and where your nearest testing site is by visiting NHS Inform</a>. When booking a test, you should answer 'No' to all questions until you reach the question: 'Why are you asking for a test?' This question should be answered by selecting: 'My local council or health protection team has asked me (or someone I live with) to get a test, even though I do not have symptoms”. After you have travelled to your term-time address, please <a href=\"/coronavirus/test/\">arrange to have a lateral flow test.</a>   </p>\n<p aria-level=\"2\">Coronavirus crisis in India </p>\n<p>All of us will have been shocked over the last few days as we have learned through news reports about the coronavirus crisis in India, with the health system there struggling to cope. With friends, colleagues, students and graduates in India, our thoughts are with everyone affected by this distressing situation.</p>\n<p>Though it might feel that there is little practical that we can do from a distance, I will draw your attention to the UK’s <a href=\"https://www.dec.org.uk/\" title=\"Disasters Emergency Committee\">Disasters Emergency Committee</a> Appeal, to help the most vulnerable facing this devastating surge. If you would like to make a donation, you can do so online.</p>\n<p aria-level=\"2\">STaR Awards </p>\n<p>I will end this message by mentioning the Students’ Union annual STaR Awards (Student Teaching and Representation Awards), which took place earlier this week. During an online broadcast mini-ceremony, student and staff recipients were recognised for their great work and achievements throughout the past year in going above and beyond to enhance the student experience at QMU. The event was also an opportunity to recognise and commemorate the memory of Dr Douglas McBean – who as many of you will know was a much-loved, respected and inspirational lecturer who sadly passed away last year, and in whose name a new award has been created. You can find the STaR award winners listed on the <a href=\"https://www.qmusu.org.uk/top-menu/your-voice/star-awards-results/star-awards-2021\">Students’ Union website</a> and listen to a <a href=\"https://youtu.be/j81U3q3GMzg\">recording of the ceremony</a>. Congratulations to all the winners. </p>\n<p>Malcolm G Cutt </p>\n<p>Director of Operations and Finance </p>\n<p> </p>\n<p>Dear colleagues, </p>\n<p aria-level=\"2\">Easing of restrictions </p>\n<p>With the easing of restrictions since Monday, it has been lovely to see people using the outdoor spaces around Maggie’s while adhering the rules about socialising.  Thank you to all the staff who have worked so hard to re-open catering and sports facilities on campus quickly and safely.  If you need a reminder on what you can and can’t do just now, please see the <a href=\"https://www.gov.scot/publications/coronavirus-covid-19-protection-levels/\">Scottish Government website</a>. </p>\n<p aria-level=\"2\">Availability of coronavirus testing </p>\n<p>With full information on community testing now published on the Scottish Government website, I will take this opportunity to summarise how to get a coronavirus test. This information is also on the FAQs on our website.   </p>\n<p><strong>If you have symptoms of coronavirus</strong>: you should book a PCR test immediately - you can choose either to have a test sent to your home or attend a testing site, which are located across Scotland. (<a href=\"https://www.gov.scot/publications/coronavirus-covid-19-getting-tested/pages/covid-symptoms/\">More information on how to book a test if you have symptoms</a>)</p>\n<p><strong>If you do not have symptoms</strong>: everyone in Scotland can now order lateral flow tests online or collect them from a test site, for twice weekly testing at home. Around one in three people who have COVID-19 display no symptoms, which is one of the ways it can spread quickly to different people. That’s why being tested is so important. It protects everyone within your household and in our community.  (<a href=\"https://www.gov.scot/publications/coronavirus-covid-19-getting-tested/pages/no-covid-symptoms/\">Find out how obtain lateral flow test kits</a>).  </p>\n<p>Alongside this, discussions continue between government and the higher education sector on the introduction of regular COVID testing for students and staff on campus.  We will provide more information on this as soon as we can. </p>\n<p aria-level=\"2\">Coronavirus crisis in India </p>\n<p>All of us will have been shocked over the last few days as we have learned through news reports about the coronavirus crisis in India, with the health system there struggling to cope. With friends, colleagues, students and graduates in India, our thoughts are with everyone affected by this distressing situation. </p>\n<p>Though it might feel that there is little practical that we can do from a distance, I will draw your attention to the UK’s <a href=\"https://www.dec.org.uk/\" title=\"Disasters Emergency Committee\">Disasters Emergency Committee</a> Appeal, to help the most vulnerable facing this devastating surge. If you would like to make a donation, you can do so online.</p>\n<p aria-level=\"2\">Assessments </p>\n<p>On behalf of the Senior Leadership Team, I will take this opportunity to thank all colleagues involved in end of year assessments, and in marking. The online assessments seem to have gone very smoothly. </p>\n<p aria-level=\"2\">Staff stress survey </p>\n<p>If you haven’t yet had the chance to complete the <a href=\"https://qmu.onlinesurveys.ac.uk/stress-2\">stress survey</a>, you have until next Friday (7th May) to do so.  Your responses will help us to identify any areas of concern and to work towards an action plan that will address the impact of work-related stress at the University.  </p>\n<p aria-level=\"2\">STaR Awards </p>\n<p>I’ll end this message by highlighting the Students’ Union annual STaR Awards (Student Teaching and Representation Awards), which took place earlier this week. During an online broadcast mini-ceremony, student and staff recipients were recognised for their great work and achievements throughout the past year in going above and beyond to enhance the student experience at QMU.  The event was also an opportunity to recognise and commemorate the memory of Dr Douglas McBean, our much-loved, and respected colleague who sadly passed away last year, and in whose name a new award has been created. You can find the STaR award winners listed on the <a href=\"https://www.qmusu.org.uk/top-menu/your-voice/star-awards-results/star-awards-2021\">Students’ Union website</a> and listen to a <a href=\"https://youtu.be/j81U3q3GMzg\">recording of the ceremony</a>. Congratulations to all the winners. </p>\n<p> </p>\n<p>Malcolm G Cutt </p>\n<p>Director of Operations and Finance</p>"
    },
