      "title": "23 April 2021",
      "content": "<p>23 April 2021 </p>\n<p> </p>\n<p>Dear students,</p>\n<p aria-level=\"2\">Further easing of restrictions  </p>\n<p>This week, the First Minister confirmed <a href=\"https://www.gov.scot/news/moving-to-level-3/\">details of further easing of restrictions</a>. From Monday (26 April), hospitality venues such as cafés, pubs and restaurants can reopen, along with non-essential retail outlets, and indoor attractions and public buildings such as galleries, museums and libraries. Adults on the shielding list can return to the workplace, if they cannot work from home. </p>\n<p>All parts of Scotland will move to Coronavirus Level 3 from Monday too. The remaining travel restrictions within Scotland will be lifted and travel within the UK will be permitted for any purpose. </p>\n<p>If everyone continues to follow the rules, the First Minister said it is expected that all of Scotland will move to Level 2 on Monday 17 May. </p>\n<p>Knowing the rules and following FACTS </p>\n<p>For more information on what we can and can’t do from Monday (and more information on what is meant by Coronavirus Level 3), see the <a href=\"https://www.gov.scot/publications/coronavirus-covid-19-protection-levels/\">Scottish Government website</a>.  </p>\n<p>To help ensure continued good progress, it is essential that we all continue to follow FACTS, ie:</p>\n<ul>\n<li data-leveltext=\"\" data-font=\"Symbol\" data-listid=\"2\" aria-setsize=\"-1\" data-aria-posinset=\"1\" data-aria-level=\"1\">Wear <strong>F</strong>ace coverings  </li>\n<li data-leveltext=\"\" data-font=\"Symbol\" data-listid=\"2\" aria-setsize=\"-1\" data-aria-posinset=\"2\" data-aria-level=\"1\"><strong>A</strong>void crowded space </li>\n<li data-leveltext=\"\" data-font=\"Symbol\" data-listid=\"2\" aria-setsize=\"-1\" data-aria-posinset=\"3\" data-aria-level=\"1\"><strong>C</strong>leaning surfaces </li>\n<li data-leveltext=\"\" data-font=\"Symbol\" data-listid=\"2\" aria-setsize=\"-1\" data-aria-posinset=\"4\" data-aria-level=\"1\">Maintain <strong>T</strong>wo metre social distancing </li>\n<li data-leveltext=\"\" data-font=\"Symbol\" data-listid=\"2\" aria-setsize=\"-1\" data-aria-posinset=\"4\" data-aria-level=\"1\"><strong>S</strong>elf-isolating if you think you have COVID. </li>\n</ul>\n<p>Please remember the rules on socialising, which limit groups to six people from six households meeting outdoors, with socialising in homes still not allowed. </p>\n<p>In addition, it is important that we all follow the advice of Campus Services staff when on campus.</p>\n<p aria-level=\"2\">Rapid regular coronavirus testing available to all </p>\n<p>From Monday, everyone in Scotland will be able to access rapid coronavirus testing.   </p>\n<p>Lateral flow home test kits will be available to anyone who does not have COVID-19 symptoms. They can be picked up from local walk/drive-through test sites for people to test themselves twice-weekly.</p>\n<p>The expansion is aimed at finding cases that would otherwise go undetected, so those people can self-isolate and avoid transmitting the virus to those around them.</p>\n<p>Very soon, the Scottish Government will publish more information on this on their <a href=\"https://www.gov.scot/publications/coronavirus-covid-19-getting-tested/pages/no-covid-symptoms/\">Community Testing website</a>.  </p>\n<p>Alongside this, discussions continue between government and the higher education sector on the introduction of regular COVID testing for students and staff on campus.  We will provide more information as soon as we can.</p>\n<p>Please remember that if you develop COVID-19 symptoms, you should still book a PCR COVID test through the <a href=\"https://www.gov.uk/get-coronavirus-test\">existing channels</a> and self-isolate immediately. </p>\n<p>What the easing of restrictions means for QMU </p>\n<p>Please continue to attend campus only if you need to.</p>\n<p>Face coverings must still be worn in classrooms and other teaching spaces beyond Monday, in addition to all other communal spaces including the LRC, except by those who are legally exempt for medical reasons.  The requirement to wear face coverings applies at all times, except when you are eating or drinking.  </p>\n<p>You will yesterday have received an email announcing the full re-opening of Maggie’s, with information also to be added to the <a href=\"/campus-life/eat-and-shop-on-campus/\" title=\"Eat and Shop on Campus\">Eat and Shop on Campus</a> page on the QMU website.  The team at Maggie’s are looking forward to welcoming customers back.  Please be aware that there are still strict rules about hospitality. In particular, please note that you will be required to leave your contact details, and that only 2 households (up to 6 people) can sit together indoors, increasing to 6 households (up to 6 people) if you sit outside.</p>\n<p>Our Sports Centre will be opening its doors again at 7am on Monday. The Centre will initially be open for individual gym workouts, in line with Government COVID-19 guidance.  For information about membership, available facilities and other details, please see the <a href=\"/{localLink:umb://document/854bacf0350b4399af7c7ec40cbea646}\" title=\"QMU Sports Centre\">Sports website</a>.  Your exercise session must be booked in advance using our <a href=\"https://sportsbookings.qmu.ac.uk/bookings\">online booking system</a>, which is available now. </p>\n<p aria-level=\"2\">Update on vaccinations for people under 30 </p>\n<p>Finally, you might also be interested to know that the Scottish Government has issued a statement on their <a href=\"https://www.studentinformation.gov.scot/coronavirus\">Student Information Scotland website</a> on the subject of vaccinations. The statement says that the plans for offering vaccines to those under 30 mean that individuals will be offered a first dose before the end of July and a second dose within the recommended timescales (between 3 and 12 weeks after the first dose), supply permitting.  It goes on to say that government recognises that many students move addresses over the summer months and that they are considering flexible arrangements to respond to this.  </p>\n<p> </p>\n<p>Professor Richard Butt </p>\n<p>Deputy Principal </p>\n<p> </p>\n<p>Dear colleagues,</p>\n<p aria-level=\"2\">Further easing of restrictions  </p>\n<p>This week, the First Minister confirmed <a href=\"https://www.gov.scot/news/moving-to-level-3/\">details of further easing of restrictions</a>. From Monday (26 April), hospitality venues such as cafés, pubs and restaurants can reopen, along with non-essential retail outlets and indoor attractions and public buildings such as galleries, museums and libraries. Adults on the shielding list can return to the workplace, if they cannot work from home.</p>\n<p>All parts of Scotland will move to Coronavirus Level 3 from Monday too. The remaining travel restrictions within Scotland will be lifted and travel within the UK will be permitted for any purpose.</p>\n<p>If everyone continues to follow the rules, the First Minister said it is expected that all of Scotland will move to Level 2 on Monday 17 May.</p>\n<p aria-level=\"2\">Knowing the rules and following FACTS </p>\n<p>For more information on what we can and can’t do from Monday (and more information on what is meant by Coronavirus Level 3), see the <a href=\"https://www.gov.scot/publications/coronavirus-covid-19-protection-levels/\">Scottish Government website</a>.</p>\n<p>To help ensure continued good progress, it is essential that we all continue to follow FACTS, ie:</p>\n<ul>\n<li data-leveltext=\"\" data-font=\"Symbol\" data-listid=\"2\" aria-setsize=\"-1\" data-aria-posinset=\"1\" data-aria-level=\"1\">Wear <strong>F</strong>ace coverings  </li>\n<li data-leveltext=\"\" data-font=\"Symbol\" data-listid=\"2\" aria-setsize=\"-1\" data-aria-posinset=\"2\" data-aria-level=\"1\"><strong>A</strong>void crowded space </li>\n<li data-leveltext=\"\" data-font=\"Symbol\" data-listid=\"2\" aria-setsize=\"-1\" data-aria-posinset=\"3\" data-aria-level=\"1\"><strong>C</strong>leaning surfaces </li>\n<li data-leveltext=\"\" data-font=\"Symbol\" data-listid=\"2\" aria-setsize=\"-1\" data-aria-posinset=\"4\" data-aria-level=\"1\">Maintaining <strong>T</strong>wo metre social distancing </li>\n<li data-leveltext=\"\" data-font=\"Symbol\" data-listid=\"2\" aria-setsize=\"-1\" data-aria-posinset=\"5\" data-aria-level=\"1\"><strong>S</strong>elf-isolating if you think you have COVID.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Please remember the rules on socialising, which limit groups to six people from six households meeting outdoors, with socialising in homes still not allowed. </p>\n<p>In addition, it is important that we all follow the advice of Campus Services staff when on campus.</p>\n<p aria-level=\"2\">Rapid regular coronavirus testing available to all </p>\n<p>From Monday, everyone in Scotland will be able to access rapid coronavirus testing.   </p>\n<p>Lateral flow home test kits will be available to anyone who does not have COVID-19 symptoms. They can be picked up from local walk/drive-through test sites for people to test themselves twice-weekly.</p>\n<p>The expansion is aimed at finding cases that would otherwise go undetected, so those people can self-isolate and avoid transmitting the virus to those around them. </p>\n<p>Very soon, the Scottish Government will publish more information on this on their <a href=\"https://www.gov.scot/publications/coronavirus-covid-19-getting-tested/pages/no-covid-symptoms/\">Community Testing website</a>. In turn, as we soon as we can, we will share relevant information with those staff who need to be on campus. </p>\n<p>Alongside this, discussions continue between government and the higher education sector on the introduction of regular COVID testing for students and staff on campus.  We will provide more information as soon as we can.  </p>\n<p>Please remember that if you develop COVID-19 symptoms, you should still book a PCR COVID test through the <a href=\"https://www.gov.uk/get-coronavirus-test\">existing channels</a> and self-isolate immediately.</p>\n<p aria-level=\"2\">What the easing of restrictions means for QMU </p>\n<p>Please remember that, until announced otherwise, staff should only visit campus for essential reasons or if you are unable to do your job effectively from home, and that attendance on campus should be agreed with your line manager. Even when staff need to be on campus, meetings should be held online rather than face to face except in exceptional circumstances. In addition, the need for cleaning etc means that meeting rooms need to be booked in advance.</p>\n<p>Staff who have been shielding are now permitted to return to work on campus.  Before they return, they must discuss this with their line manager to consider all COVID-related safety measures.  </p>\n<p>We have been are keeping the University-wide risk assessment up to date with the easing of restrictions.  You can always find the latest risk assessment on the <a href=\"https://myshare.qmu.ac.uk/services/campus-commercial-services/covid19/SitePages/Risk%20Assessments.aspx\">COVID intranet site</a>. It is a detailed document setting out the range of control measures implemented to protect your health, safety and wellbeing at QMU.</p>\n<p>Face coverings must still be worn in classrooms and other teaching spaces beyond Monday, in addition to all other communal spaces including the LRC, except by those who are legally exempt for medical reasons.  The requirement to wear face coverings applies at all times, except when you are eating or drinking. </p>\n<p>You will yesterday have received an email announcing the full re-opening of Maggie’s, with information also to be added to the <a href=\"/{localLink:umb://document/7ac62a9a0ac442c78ae93816a9e60377}\" title=\"Eat and Shop on Campus\">Eat and Shop on Campus</a> page on the QMU website.  The team at Maggie’s are looking forward to welcoming customers back.  Please be aware that there are still strict rules about hospitality. In particular, please note that you will be required to leave your contact details, and that only 2 households (up to 6 people) can sit together indoors, increasing to 6 households (up to 6 people) if you sit outside.</p>\n<p>Our Sports Centre will be opening its doors again at 7am on Monday. The Centre will initially be open for individual gym workouts, in line with Government COVID-19 guidance.  For information about membership, available facilities and other details, please see the <a href=\"/{localLink:umb://document/854bacf0350b4399af7c7ec40cbea646}\" title=\"QMU Sports Centre\">Sports website</a>.  Your exercise session must be booked in advance using our <a href=\"https://sportsbookings.qmu.ac.uk/bookings\">online booking system</a>, which is available now.</p>\n<p aria-level=\"2\">Update on vaccinations for people under 30 </p>\n<p>You might also be interested to know that the Scottish Government has issued a statement on their <a href=\"https://www.studentinformation.gov.scot/coronavirus\">Student Information Scotland website</a> on the subject of vaccinations. The statement says that the plans for offering vaccines to those under 30 mean that individuals will be offered a first dose before the end of July and a second dose within the recommended timescales (between 3 and 12 weeks after the first dose), supply permitting.  It goes on to say that government recognises that many students move addresses over the summer months and that they are considering flexible arrangements to respond to this.</p>\n<p aria-level=\"2\">Stress survey for staff </p>\n<p>Thank you again to everyone who has completed the <a href=\"https://qmu.onlinesurveys.ac.uk/stress-2\">stress survey</a> so far. If you haven’t completed the survey yet, we encourage you to do so. Your responses will help us to identify any areas of concern and to work towards an action plan that will address the impact of work-related stress at the University. The survey should take approximately 15 minutes to complete and is open until Friday 7 May. </p>\n<p aria-level=\"2\">Praise for the University’s response to COVID </p>\n<p>Finally, you might like to know that attendees at the QMU Community Forum meeting that took place this week were effusive in their praise for the University’s COVID response. One local East Lothian councillor described the University as ‘an oasis of calm’ during the pandemic.  The chair of the Musselburgh and Inveresk Community Council expressed ‘a big thank you’ to the University for ‘incredible’ work during COVID which had been ‘well talked about’ and merited ‘a gold star’.  Thank you to all of you for all you have done, and continue to do. </p>\n<p> </p>\n<p>Professor Richard Butt </p>\n<p>Deputy Principal</p>"
    },
