      "contentTypeKey": "216ea22b-01af-4645-8972-5766bbd75b6c",
      "udi": "umb://element/60e07802d66f4c83a1a97c108366691f",
      "title": "16 April 2021",
      "content": "<p class=\"x_MsoNormal\">16 April 2021</p>\n<p class=\"x_MsoNormal\"> </p>\n<p>Dear students,</p>\n<p aria-level=\"2\">Acceleration of the easing of lockdown </p>\n<p>This week, the <a href=\"https://www.gov.scot/news/accelerated-easing-of-restrictions/\">First Minister announced some acceleration of the easing of lockdown</a>, allowing travel around mainland Scotland from today (Friday) for the purposes of outdoor socialising, recreation and exercise, along with meetings of groups of up to six adults from six households in outdoor settings. While this is all really encouraging, we need to continue to avoid the temptation to meet in larger groups than permitted, and avoid using final classes and assessments as an opportunity for socialising in ways that might breach coronavirus rules. In addition, we all need to be mindful that, under coronavirus law, it is illegal to drink alcohol in any public space, including parks, and that Police have been patrolling areas such as the Meadows area of Edinburgh to ensure compliance. For more information on what you can and cannot do just now, see the <a href=\"https://www.gov.scot/publications/coronavirus-covid-19-protection-levels/\">Scottish Government website</a>.</p>\n<p aria-level=\"2\">Looking ahead to the 21/22 academic year</p>\n<p>Discussions continue between the higher education sector and government on planning assumptions for the 21/22 academic year. In the meantime, you can see our working assumptions on the <a href=\"/{localLink:umb://document/b673e3c08a21451691ec92f364641f89}\" title=\"Coronavirus\">COVID section of the website</a>. </p>\n<p>In partnership with government, we continue to work towards being able to provide regular asymptomatic COVID testing for students and staff in the very near future.  We will provide more information as soon as we can. </p>\n<p>Graduation</p>\n<p>You will have received the message from the Principal expressing our determination to celebrate the success of the graduating class of 2021, and of the class of 2020, but saying, with great regret, that we will be unable to hold the graduation ceremonies and the celebratory event we had planned for the Usher Hall in July this year. As the Principal said, we know all too well how disappointing this will be for graduating students, and for those graduates who missed out last year, which is why we are working to find another way to mark this important milestone in their academic journey, planning to provide them with the opportunity to come together safely, and in an appropriately socially distanced way with their QMU friends, to celebrate their achievements with family and supporters. As the Principal said in his message, we are deeply committed to finding a fitting way to reward the resilience, patience and hard work of our graduating students.</p>\n<p aria-level=\"2\">Wellbeing resources</p>\n<p>With assessments starting next week, do remember the wellbeing resources available to you at the University. Our <a href=\"/{localLink:umb://document/35f6be9d3cfe4664b7ffe6d54165c449}\" title=\"Counselling Service\">Counselling</a> and <a href=\"/{localLink:umb://document/8d2f92c8533d41ec9baa7182c2a76a9b}\" title=\"Wellbeing Service\">Wellbeing</a> teams are providing online/phone support, and face-to-face sessions where appropriate. You can book an appointment either through <a href=\"https://studentcentral.qmu.ac.uk/students/login?ReturnUrl=%2f\">Student Central</a> or by emailing the relevant team. You can also contact your Personal Academic Tutor (names on the Student Portal). You might also want to sign up for <a href=\"/study-here/student-services/togetherall/%22%20/o%20%22togetherall\">Togetherall</a> which is available to you through the University. This is a digital mental health support service which is available online, 24/7, and is completely anonymous so you can express yourself freely and openly. The <a href=\"https://www.qmusu.org.uk/top-menu/advice-support\">Students’ Union</a> can also offer advice and support on academic and welfare matters which is independent from the University. </p>\n<p> </p>\n<p>Malcolm G Cutt </p>\n<p>Director of Operations and Finance </p>\n<p> </p>\n<p>Dear colleagues, </p>\n<p aria-level=\"2\">Acceleration of the easing of lockdown</p>\n<p>This week, the <a href=\"https://www.gov.scot/news/accelerated-easing-of-restrictions/\">First Minister announced some acceleration of the easing of lockdown</a>, allowing travel around mainland Scotland from today (Friday) for the purposes of outdoor socialising, recreation and exercise, along with meetings of groups of up to six adults from six households in outdoor settings. While this is all really encouraging, we all need to continue to avoid the temptation to meet in larger groups than permitted, and encourage students to avoid using final classes and assessments as an opportunity for socialising in ways that might breach coronavirus rules. For more information on what you can and cannot do just now, see the <a href=\"https://www.gov.scot/publications/coronavirus-covid-19-protection-levels/\">Scottish Government website</a>. </p>\n<p>Please remember that, until announced otherwise, staff should only visit campus for essential reasons or if you are unable to do your job effectively from home, and that attendance on campus should be agreed with your line manager. Even when staff need to be on campus, meetings should be held online rather than face to face except in exceptional circumstances. In addition, the need for cleaning etc means that meeting rooms need to be booked in advance.</p>\n<p aria-level=\"2\">Looking ahead to the 21/22 academic year</p>\n<p>Discussions continue between the higher education sector and government on planning assumptions for the 21/22 academic year. In the meantime, you can see our working assumptions on the <a href=\"/{localLink:umb://document/84daaed5f3d04cd09566859f91fb8d90}\" title=\"Applicants\">COVID section of the website</a>. </p>\n<p>In partnership with government, we continue to work towards being able to provide regular asymptomatic COVID testing for students and staff in the very near future.  We will provide more information as soon as we can. </p>\n<p>Graduation</p>\n<p>You will have received the message from the Principal expressing our determination to celebrate the success of the graduating class of 2021, and of the class of 2020, but saying, with great regret, that we will be unable to hold the graduation ceremonies and the celebratory event we had planned for the Usher Hall in July this year. As the Principal said, we know all too well how disappointing this will be for graduating students, and for those graduates who missed out last year, which is why we are working to find another way to mark this important milestone in their academic journey, planning to provide them with the opportunity to come together safely, and in an appropriately socially distanced way with their QMU friends, to celebrate their achievements with family and supporters. As the Principal said in his message, we are deeply committed to finding a fitting way to reward the resilience, patience and hard work of our graduating students.</p>\n<p aria-level=\"2\">Stress survey</p>\n<p>Thank you to everyone who has completed the <a href=\"https://qmu.onlinesurveys.ac.uk/stress-2\">stress survey</a> so far. If you haven’t completed the survey yet, we encourage you to do so. Your responses will help us to identify any areas of concern and to work towards an action plan that will address the impact of work-related stress at the University. The survey should take approximately 15 minutes to complete and is open until Friday 7 May. </p>\n<p>Wellbeing resources</p>\n<p>With assessments starting next week, in today’s COVID message to students, we remind them of the wellbeing resources available to them. Our <a href=\"/{localLink:umb://document/35f6be9d3cfe4664b7ffe6d54165c449}\" title=\"Counselling Service\">Counselling</a> and <a href=\"/{localLink:umb://document/8d2f92c8533d41ec9baa7182c2a76a9b}\" title=\"Wellbeing Service\">Wellbeing</a> teams are providing online/phone support, and face-to-face sessions where appropriate. Students can book an appointment either through <a href=\"https://studentcentral.qmu.ac.uk/students/login?ReturnUrl=%2f\">Student Central</a> or by emailing the relevant team. The <a href=\"https://www.qmusu.org.uk/top-menu/advice-support\">Students’ Union</a> can also offer advice and support on academic and welfare matters which is independent from the University.</p>\n<p>Students (and staff) might also want to sign up for <a href=\"/{localLink:umb://document/e00bacac83974570aebf5fe3550958cf}\" title=\"togetherall\">Togetherall</a> which is available to all of us through the University. This is a digital mental health support service which is available online, 24/7, and is completely anonymous so you can express yourself freely and openly.  You can find more information on wellbeing resources for staff on the <a href=\"https://myshare.qmu.ac.uk/services/campus-commercial-services/covid19/SitePages/Staff%20Wellbeing.aspx\">COVID section of the intranet</a>. </p>\n<p> </p>\n<p>Malcolm G Cutt </p>\n<p>Director of Operations and Finance </p>"
