      "title": "8 April 2021",
      "content": "<p class=\"x_MsoNormal\">8 April 2021</p>\n<p class=\"x_MsoNormal\"> </p>\n<p class=\"x_MsoNormal\">Dear students,  </p>\n<p class=\"x_MsoNormal\">I hope that you had an enjoyable Easter break.</p>\n<p class=\"x_MsoNormal\">‘Stay local’ replaces ‘Stay at home’ advice</p>\n<p class=\"x_MsoNormal\">‘<a rel=\"noopener noreferrer\" href=\"https://www.gov.scot/news/stay-local-from-2-april/\" target=\"_blank\" data-auth=\"NotApplicable\" data-linkindex=\"0\">Stay local’</a> guidance has now replaced the ‘Stay at home’ advice that has been in place since late last year. This means that people across Scotland can now make non-essential journeys within their local authority area, and some non-essential retail and service outlets can open. Please see the Scottish Government website for more information on <a rel=\"noopener noreferrer\" href=\"https://www.gov.scot/coronavirus-covid-19/\" target=\"_blank\" data-auth=\"NotApplicable\" data-linkindex=\"1\">what you can and can’t do now</a>.</p>\n<p class=\"x_MsoNormal\">Find the Scottish Government website for their latest <a href=\"https://www.gov.scot/publications/coronavirus-covid-19-universities-colleges-and-community-learning-and-development-providers/\" title=\"Covid guidance for universities, colleges and student accommodation providers\">guidance for universities, colleges and student accommodation</a>.</p>\n<p class=\"x_MsoNormal\">A reminder about the importance of sticking to the rules and avoiding student house parties</p>\n<p class=\"x_MsoNormal\">Universities across Scotland have been informed by the government’s COVID Safety and Compliance team that Police Scotland has received several reports of student house parties at some universities over the Easter holiday weekend.</p>\n<p class=\"x_MsoNormal\">We would like to remind all QMU students that restrictions on indoor and outdoor gatherings remain in place due to the significant threat to public health that the virus still poses. We realise how disappointing this will be, particularly as the academic year is now beginning to draw to a close. It is crucial, however, that our collective efforts to limit the spread of the virus continue.</p>\n<p class=\"x_MsoNormal\">We would like to thank everyone for their continued patience and understanding and for helping to keep the QMU community safe.</p>\n<p class=\"x_MsoNormal\"><span class=\"lead\">Video message to students from the Principal </span></p>\n<p class=\"x_MsoNormal\">As many of you will have seen on the University’s social media, the Principal has issued a video message to students, focusing on upcoming assessments and support. You can find the message on <a rel=\"noopener noreferrer\" href=\"https://www.facebook.com/QueenMargaretUniversity/videos/1644366235951363\" target=\"_blank\" data-auth=\"NotApplicable\" data-linkindex=\"3\">Facebook</a>.</p>\n<p class=\"x_MsoNormal\"> </p>\n<p class=\"x_MsoNormal\">Malcolm G Cutt</p>\n<p class=\"x_MsoNormal\">Director of Operations and Finance</p>\n<p class=\"x_MsoNormal\"> </p>\n<div class=\"x_WordSection1\">\n<p class=\"x_MsoNormal\"><span class=\"lead\">Dear colleagues, </span></p>\n<p class=\"x_MsoNormal\">I hope that you had an enjoyable Easter break. </p>\n<p class=\"x_MsoNormal\">‘Stay local’ replaces ‘Stay at home’ advice</p>\n<p class=\"x_MsoNormal\">‘<a rel=\"noopener noreferrer\" href=\"https://www.gov.scot/news/stay-local-from-2-april/\" target=\"_blank\" data-auth=\"NotApplicable\" data-linkindex=\"0\">Stay local’</a> guidance has now replaced the ‘Stay at home’ advice that has been in place since late last year. This means that people across Scotland can now make non-essential journeys within their local authority area, and some non-essential retail and service outlets can open. Please see the Scottish Government website for more information on <a rel=\"noopener noreferrer\" href=\"https://www.gov.scot/coronavirus-covid-19/\" target=\"_blank\" data-auth=\"NotApplicable\" data-linkindex=\"1\">what you can and can’t do now</a>.</p>\n<p class=\"x_MsoNormal\">Staff stress survey </p>\n<p class=\"x_MsoNormal\">QMU is committed to protecting the health, safety and wellbeing of our employees, and we acknowledge that these extraordinary circumstances and rapidly changing situations may be stressful for some members of staff.</p>\n<p class=\"x_MsoNormal\">April is National Stress Awareness Month in the UK, so we can think of no better time to raise awareness of work-related stress, and kindly ask you to tell us about your experience of stress at QMU.</p>\n<p class=\"x_MsoNormal\">A <a rel=\"noopener noreferrer\" href=\"https://qmu.onlinesurveys.ac.uk/stress-2\" target=\"_blank\" data-auth=\"NotApplicable\" data-linkindex=\"4\">survey</a> is now available to all staff. Your responses will help us identify any areas of concern and work towards an action plan that will control the impact of work-related stress at the University. The survey should take approximately 15 minutes to complete.</p>\n<p class=\"x_MsoNormal\">We would be grateful for your participation.</p>\n<p class=\"x_MsoNormal\"><span class=\"lead\">Video message to students from the Principal </span></p>\n<p class=\"x_MsoNormal\">As many of you will have seen on the University’s social media, the Principal has issued a video message to students, focusing on upcoming assessments and support. You can find the message on <a rel=\"noopener noreferrer\" href=\"https://www.facebook.com/QueenMargaretUniversity/videos/1644366235951363\" target=\"_blank\" data-auth=\"NotApplicable\" data-linkindex=\"5\">Facebook</a>.</p>\n<p class=\"x_MsoNormal\"> </p>\n<p class=\"x_MsoNormal\">Malcolm G Cutt</p>\n<p class=\"x_MsoNormal\">Director of Operations and Finance</p>\n</div>\n<p class=\"x_MsoNormal\"> </p>"
    },
    {
      "contentTypeKey": "216ea22b-01af-4645-8972-5766bbd75b6c",
      "udi": "umb://element/b27fb4ee3cb84b9cb0b0631b014f96d2",
      "title": "26 March 2021",
      "content": "<p>26 March 2021</p>\n<p> </p>\n<p>Dear students,</p>\n<p>In this, the anniversary week of the start of the first UK COVID lockdown, all of us in the Senior Leadership Team are particularly conscious of the myriad of challenges that all of you have faced in the last year. </p>\n<p>Reminder of Easter Closure dates: Friday 2 April and Monday 5 April (Good Friday and Easter Monday)</p>\n<p>Please remember that as part of our efforts to support staff health and wellbeing, 2 and 5 April have been designated closure dates.  This means that, with a few exceptions, staff will not be available on these dates.</p>\n<p>Guidance on student travel over Easter and other updates from Government</p>\n<p>The Minister for Further Education, Higher Education and Skills has this week issued a letter {link no longer available} to students.  In it, he advises that students should not travel home during the Easter break, unless it is for an essential purpose. </p>\n<p>If you do need to travel for essential purposes, he advises that you should use available testing facilities to test before changing household (with us, this is currently <a href=\"/{localLink:umb://document/ce8c5f4b067647529811fd507b9beadb}\" title=\"Test\">through the University of Edinburgh</a>)  and, where possible, to use a Community Testing Site to test again once the household change has been made. Prior to returning after the Easter break, and ahead of any change of household, you can now book a PCR test through the Department for Health &amp; Social Care online booking portal. More information on this is available on the <a href=\"https://www.studentinformation.gov.scot/coronavirus/term-two\">section of the  Student Information Scotland website concerned with semester two return</a>, in the sub-section headed ‘Student accommodation/Testing’.</p>\n<p>The Minister also sets out the current status with the phased return of student but, as QMU plans are already aligned with government advice, this does not mean any changes to current arrangements for our students.   He also refers to plans to roll out regular COVID testing for students and staff. As and when we have more information on this, we will share it with you.  In addition, he provides information on funding for students who need to extend or repeat courses and placements because of COVID.</p>\n<p>Next steps on easing lockdown</p>\n<p>The Scottish Government and higher education sector representatives have been liaising closely on the specific impacts on university operations of the key milestones in the <a href=\"https://www.gov.scot/news/timetable-for-further-lockdown-easing/\">Scottish Government’s timetable for easing lockdown</a>. We will share more information as and when it becomes available. </p>\n<p>Use of the Scottish Government’s Coronavirus Student Discretionary Funds</p>\n<p>You might appreciate an update on use of the discretionary student funding released by the Scottish Government to mitigate the impacts of COVID. To date, over 300 students have received awards from the fund with a large number of applications still being processed. This includes awards to student groups not normally eligible for such funding including international, EU &amp; Nursing students. Applications to the fund are now closed, but students will continue to be supported by established discretionary and international hardship funds.  I extend my sincere thanks to those staff in Student Services and in the Finance Office team who have worked so hard to enable distribution of these extra payments. </p>\n<p>More funding announcements</p>\n<p>The Scottish Government has announced <a href=\"https://www.gov.scot/news/over-gbp-8-million-for-healthcare-students/\">new funding for universities to help enable healthcare students to access alternative clinical placements</a> to support their practical education disrupted by coronavirus. We are awaiting further specific details for QMU, but aim to continue some of the innovative practices we have initiated in the last year, to sustain practice based learning.</p>\n<p>Next update</p>\n<p>Unless there is anything urgent to report, we will update you again after Easter, rather than at the end of next week, given the closure dates.   </p>\n<p> </p>\n<p>Malcolm G Cutt</p>\n<p>Director of Operations and Finance</p>\n<p> </p>\n<p>Dear colleagues,</p>\n<p>In this, the anniversary week of the start of the first UK COVID lockdown, all of us in the Senior Leadership Team are particularly conscious of the myriad of challenges that all of you have faced in the last year. </p>\n<p>Easter Closure dates: Friday 2 April and Monday 5 April (Good Friday and Easter Monday) </p>\n<p>Please remember that, as part of our efforts to support staff health and wellbeing, 2 and 5 April have been designated closure dates.  Thank you to those essential staff who are required to work on these dates (such colleagues will have been advised by their line manager, and alternative arrangements have been put in place to ensure that they also receive a benefit).</p>\n<p>Next steps on easing lockdown</p>\n<p>The Scottish Government and higher education sector representatives have been liaising closely on the specific impacts on university operations of the key milestones in the <a href=\"https://www.gov.scot/news/timetable-for-further-lockdown-easing/\">Scottish Government’s timetable for easing lockdown</a>. We will share more information as and when it becomes available.  Discussions also continue between the Scottish Government and the sector on planning assumptions for the autumn semester, including consideration of scenarios on the anticipated level of physical distancing.</p>\n<p>Use of Scottish Government’s Coronavirus Student Discretionary Funds</p>\n<p>You might appreciate an update on use of the discretionary student funding released by the Scottish Government to mitigate the impacts of COVID. To date, over 300 students have received awards from the fund with a large number of applications still being processed. This includes awards to student groups not normally eligible for such funding including international, EU &amp; Nursing students. Applications to the fund are now closed, but students will continue to be supported by established discretionary and international hardship funds.  I extend my sincere thanks to those staff in Student Services and in the Finance Office team who have worked so hard to enable distribution of these extra payments. </p>\n<p>More funding announcements</p>\n<p>The Scottish Government has announced <a href=\"https://www.gov.scot/news/over-gbp-8-million-for-healthcare-students/\">new funding for universities to help enable healthcare students to access alternative clinical placements</a> to support their practical education disrupted by coronavirus. We are awaiting further specific details for QMU, but aim to continue some of the innovative practices we have initiated in the last year, to sustain practice based learning.</p>\n<p>More broadly on funding, this week the SFC announced additional funding to universities to mitigate the financial impacts of COVID.  SFC also announced initial funding allocations for 2021/22.  In both cases, the impacts for QMU look positive, based on our initial review, but we are continuing to work through the details. </p>\n<p>Guidance on student travel over Easter and other updates from Government</p>\n<p>The Minister for Further Education, Higher Education and Skills has this week issued a letter {link no longer available) to students.  In it, he advises that students should not travel home during the Easter break, unless it is for an essential purpose. </p>\n<p>If students do need to travel for essential purposes, he advises that they should use available testing facilities to test before changing household (with us, this is currently <a href=\"/coronavirus/test/\">through the University of Edinburgh</a>)  and, where possible, to use a Community Testing Site to test again once the household change has been made. Prior to returning after the Easter break, and ahead of any change of household, students can now book a PCR test through the Department for Health &amp; Social Care online booking portal. More information on this is available on the <a href=\"https://www.studentinformation.gov.scot/coronavirus/term-two\">section of the  Student Information Scotland website concerned with semester two return</a>, in the sub-section headed ‘Student accommodation/Testing’.</p>\n<p>The Minister also sets out the current status with the phased return of student but, as QMU plans are already aligned with government advice, this does not mean any changes to current arrangements for our students.   He also refers to plans to roll out regular COVID testing for students and staff. As and when we have more information on this, we will share it with you.  In addition, he provides information on funding for students who need to extend or repeat courses and placements because of COVID.</p>\n<p>UCEA and trade union joint statement on vaccinations for staff</p>\n<p>You will remember that in a previous update, I emphasised that we encourage all staff to take the opportunity of a COVID vaccination when it is offered to you. As I indicated, you are entitled to reasonable time off during your normal working hours to attend medical appointments, including an appointment to receive your vaccination. When you receive your invitation, please inform your manager of the time and date of your appointment.  You might also like to note that UCEA (the Universities &amp; Colleges Employers’ Association, of which QMU is a member) and the five sector HE trade unions have this week agreed a <a href=\"https://www.ucea.ac.uk/library/publications/principles-for-working-safely-on-campus-during-the-coronavirus-covid-19-pandemic/\">joint statement on vaccinations for staff</a>. </p>\n<p>Next update</p>\n<p>Unless there is anything urgent to report, I will update you again after Easter, rather than at the end of next week, given the closure dates.  I do hope that you enjoy the Easter break.</p>\n<p> </p>\n<p>Malcolm G Cutt</p>\n<p>Director of Operations and Finance</p>"
