      "title": "19 March 2021",
      "content": "<p>19 March 2021</p>\n<p> </p>\n<p>Dear students, </p>\n<p>First Minister’s announcement on next steps out of lockdown </p>\n<p>In an update to the Scottish Parliament on Tuesday, the First Minister set out <a href=\"https://www.gov.scot/news/timetable-for-further-lockdown-easing/\">next steps out of lockdown</a>. She made the point that all steps are dependent on progress on vaccination and on suppressing the virus, and emphasised the need for continued care and caution. </p>\n<p>‘Stay at Home’ regulations will be lifted on 2 April and replaced with guidance to ‘Stay Local’ (ie within your council area), with more services including hairdressers, garden centres and non-essential click and collect services able to open from 5 April. It is anticipated that as of 26 April, all mainland Scotland areas will be designated as level 3 areas for the purposes of coronavirus restrictions. This would mean a further relaxation of the restrictions, including freedom to travel within mainland Scotland and perhaps to the rest of the UK, opening of museums, galleries and tourist destinations and some (mainly outdoor) hospitality. </p>\n<p aria-level=\"2\">What this means for QMU </p>\n<p>The Senior Leadership Team and Business Continuity Group are working through the implications of these possible relaxations for the University.  Any possible increased opportunities for students to interact face-to-face on campus will be communicated at programme level, and working from home for staff, other than in cases where staff have been advised that they need to be present on campus, remains the default position for now.  We will let you know through future COVID updates about further opening up of catering facilities from 26 April and any relaxations in the current adaptations to LRC use. </p>\n<p>The Students’ Union has been looking into the implications of the previously announced relaxations on outdoor non-contact sport.  Unfortunately, as there are still restrictions preventing students from crossing local authority boundaries, it is still very challenging to facilitate sport right now. </p>\n<p aria-level=\"2\">Guidance on student travel over Easter </p>\n<p>As only essential travel beyond your local authority area will be allowed at Easter time, the Scottish Government is planning to issue travel guidance for students. We will share this guidance as soon as we have it. </p>\n<p aria-level=\"2\">Senate decisions on assessment regulations, examination boards and the start of Academic Year 2021/22 </p>\n<p>Senate has approved extension of the University’s current <a href=\"/{localLink:umb://document/e9f078ecf44140bda12e1de86b67d0a5}\" title=\"Updated Assessment Regulations\">emergency regulations</a> to ensure continued fairness, equity and integrity in decisions concerning student academic progress. This means that these regulations will continue for the remainder of academic year 2020/21. </p>\n<p>Senate also agreed to extend the period of time over which Boards of Examiners can be held during the COVID pandemic. This means that some students may receive their exam results a little later than originally planned. The published Academic Calendar for Session 2020-21 advises students and staff that assessment, progression and award decisions will be published on 14 June 2021.  Assessment results will now be released by 28 June 2021 at the latest. Programme and cohort marks approved by Boards of Examiners before this date will be released to students as soon as possible.  This means that, for this academic year, student assessment results will not be released simultaneously from all Boards of Examiners on a single date.    </p>\n<p>For COVID-related reasons, Senate also approved a delay to the start of academic year 2021/22 with induction week starting Monday 13 September 2021 and Semester 1 commencing on Monday 20 September 2021. The start of Semester 2 in academic year 2021/22 will also be delayed and will commence on Monday 17 January 2022.  </p>\n<p> </p>\n<p>While there is still quite a long road to travel, I hope you, like me, feel cheered by the beautiful spring weather we’ve been enjoying and the prospect of easing of restrictions and a gradual return to something more like normality. </p>\n<p> </p>\n<p>Malcolm G Cutt </p>\n<p>Director of Operations and Finance </p>\n<p> </p>\n<p>Dear colleagues,</p>\n<p aria-level=\"2\">First Minister’s announcement on next steps out of lockdown </p>\n<p>In an update to the Scottish Parliament on Tuesday, the First Minister set out <a href=\"https://www.gov.scot/news/timetable-for-further-lockdown-easing/\">next steps out of lockdown</a>. She made the point that all steps are dependent on progress on vaccination and on suppressing the virus, and emphasised the need for continued care and caution. </p>\n<p>‘Stay at Home’ regulations will be lifted on 2 April and replaced with guidance to ‘Stay Local’ (ie within your council area), with more services including hairdressers, garden centres and non-essential click and collect services able to open from 5 April. It is anticipated that as of 26 April, all mainland Scotland areas will be designated as level 3 areas for the purposes of coronavirus restrictions. This would mean a further relaxation of the restrictions, including freedom to travel within mainland Scotland and perhaps to the rest of the UK, opening of museums, galleries and tourist destinations and some (mainly outdoor) hospitality. </p>\n<p>What this means for QMU </p>\n<p>The Senior Leadership Team and Business Continuity Group are working through the implications of these possible relaxations for the University.  Any possible increased opportunities for students to interact face-to-face on campus will be communicated at programme level, and working from home for staff, other than in cases where staff have been advised that they need to be present on campus, remains the default position for now.  We will let you know through future COVID updates about further opening up of catering facilities from 26 April and any relaxations in the current adaptations to LRC use. </p>\n<p>The Students’ Union has been looking into the implications of the previously announced relaxations on outdoor non-contact sport.  Unfortunately, as there are still restrictions preventing students from crossing local authority boundaries, it is still very challenging to facilitate sport right now. </p>\n<p aria-level=\"2\">Guidance on student travel over Easter </p>\n<p>As only essential travel beyond your local authority area will be allowed at Easter time, the Scottish Government is planning to issue travel guidance for students. We will share this guidance as soon as we have it. </p>\n<p aria-level=\"2\">Senate decisions on assessment regulations, examination boards and the start of Academic Year 2021/22 </p>\n<p>Senate has approved extension of the University’s current <a href=\"/{localLink:umb://document/e9f078ecf44140bda12e1de86b67d0a5}\" title=\"Updated Assessment Regulations\">emergency regulations</a> to ensure continued fairness, equity and integrity in decisions concerning student academic progress. This means that these regulations will continue for the remainder of academic year 2020/21. </p>\n<p>Senate also agreed to extend the period of time over which Boards of Examiners can be held during the COVID pandemic. This means that some students may receive their exam results a little later than originally planned. The published Academic Calendar for Session 2020-21 advises students and staff that assessment, progression and award decisions will be published on 14 June 2021.  Assessment results will now be released by 28 June 2021 at the latest. Programme and cohort marks approved by Boards of Examiners before this date will be released to students as soon as possible.  This means that, for this academic year, student assessment results will not be released simultaneously from all Boards of Examiners on a single date.</p>\n<p>For COVID-related reasons, Senate also approved a delay to the start of academic year 2021/22 with induction week starting Monday 13 September 2021 and Semester 1 commencing on Monday 20 September 2021. The start of Semester 2 in academic year 2021/22 will also be delayed and will commence on Monday 17 January 2022.  </p>\n<p>Looking ahead to the autumn semester</p>\n<p>The Senior Leadership Team has already been considering carefully what assumptions we can make about which COVID restrictions might extend into the autumn semester.  Helpfully, the Scottish Government is engaging with the higher education sector on planning assumptions, which will help to ensure that there is a consistent approach.  Student Experience Committee and Senate have had initial discussions about the implications of these assumptions for the delivery of learning and teaching in the autumn semester. </p>\n<p> </p>\n<p>While there is still quite a long road to travel, I hope you, like me, feel cheered by the beautiful spring weather we’ve been enjoying and the prospect of easing of restrictions and a gradual return to something more like normality. </p>\n<p> </p>\n<p>Malcolm G Cutt </p>\n<p>Director of Operations and Finance </p>"
