      "title": "12 March 2021",
      "content": "<p>12 March 2021</p>\n<p> </p>\n<p>Dear students, </p>\n<p aria-level=\"2\">First Minister’s update </p>\n<p>In her update to the Scottish Parliament on Tuesday, the First Minister announced a <a href=\"https://www.gov.scot/news/changes-to-level-4-restrictions/\">cautious acceleration of lockdown easing</a>. Notably, from today (Friday) up to four adults from two households can meet locally in any outdoor space, including in private gardens, for social and recreational purposes. </p>\n<p>Outdoor non-contact sports and group exercise will also resume for adults in groups of up to 15 people from today. Our Students’ Union have been working fast to find out what this means for student sports and will make appropriate arrangements as soon as possible.  </p>\n<p aria-level=\"2\">Reminder to wear face coverings on campus </p>\n<p>Students and staff have reported that some people seem to be forgetting to wear a face covering on campus.  If you do need to be on campus, please remember that, as required by Scottish Government regulations, face coverings must now be worn in classrooms and other teaching spaces, in addition to all other communal spaces, including the LRC, except by those who are legally exempt for medical reasons.   </p>\n<p>Face coverings will continue to be required in classrooms and other teaching spaces until we return to the Scottish Government’s COVID Level 3 or lower. The requirement to wear face coverings applies at all times, except when you are eating or drinking.  </p>\n<p>As we all struggle to remember the rules from time to time, none of us should feel hesitant about reminding anyone else to wear a face covering, or to keep their distance. </p>\n<p>QMYOU magazine: celebrating your efforts responding to COVID  </p>\n<p>Finally, if you haven’t seen it already, you might want to check out the latest issue of QMYOU, the magazine for friends of the University, which features a number of stories on how students, staff and alumni have responded to COVID.  You can <a href=\"/{localLink:umb://document/02401f4ca909431993744ba87ae5b360}\" title=\"Magazine\">find key articles from the magazine on our website</a> or view the full publication on <a href=\"https://view.joomag.com/qmyou-alumni-magazine-issue-88-march-2021/0385538001614872899?short&amp;\">Joomag</a>. </p>\n<p> </p>\n<p>Professor Richard Butt </p>\n<p>Deputy Principal </p>\n<p> </p>\n<p>Dear Colleagues,</p>\n<p aria-level=\"2\">First Minister’s update </p>\n<p>In her update to the Scottish Parliament on Tuesday, the First Minister announced a <a href=\"https://www.gov.scot/news/changes-to-level-4-restrictions/\">cautious acceleration of lockdown easing</a>. Notably, from today (Friday) up to four adults from two households can meet locally in any outdoor space, including in private gardens, for social and recreational purposes. </p>\n<p>Outdoor non-contact sports and group exercise will also resume for adults in groups of up to 15 people from today. Our Students’ Union have been working fast to find out what this means for student sports and will make appropriate arrangements as soon as possible.   </p>\n<p aria-level=\"2\">Home working e-learning module for staff (WorkRite) </p>\n<p>You should have received an email from WorkRite, and our health and safety adviser, Mike Kennedy, with a link to a new e-learning module entitled “QMU Homeworking”. This module has been created to provide all staff with the knowledge and guidance necessary to self-assess their current home working environment, identify any potential hazards, and implement reasonable and practicable solutions. Completing this module is mandatory for all those working from home and only takes a few minutes to complete. Please use your QMU email address, and click on the “forgot password” option to create a new password on first log in.  If you experience any difficulties accessing the system, please email the health and safety team – <a href=\"mailto:hs-staff@qmu.ac.uk\">hs-staff@qmu.ac.uk</a>, </p>\n<p aria-level=\"2\">Face coverings on campus</p>\n<p>Students and staff have reported that some people seem to be forgetting to wear a face covering on campus.  As required by Scottish Government regulations, face coverings must now be worn in classrooms and other teaching spaces, in addition to all other communal spaces, including the LRC, except by those who are legally exempt for medical reasons.  </p>\n<p>Face coverings will continue to be required in classrooms and other teaching spaces until we return to the Scottish Government’s COVID Level 3 or lower. The requirement to wear face coverings applies at all times, except when you are eating or drinking.</p>\n<p>As we all struggle to remember the rules from time to time, none of us should feel hesitant about reminding anyone else to wear a face covering, or to keep their distance. </p>\n<p aria-level=\"2\">QMYOU magazine: celebrating your efforts responding to COVID  </p>\n<p>Finally, if you haven’t seen it already, you might want to check out the latest issue of QMYOU, the magazine for friends of the University, which features a number of stories on how students, staff and alumni have responded to COVID.  You can <a href=\"/{localLink:umb://document/02401f4ca909431993744ba87ae5b360}\" title=\"Magazine\">find key articles from the magazine on our website</a> or view the full publication on <a href=\"https://view.joomag.com/qmyou-alumni-magazine-issue-88-march-2021/0385538001614872899?short&amp;\">Joomag</a>. </p>\n<p> </p>\n<p>Professor Richard Butt </p>\n<p>Deputy Principal </p>"
    },
