      "title": "05 March 2021",
      "content": "<p>5 March 2021</p>\n<p> </p>\n<p>STUDENT MESSAGE </p>\n<p>Dear students,</p>\n<p aria-level=\"2\">Latest update from the Scottish Government </p>\n<p>In her <a href=\"https://www.gov.scot/news/phase-2-of-schools-return/\">COVID update</a> to parliament on Tuesday, the First Minister said that all remaining primary school children will return to school full-time from 15 March, with all secondary pupils returning on a part-time basis from that date. I am sure that this will be welcome news for all students with children affected.  There was no further update on higher or further education in the First Minister’s speech. </p>\n<p aria-level=\"2\">LRC access, and academic writing support  </p>\n<p>I will take this opportunity to remind students, including those undertaking dissertations, that the Learning Resource Centre (LRC) remains open to those who need to use it, subject to the <a href=\"https://www.studentinformation.gov.scot/coronavirus/term-two\">Scottish Government’s coronavirus guidance</a>. You will need to book a space to study in the library. Information on this and other COVID adaptations are available on the <a href=\"/{localLink:umb://document/71b99825061d4a2e8bd48daeb9d7cfe2}\" title=\"Library\">library website</a>.    </p>\n<p>Level four students currently working on their dissertations and final year projects might also like to note that they can access <a href=\"/study-here/learning-facilities/it-services/learning-and-technologies/studiosity-academic-writing-feedback-queen-margaret-university/\">Studiosity</a>, a free external online service accessed via the Hub that provides 24/7 constructive feedback on key elements of academic writing. Studiosity will review your draft work and give you quick feedback on how to improve your academic writing style and structure.  </p>\n<p aria-level=\"2\">New arrangements for COVID testing for students returning to University </p>\n<p>The Scottish Government is asking that students returning to the University (while complying with <a href=\"https://www.studentinformation.gov.scot/coronavirus/term-two\">coronavirus restrictions</a>) obtain a PCR test (free of charge) before they change address. For more information, including the steps you need to take to order your PCR test, see the <a href=\"https://www.studentinformation.gov.scot/coronavirus/term-two\">section of the  Student Information Scotland website concerned with semester two return</a>, in the sub-section headed ‘Student accommodation/Testing’.  </p>\n<p>In short, the process is that you request your test through the UK-wide <a href=\"https://www.nhsinform.scot/illnesses-and-conditions/infections-and-poisoning/coronavirus-covid-19/test-and-protect/coronavirus-covid-19-testing\">existing arrangements</a>. When booking a test, you should answer ‘No’ to all questions until you reach the question: ‘Why are you asking for a test?’ This question should be answered by selecting: ‘My local council or health protection team has asked me (or someone I live with) to get a test, even though I do not have symptoms.’ </p>\n<p>Financial support for students facing financial difficulties: Coronavirus Discretionary Fund </p>\n<p>Do remember that the University has received a substantial addition to our funds to help support any student, regardless of their fee category, who faces financial difficulties caused by COVID. The reasons could include being unable to secure rent rebates from landlords and difficulties in finding part-time employment, but all reasons for applying will be considered.<a href=\"/{localLink:umb://document/a33d92be97574482967def19ff8a302f}\" title=\"Student Services\"> For more information, and to apply, see the Funding Service website</a>.  While we continue to ask that you apply before 25 March wherever possible, applications will be considered after this date until the fund has been fully spent. Furthermore, the Scottish Government has now agreed that Scottish and RUK Nursing and Midwifery students, who were previously excluded, can now apply to this scheme.  </p>\n<p aria-level=\"2\">Graduate Route visa information for international students </p>\n<p>The new Graduate Route visa for international students will open for applications from 1 July. The UK Government’s Home Office has also revised the date by which international students must be in the UK in order to take advantage of the scheme. As such, the previous 6 April date will be removed and replaced with a new date of 21 June.  Further details are available on a <a href=\"https://homeofficemedia.blog.gov.uk/2019/10/14/fact-sheet-graduate-immigration-route/\">Home Office Factsheet</a>.  </p>\n<p aria-level=\"2\">Stories of COVID project at QMU: online exhibition opens </p>\n<p>You might have seen coverage of the <a href=\"/{localLink:umb://document/7ba6f97248bf49968a689853aa896dec}\" title=\"Stories of Covid - Digital Instructions\">Stories of COVID</a> project at QMU on social media or in the Edinburgh Evening News this week.  Coverage focused on the <a href=\"https://www.artsteps.com/view/6022d811d15c2317e4bdf264\">online exhibition</a> associated with the project that captures real life experiences of staff, students and the wider university community during the first lockdown period in 2020.</p>\n<p> </p>\n<p>Have a good weekend, the first weekend of meteorological spring.</p>\n<p> </p>\n<p>Malcolm G Cutt </p>\n<p>Director of Operations and Finance </p>\n<p>  </p>\n<p>STAFF MESSAGE </p>\n<p>Dear colleagues </p>\n<p aria-level=\"2\">Latest update from the Scottish Government  </p>\n<p>In her <a href=\"https://www.gov.scot/news/phase-2-of-schools-return/\">COVID update</a> to parliament on Tuesday, the First Minister said that all remaining primary school children will return to school full-time from 15 March, with all secondary pupils returning on a part-time basis from that date. I am sure that this will be welcome news for all staff and students with children affected.  There was no further update on higher or further education in the First Minister’s speech. </p>\n<p>Working Safety on Campus e-learning module now available to all staff </p>\n<p>The online ‘Working Safely on Campus’ e-learning module (accessed through your <a href=\"https://app.workrite.co.uk/SecureLogin/SecureLogin.aspx\">WorkRite Login</a>) is now available to all staff, not just those registered as currently working on campus.  It takes just 10 minutes to complete and is designed to ensure that you are familiar with the COVID workplace adaptations we have implemented to keep you safe, and your role and responsibilities while on campus.  When logging in for the first time, please click on the “Forgot Password” link to create a new password.  </p>\n<p>Please remember that staff should only visit campus for essential reasons or if you are unable to do your job from home, and that attendance on campus should be agreed with your line manager.  </p>\n<p>Any questions or difficulties logging into the system should be directed to <a href=\"mailto:HR-Staff@qmu.ac.uk\">HR-Staff@qmu.ac.uk</a>.  </p>\n<p aria-level=\"2\">LRC access, and academic writing support </p>\n<p>In today’s COVID update for students, we remind students, including those undertaking dissertations, that the Learning Resource Centre (LRC) remains open to those who need to use it, subject to the <a href=\"https://www.studentinformation.gov.scot/coronavirus/term-two\">Scottish Government’s coronavirus guidance</a>. Students will need to book a space to study in the library. Information on this and other COVID adaptations are available on the <a href=\"/{localLink:umb://document/66bed97569a0485ba7eb1ff03097a3d2}\" title=\"Learning Facilities\">library website</a>.   </p>\n<p>We also point out that level four students currently working on their dissertations and final year projects can access <a href=\"/study-here/learning-facilities/it-services/learning-and-technologies/studiosity-academic-writing-feedback-queen-margaret-university/\">Studiosity</a>, a free external online service accessed via the Hub that provides 24/7 constructive feedback on key elements of academic writing.  </p>\n<p aria-level=\"2\">New arrangements for COVID testing for students returning to University </p>\n<p>The Scottish Government is asking that students returning to the University (while complying with <a href=\"https://www.studentinformation.gov.scot/coronavirus/term-two\">coronavirus restrictions</a>) obtain a PCR test (free of charge) before they change address. For more information  including the steps students need to take to order a PCR test, see the <a href=\"https://www.studentinformation.gov.scot/coronavirus/term-two\">section of the  Student Information Scotland website concerned with semester two return</a>, in the sub-section headed ‘Student accommodation/Testing. </p>\n<p>Financial support for students facing financial difficulties: Coronavirus Discretionary Fund </p>\n<p>Do remember that the University has received a substantial addition to our funds to help support any student, regardless of their fee category, who faces financial difficulties caused by COVID. The reasons could include being unable to secure rent rebates from landlords and difficulties in finding part-time employment, but all reasons for applying will be considered. Students need to <a href=\"/study-here/student-services/student-funding-service\">apply on our website</a>.  While we continue to ask that students apply before 25 March wherever possible, applications will be considered after this date until the fund has been fully spent. Furthermore, the Scottish Government has now agreed that Scottish and RUK Nursing and Midwifery students, who were previously excluded, can now apply to this scheme.  </p>\n<p aria-level=\"2\">Stories of COVID project at QMU: online exhibition opens </p>\n<p>You might have seen coverage of the <a href=\"/{localLink:umb://document/7ba6f97248bf49968a689853aa896dec}\" title=\"Stories of Covid - Digital Instructions\">Stories of COVID</a>  project at QMU on social media or in the Edinburgh Evening News this week.  Coverage focused on the <a href=\"https://www.artsteps.com/view/6022d811d15c2317e4bdf264\">online exhibition</a> associated with the project that captures real life experiences of staff, students and the wider university community during the first lockdown period in 2020. </p>\n<p> </p>\n<p>Have a good weekend, the first weekend of meteorological spring.</p>\n<p> </p>\n<p>Malcolm G Cutt </p>\n<p>Director of Operations and Finance</p>"
