      "title": "26 February 2021",
      "content": "<p class=\"x_MsoNormal\">26 February 2021</p>\n<p class=\"x_MsoNormal\"> </p>\n<div><strong>STUDENTS</strong></div>\n<div>\n<div>Dear students, </div>\n<div>\n<div class=\"x_OutlineElement x_Ltr x_BCX4 x_SCXW134466332\">\n<p class=\"x_Paragraph x_SCXW134466332 x_BCX4\"><span class=\"x_NormalTextRun x_SCXW134466332 x_BCX4\">The Scottish Government’s new strategic framework for easing COVID restrictions.</span></p>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n<div>\n<div class=\"x_OutlineElement x_Ltr x_BCX4 x_SCXW134466332\">\n<p class=\"x_Paragraph x_SCXW134466332 x_BCX4\"><span class=\"x_NormalTextRun x_SCXW134466332 x_BCX4\">On Tuesday, the First Minister gave an overview of the Scottish Government’s new </span><a rel=\"noreferrer noopener\" href=\"https://www.gov.scot/news/gradually-easing-lockdown-restrictions/\" target=\"_blank\" class=\"x_Hyperlink x_SCXW134466332 x_BCX4\" data-auth=\"NotApplicable\"><span class=\"x_NormalTextRun x_SCXW134466332 x_BCX4\">strategic framework for easing COVID restrictions</span></a><span class=\"x_NormalTextRun x_SCXW134466332 x_BCX4\">. In brief, the new framework indicates a return to the variable COVID levels system</span><span class=\"x_NormalTextRun x_SCXW134466332 x_BCX4\">, potentially by </span><span class=\"x_NormalTextRun x_SCXW134466332 x_BCX4\">the end of April, with the hope that all areas previously designated as level 4 can move to level 3 then. Between now and the</span><span class=\"x_NormalTextRun x_SCXW134466332 x_BCX4\">n</span><span class=\"x_NormalTextRun x_SCXW134466332 x_BCX4\">, the plan is to ease level 4 restrictions in a phased way. This has already begun, for example, with the re-opening of early </span><span class=\"x_NormalTextRun x_SCXW134466332 x_BCX4\">years</span><span class=\"x_NormalTextRun x_SCXW134466332 x_BCX4\"> education and some return of students to in-person higher education. The government envisages that the current ‘stay at home’ requirement could be lifted in early April. The intention is to continue the gradual re-opening of the economy and society in a more meaningful way</span><span class=\"x_NormalTextRun x_SCXW134466332 x_BCX4\">, again hopefully from around</span><span class=\"x_NormalTextRun x_SCXW134466332 x_BCX4\"> the end of April.  </span> </p>\n</div>\n<div class=\"x_OutlineElement x_Ltr x_BCX4 x_SCXW134466332\">\n<p class=\"x_Paragraph x_SCXW134466332 x_BCX4\"><span class=\"x_NormalTextRun x_SCXW134466332 x_BCX4\">The First Minister made it clear that</span><span class=\"x_NormalTextRun x_SCXW134466332 x_BCX4\">,</span><span class=\"x_NormalTextRun x_SCXW134466332 x_BCX4\"><span class=\"x_Apple-converted-space\"> while the strategic framework reflects a cautious approach, dates are indicative only at this stage. She emphasised the importance of people remembering </span></span><a rel=\"noreferrer noopener\" href=\"https://www.bing.com/videos/search?q=you+tube+remember+facts+scot+gov&amp;docid=608016668033157799&amp;mid=5A054DEF8BD91E82832B5A054DEF8BD91E82832B&amp;view=detail&amp;FORM=VIRE\" target=\"_blank\" class=\"x_Hyperlink x_SCXW134466332 x_BCX4\" data-auth=\"NotApplicable\"><span class=\"x_NormalTextRun x_SCXW134466332 x_BCX4\">FACTS</span></a><span class=\"x_NormalTextRun x_SCXW134466332 x_BCX4\"><span class=\"x_Apple-converted-space\"> and sticking with the current restrictions in order to give the vaccination programme time to work and provide our path out of lockdown. She indicated that the government would release a further document in mid-March, with more detail on sequencing.  </span></span> </p>\n</div>\n<div class=\"x_OutlineElement x_Ltr x_BCX4 x_SCXW134466332\">\n<p class=\"x_Paragraph x_SCXW134466332 x_BCX4\"><span class=\"x_NormalTextRun x_SCXW134466332 x_BCX4\"><a href=\"https://www.studentinformation.gov.scot/files/189/minister-letter-to-students-feb21.pdf\" title=\"Letter from Richard Lochhead\">Letter for Further and Higher Education Students from Richard Lochhead MSP</a>.</span></p>\n<p class=\"x_Paragraph x_SCXW134466332 x_BCX4\"><span class=\"x_NormalTextRun x_SCXW134466332 x_BCX4\">Richard Lochhead MSP, Minister for Further Education, Higher Education and Science, has written to students about the phased return to colleges and universities. </span> </p>\n</div>\n<div class=\"x_OutlineElement x_Ltr x_BCX4 x_SCXW134466332\">\n<p class=\"x_Paragraph x_SCXW134466332 x_BCX4\"><span class=\"x_TextRun x_SCXW134466332 x_BCX4\"><span class=\"x_NormalTextRun x_SCXW134466332 x_BCX4\">Students’ Union Impact Report.</span></span></p>\n<p class=\"x_Paragraph x_SCXW134466332 x_BCX4\"><span class=\"x_NormalTextRun x_SCXW134466332 x_BCX4\">The Students’ Union has prepared a short impact report summarising some of the things they have been able to achieve to support students over the last semester despite the pandemic – including coordination of class reps, participation in 100+ meetings representing students, facilitating the QMU Food Pantry, advising students in the Help Zone, and arranging COVID-secure events in-person and online. You can read the report </span><a rel=\"noreferrer noopener\" href=\"https://www.qmusu.org.uk/top-menu/your-union/what-we-did-in-semester-1-of-2020-21\" target=\"_blank\" class=\"x_Hyperlink x_SCXW134466332 x_BCX4\" data-auth=\"NotApplicable\"><span class=\"x_NormalTextRun x_SCXW134466332 x_BCX4\">on the Students’ Union website</span></a><span class=\"x_NormalTextRun x_SCXW134466332 x_BCX4\">. On behalf of the Senior Leadership, I will take this opportunity to thank the Students’ Union for all they have done, and continue to do, to support students during COVID</span><span class=\"x_NormalTextRun x_SCXW134466332 x_BCX4\">,</span><span class=\"x_NormalTextRun x_SCXW134466332 x_BCX4\"> and the support that they offer the University community more broadly. </span> </p>\n</div>\n<div class=\"x_OutlineElement x_Ltr x_BCX4 x_SCXW134466332\">\n<p class=\"x_Paragraph x_SCXW134466332 x_BCX4\"><span class=\"x_TextRun x_SCXW134466332 x_BCX4\"><span class=\"x_NormalTextRun x_SCXW134466332 x_BCX4\">Additional Easter Closure Days: Friday 2 April and Monday 5 April</span><span class=\"x_NormalTextRun x_SCXW134466332 x_BCX4\"> </span></span></p>\n<p class=\"x_Paragraph x_SCXW134466332 x_BCX4\"><span class=\"x_NormalTextRun x_SCXW134466332 x_BCX4\">The Senior Leadership Team has taken the decision to grant two additional closure days in order to provide some extra time for staff to rest over the Easter period. This is in recognition of the efforts that staff have been making to keep the University running, whilst also continuing to support students through what has been a difficult and unsettling time for many.</span><span class=\"x_NormalTextRun x_SCXW134466332 x_BCX4\"></span></p>\n</div>\n<div class=\"x_OutlineElement x_Ltr x_BCX4 x_SCXW134466332\">\n<p class=\"x_Paragraph x_SCXW134466332 x_BCX4\"><span class=\"x_NormalTextRun x_SCXW134466332 x_BCX4\">These additional closure dates are Friday 2 April and Monday 5 April (Good Friday and Easter Monday).<span class=\"x_Apple-converted-space\"> </span></span><a rel=\"noreferrer noopener\" href=\"https://myshare.qmu.ac.uk/news/Lists/Posts/Post.aspx?ID=1800\" target=\"_blank\" class=\"x_Hyperlink x_SCXW134466332 x_BCX4\" data-auth=\"NotApplicable\"><span class=\"x_NormalTextRun x_SCXW134466332 x_BCX4\">Staff can find more information on the intranet</span></a><span class=\"x_NormalTextRun x_SCXW134466332 x_BCX4\">, including details of provision for the essential staff that will be required to work.<span class=\"x_Apple-converted-space\"> </span></span><span class=\"x_NormalTextRun x_SCXW134466332 x_BCX4\">While this means for the ma</span><span class=\"x_NormalTextRun x_SCXW134466332 x_BCX4\">jority of students there are no</span><span class=\"x_NormalTextRun x_SCXW134466332 x_BCX4\"><span class=\"x_Apple-converted-space\"> classes on these two days, there are some </span></span><span class=\"x_NormalTextRun x_SCXW134466332 x_BCX4\">online<span class=\"x_Apple-converted-space\"> </span></span><span class=\"x_NormalTextRun x_SCXW134466332 x_BCX4\">exceptions in the School of Health Sciences to enable the timely completion of those programmes, of which the students affected will be already aware.</span><span class=\"x_NormalTextRun x_SCXW134466332 x_BCX4\"> </span><span class=\"x_NormalTextRun x_SCXW134466332 x_BCX4\"></span></p>\n</div>\n<div class=\"x_OutlineElement x_Ltr x_BCX4 x_SCXW134466332\">\n<p class=\"x_Paragraph x_SCXW134466332 x_BCX4\"><span class=\"x_TextRun x_SCXW134466332 x_BCX4\"><span class=\"x_NormalTextRun x_SCXW134466332 x_BCX4\">Short term laptop loans for students</span><span class=\"x_NormalTextRun x_SCXW134466332 x_BCX4\"> </span> </span></p>\n</div>\n<div class=\"x_OutlineElement x_Ltr x_BCX4 x_SCXW134466332\">\n<p class=\"x_Paragraph x_SCXW134466332 x_BCX4\"><span class=\"x_NormalTextRun x_SCXW134466332 x_BCX4\">You might find it useful to know that the Helpdesk has a small bank of laptops available to students for a short term loan of up to four weeks. Students can apply using a<span class=\"x_Apple-converted-space\"> </span></span><a rel=\"noreferrer noopener\" href=\"https://forms.office.com/Pages/ResponsePage.aspx?id=OO8zKCsh_EepOj3VBAOL8t5izRacj2dCvoMONEI-E2lURDlPUEVLNjFMU0g4RkZVUFdBUUZIWU40Vi4u\" target=\"_blank\" class=\"x_Hyperlink x_SCXW134466332 x_BCX4\" data-auth=\"NotApplicable\"><span class=\"x_NormalTextRun x_SCXW134466332 x_BCX4\">link</span></a><span class=\"x_NormalTextRun x_SCXW134466332 x_BCX4\"><span class=\"x_Apple-converted-space\"> which is available on the ‘How to use the Library: </span></span><a rel=\"noreferrer noopener\" href=\"https://libguides.qmu.ac.uk/Libraryservices/ithelp\" target=\"_blank\" class=\"x_Hyperlink x_SCXW134466332 x_BCX4\" data-auth=\"NotApplicable\"><span class=\"x_NormalTextRun x_SCXW134466332 x_BCX4\">Student IT Help</span></a><span class=\"x_NormalTextRun x_SCXW134466332 x_BCX4\">’ section of the website.  </span> </p>\n</div>\n<div class=\"x_OutlineElement x_Ltr x_BCX4 x_SCXW134466332\">\n<p class=\"x_Paragraph x_SCXW134466332 x_BCX4\"><span class=\"x_TextRun x_SCXW134466332 x_BCX4\"><span class=\"x_NormalTextRun x_SCXW134466332 x_BCX4\">COVID vaccination appointments</span><span class=\"x_NormalTextRun x_SCXW134466332 x_BCX4\"> </span> </span></p>\n</div>\n<div class=\"x_OutlineElement x_Ltr x_BCX4 x_SCXW134466332\">\n<p class=\"x_Paragraph x_SCXW134466332 x_BCX4\">As the COVID-19 vaccination programme continues to roll out, we encourage all students to take the opportunity to be vaccinated when it is offered to you. Students are reminded they are excused from scheduled classes to attend important medical appointments, including an appointment to receive your vaccination.</p>\n<p class=\"x_Paragraph x_SCXW134466332 x_BCX4\"> </p>\n<p class=\"x_Paragraph x_SCXW134466332 x_BCX4\">STAFF</p>\n</div>\n<div class=\"x_OutlineElement x_Ltr x_BCX4 x_SCXW36080647\">\n<p class=\"x_Paragraph x_SCXW36080647 x_BCX4\">Dear colleagues,</p>\n</div>\n<div class=\"x_OutlineElement x_Ltr x_BCX4 x_SCXW36080647\">\n<p class=\"x_Paragraph x_SCXW36080647 x_BCX4\"><span class=\"x_TextRun x_SCXW36080647 x_BCX4\"><span class=\"x_NormalTextRun x_SCXW36080647 x_BCX4\">The Scottish Government’s new strategic framework for easing COVID restrictions</span><span class=\"x_NormalTextRun x_SCXW36080647 x_BCX4\"> </span> </span></p>\n</div>\n<div class=\"x_OutlineElement x_Ltr x_BCX4 x_SCXW36080647\">\n<p class=\"x_Paragraph x_SCXW36080647 x_BCX4\"><span class=\"x_NormalTextRun x_SCXW36080647 x_BCX4\">On Tuesday, the First Minister gave an overview of the Scottish Government’s new<span class=\"x_Apple-converted-space\"> </span></span><a rel=\"noreferrer noopener\" href=\"https://www.gov.scot/news/gradually-easing-lockdown-restrictions/\" target=\"_blank\" class=\"x_Hyperlink x_SCXW36080647 x_BCX4\" data-auth=\"NotApplicable\"><span class=\"x_NormalTextRun x_SCXW36080647 x_BCX4\">strategic framework for easing COVID restrictions</span></a><span class=\"x_NormalTextRun x_SCXW36080647 x_BCX4\">. In brief, the new framework indicates a return to the variable COVID levels system</span><span class=\"x_NormalTextRun x_SCXW36080647 x_BCX4\">, potentially by<span class=\"x_Apple-converted-space\"> </span></span><span class=\"x_NormalTextRun x_SCXW36080647 x_BCX4\">the end of April, with the hope that all areas previously designated as level 4 can move to level 3 then. Between now and the</span><span class=\"x_NormalTextRun x_SCXW36080647 x_BCX4\">n</span><span class=\"x_NormalTextRun x_SCXW36080647 x_BCX4\">, the plan is to ease level 4 restrictions in a phased way. This has already begun, for example, with the re-opening of early<span class=\"x_Apple-converted-space\"> </span></span><span class=\"x_NormalTextRun x_SCXW36080647 x_BCX4\">years</span><span class=\"x_NormalTextRun x_SCXW36080647 x_BCX4\"><span class=\"x_Apple-converted-space\"> </span>education and some return of students to in-person higher education. The government envisages that the current ‘stay at home’ requirement could be lifted in early April. The intention is to continue the gradual re-opening of the economy and society in a more meaningful way</span><span class=\"x_NormalTextRun x_SCXW36080647 x_BCX4\">, again hopefully from around</span><span class=\"x_NormalTextRun x_SCXW36080647 x_BCX4\"><span class=\"x_Apple-converted-space\"> </span>the end of April.  </span> </p>\n</div>\n<div class=\"x_OutlineElement x_Ltr x_BCX4 x_SCXW36080647\">\n<p class=\"x_Paragraph x_SCXW36080647 x_BCX4\"><span class=\"x_NormalTextRun x_SCXW36080647 x_BCX4\">The First Minister made it clear that</span><span class=\"x_NormalTextRun x_SCXW36080647 x_BCX4\">,</span><span class=\"x_NormalTextRun x_SCXW36080647 x_BCX4\"><span class=\"x_Apple-converted-space\"> </span>while the strategic framework reflects a cautious approach, dates are indicative only at this stage. She emphasised the importance of people remembering<span class=\"x_Apple-converted-space\"> </span></span><a rel=\"noreferrer noopener\" href=\"https://www.bing.com/videos/search?q=you+tube+remember+facts+scot+gov&amp;docid=608016668033157799&amp;mid=5A054DEF8BD91E82832B5A054DEF8BD91E82832B&amp;view=detail&amp;FORM=VIRE\" target=\"_blank\" class=\"x_Hyperlink x_SCXW36080647 x_BCX4\" data-auth=\"NotApplicable\"><span class=\"x_NormalTextRun x_SCXW36080647 x_BCX4\">FACTS</span></a><span class=\"x_NormalTextRun x_SCXW36080647 x_BCX4\"><span class=\"x_Apple-converted-space\"> </span>and sticking with the current restrictions in order to give the vaccination programme time to work and provide our path out of lockdown. She indicated that the government would release a further document in mid-March, with more detail on sequencing.  </span> </p>\n</div>\n<div class=\"x_OutlineElement x_Ltr x_BCX4 x_SCXW36080647\">\n<p class=\"x_Paragraph x_SCXW36080647 x_BCX4\"><a href=\"https://www.studentinformation.gov.scot/files/189/minister-letter-to-students-feb21.pdf\" title=\"Letter from Richard Lochhead\">Letter for Further and Higher Education Students from Richard Lochhead MSP</a>.</p>\n</div>\n<div class=\"x_OutlineElement x_Ltr x_BCX4 x_SCXW36080647\">\n<p class=\"x_Paragraph x_SCXW36080647 x_BCX4\"><span class=\"x_NormalTextRun x_SCXW36080647 x_BCX4\">Richard Lochhead MSP, Minister for Further Education, Higher Education and Science, has written to students about the phased return to colleges and universities. </span><span class=\"x_NormalTextRun x_SCXW36080647 x_BCX4\"> </span> </p>\n</div>\n<div class=\"x_OutlineElement x_Ltr x_BCX4 x_SCXW36080647\">\n<p class=\"x_Paragraph x_SCXW36080647 x_BCX4\"><span class=\"x_TextRun x_SCXW36080647 x_BCX4\"><span class=\"x_NormalTextRun x_SCXW36080647 x_BCX4\">Students’ Union Impact Report</span><span class=\"x_NormalTextRun x_SCXW36080647 x_BCX4\"> </span> </span></p>\n</div>\n<div class=\"x_OutlineElement x_Ltr x_BCX4 x_SCXW36080647\">\n<p class=\"x_Paragraph x_SCXW36080647 x_BCX4\"><span class=\"x_NormalTextRun x_SCXW36080647 x_BCX4\">The Students’ Union has prepared a short impact report summarising some of the things they have been able to achieve to support students over the last semester despite the pandemic – including coordination of class reps, participation in 100+ meetings representing students, facilitating the QMU Food Pantry, advising students in the Help Zone, and arranging COVID-secure events in-person and online. You can read the report<span class=\"x_Apple-converted-space\"> </span></span><a rel=\"noreferrer noopener\" href=\"https://www.qmusu.org.uk/top-menu/your-union/what-we-did-in-semester-1-of-2020-21\" target=\"_blank\" class=\"x_Hyperlink x_SCXW36080647 x_BCX4\" data-auth=\"NotApplicable\"><span class=\"x_NormalTextRun x_SCXW36080647 x_BCX4\">on the Students’ Union website</span></a><span class=\"x_NormalTextRun x_SCXW36080647 x_BCX4\">. On behalf of the Senior Leadership, I will take this opportunity to thank the Students’ Union for all they have done, and continue to do, to support students during COVID</span><span class=\"x_NormalTextRun x_SCXW36080647 x_BCX4\">,</span><span class=\"x_NormalTextRun x_SCXW36080647 x_BCX4\"><span class=\"x_Apple-converted-space\"> </span>and the support that they offer the University community more broadly. </span> </p>\n</div>\n<div class=\"x_OutlineElement x_Ltr x_BCX4 x_SCXW36080647\">\n<p class=\"x_Paragraph x_SCXW36080647 x_BCX4\"><span class=\"x_TextRun x_SCXW36080647 x_BCX4\"><span class=\"x_NormalTextRun x_SCXW36080647 x_BCX4\">Additional Easter Closure Days: Friday 2 April and Monday 5 April</span><span class=\"x_NormalTextRun x_SCXW36080647 x_BCX4\">  </span> </span></p>\n</div>\n<div class=\"x_OutlineElement x_Ltr x_BCX4 x_SCXW36080647\">\n<p class=\"x_Paragraph x_SCXW36080647 x_BCX4\"><span class=\"x_NormalTextRun x_SCXW36080647 x_BCX4\">The Senior Leadership Team has taken the decision to grant two additional closure days in order to provide some extra time for staff to rest over the Easter period. This is in recognition of the efforts that staff have been making to keep the University running, whilst also continuing to support students through what has been a difficult and unsettling time for many.</span><span class=\"x_NormalTextRun x_SCXW36080647 x_BCX4\"></span></p>\n</div>\n<div class=\"x_OutlineElement x_Ltr x_BCX4 x_SCXW36080647\">\n<p class=\"x_Paragraph x_SCXW36080647 x_BCX4\"><span class=\"x_NormalTextRun x_SCXW36080647 x_BCX4\">These additional closure dates are Friday 2 April and Monday 5 April (Good Friday and Easter Monday).<span class=\"x_Apple-converted-space\"> </span></span><a rel=\"noreferrer noopener\" href=\"https://myshare.qmu.ac.uk/news/Lists/Posts/Post.aspx?ID=1800\" target=\"_blank\" class=\"x_Hyperlink x_SCXW36080647 x_BCX4\" data-auth=\"NotApplicable\"><span class=\"x_NormalTextRun x_SCXW36080647 x_BCX4\">Staff can find more information on the intranet</span></a><span class=\"x_NormalTextRun x_SCXW36080647 x_BCX4\">, including details of provision for the essential staff that will be required to work.<span class=\"x_Apple-converted-space\"> </span></span><span class=\"x_NormalTextRun x_SCXW36080647 x_BCX4\">While this means for the ma</span><span class=\"x_NormalTextRun x_SCXW36080647 x_BCX4\">jority of students there are no</span><span class=\"x_NormalTextRun x_SCXW36080647 x_BCX4\"><span class=\"x_Apple-converted-space\"> </span>classes on these two days, there are some<span class=\"x_Apple-converted-space\"> </span></span><span class=\"x_NormalTextRun x_SCXW36080647 x_BCX4\">online<span class=\"x_Apple-converted-space\"> </span></span><span class=\"x_NormalTextRun x_SCXW36080647 x_BCX4\">exceptions in the School of Health Sciences to enable the timely completion of those programmes, of which the students affected will be already aware.</span><span class=\"x_NormalTextRun x_SCXW36080647 x_BCX4\"></span></p>\n</div>\n<div class=\"x_OutlineElement x_Ltr x_BCX4 x_SCXW36080647\">\n<p class=\"x_Paragraph x_SCXW36080647 x_BCX4\"><span class=\"x_TextRun x_SCXW36080647 x_BCX4\"><span class=\"x_NormalTextRun x_SCXW36080647 x_BCX4\">Short term laptop loans for students</span><span class=\"x_NormalTextRun x_SCXW36080647 x_BCX4\"> </span> </span></p>\n</div>\n<div class=\"x_OutlineElement x_Ltr x_BCX4 x_SCXW36080647\">\n<p class=\"x_Paragraph x_SCXW36080647 x_BCX4\"><span class=\"x_NormalTextRun x_SCXW36080647 x_BCX4\">You might find it useful to know that the Helpdesk has a small bank of laptops available to students for a short-term loan of up to four weeks. Students can <a href=\"https://forms.office.com/Pages/ResponsePage.aspx?id=OO8zKCsh_EepOj3VBAOL8t5izRacj2dCvoMONEI-E2lURDlPUEVLNjFMU0g4RkZVUFdBUUZIWU40Vi4u\" title=\"Laptop application form\" data-anchor=\"?id=OO8zKCsh_EepOj3VBAOL8t5izRacj2dCvoMONEI-E2lURDlPUEVLNjFMU0g4RkZVUFdBUUZIWU40Vi4u\">apply using a form</a></span><span class=\"x_NormalTextRun x_SCXW36080647 x_BCX4\">which is available on the ‘How to use the Library:<span class=\"x_Apple-converted-space\"> </span></span><a rel=\"noreferrer noopener\" href=\"https://libguides.qmu.ac.uk/Libraryservices/ithelp\" target=\"_blank\" class=\"x_Hyperlink x_SCXW36080647 x_BCX4\" data-auth=\"NotApplicable\"><span class=\"x_NormalTextRun x_SCXW36080647 x_BCX4\">Student IT Help</span></a><span class=\"x_NormalTextRun x_SCXW36080647 x_BCX4\">’ section of the website.  </span> </p>\n</div>\n<div class=\"x_OutlineElement x_Ltr x_BCX4 x_SCXW36080647\">\n<p class=\"x_Paragraph x_SCXW36080647 x_BCX4\"><span class=\"x_TextRun x_SCXW36080647 x_BCX4\"><span class=\"x_NormalTextRun x_SCXW36080647 x_BCX4\">COVID vaccination appointments</span><span class=\"x_NormalTextRun x_SCXW36080647 x_BCX4\"> </span> </span></p>\n</div>\n<div class=\"x_OutlineElement x_Ltr x_BCX4 x_SCXW36080647\">\n<p class=\"x_Paragraph x_SCXW36080647 x_BCX4\"><span class=\"x_NormalTextRun x_SCXW36080647 x_BCX4\">As the COVID-19 vaccination programme continues to roll out, we encourage all of our staff to take the opportunity to be vaccinated when it is offered to you. The vaccination programme is reaching a stage where we expect increasing numbers of our staff to receive their invitations to attend a vaccination centre over the coming weeks. We want to take this opportunity to remind staff that you are entitled to reasonable time off during your normal working hours to attend medical appointments, including an appointment to receive your vaccination. When you receive your invitation, please inform your manager of the time and date of your appointment.  </span> </p>\n</div>\n<div class=\"x_OutlineElement x_Ltr x_BCX4 x_SCXW36080647\">\n<p class=\"x_Paragraph x_SCXW36080647 x_BCX4\"><span class=\"x_TextRun x_SCXW36080647 x_BCX4\"><span class=\"x_NormalTextRun x_SCXW36080647 x_BCX4\">Staff working on campus</span><span class=\"x_NormalTextRun x_SCXW36080647 x_BCX4\"> </span> </span></p>\n</div>\n<div class=\"x_OutlineElement x_Ltr x_BCX4 x_SCXW36080647\">\n<p class=\"x_Paragraph x_SCXW36080647 x_BCX4\"><span class=\"x_NormalTextRun x_SCXW36080647 x_BCX4\">Please remember that<span class=\"x_Apple-converted-space\"> </span></span><span class=\"x_NormalTextRun x_SCXW36080647 x_BCX4\">members of<span class=\"x_Apple-converted-space\"> </span></span><span class=\"x_NormalTextRun x_SCXW36080647 x_BCX4\">staff<span class=\"x_Apple-converted-space\"> </span></span><span class=\"x_NormalTextRun x_SCXW36080647 x_BCX4\">should only visit campus for essential reasons or if you are unable to do your job from home</span><span class=\"x_NormalTextRun x_SCXW36080647 x_BCX4\">, and that attendance on campus should be agreed with your line manager</span><span class=\"x_NormalTextRun x_SCXW36080647 x_BCX4\">. Visit <a href=\"https://www.gov.scot/publications/coronavirus-covid-19-general-guidance-for-safer-workplaces/\" title=\"Guidance for safer workplaces\">The Scottish Government's latest guidance for safer workplaces</a>.</span></p>\n<p class=\"x_x_x_xmsonormal\"> </p>\n<p class=\"x_x_x_xmsonormal\">Malcolm G Cutt</p>\n<p class=\"x_x_x_xmsonormal\">Director of Operations and Finance</p>\n</div>\n</div>"
    },
    {
      "contentTypeKey": "216ea22b-01af-4645-8972-5766bbd75b6c",
      "udi": "umb://element/aa72357bb1124ebbbedbd8a751e82976",
      "title": "19 February 2021",
      "content": "<p class=\"x_MsoNormal\">19 February 2021</p>\n<p class=\"x_MsoNormal\"><strong>STUDENT MESSAGE</strong></p>\n<p class=\"x_MsoNormal\"><strong>Dear students</strong></p>\n<p><strong>Update on staggered return of undergraduate in-person teaching</strong></p>\n<p>This week, the Scottish Government advised universities that we should expect to remain in <a rel=\"noopener noreferrer\" href=\"https://www.studentinformation.gov.scot/coronavirus/term-two\" target=\"_blank\" data-auth=\"NotApplicable\">phase 1</a> of the staggered return at least until the middle of March.  Under phase 1, the default remains online teaching, except where attendance is critical and time-sensitive to the course or assessment and cannot be delivered remotely, or for those students on essential placements.   </p>\n<p>Undergraduate programme leaders have started to communicate what this means for each programme currently being delivered online, with the aim of giving you more certainty about how your classes will be delivered for the rest of the semester. If you are an undergraduate student currently being taught online and have not heard from your programme leader yet, you will very soon.  Any changes to your timetable will be reflected in the published timetable too. </p>\n<p class=\"x_MsoNormal\">There may also be some minor timetable changes for those Health Sciences students who are already receiving in-person teaching, and postgraduate students in ASSaM should anticipate changes to what had previously been scheduled, as a consequence of universities remaining in phase 1 of the Scottish Government’s staggered return.</p>\n<p class=\"x_MsoNormal\">In general, all students should continue to check their timetable for any updates to their timetabled teaching given the dynamic situation in which we remain.</p>\n<p class=\"x_MsoNormal\"><strong>Other updates</strong></p>\n<p class=\"x_MsoListParagraphCxSpFirst\">· Quarantine hotels: in our <a rel=\"noopener\" href=\"/{localLink:umb://document/4da50204dcaa4c608ee3d0a49f0438c5}\" target=\"_blank\" title=\"International\" data-auth=\"NotApplicable\">international student coronavirus FAQs</a>, we have published information on new laws regarding international travel and the requirement for managed isolation (ie ‘quarantine hotels’). If this issue could affect you, please contact our international team with any queries (<a rel=\"noopener noreferrer\" href=\"mailto:international@qmu.ac.uk\" target=\"_blank\" data-auth=\"NotApplicable\">international@qmu.ac.uk</a>) after you have read the published information.</p>\n<p class=\"x_MsoListParagraphCxSpMiddle\">· Taking COVID into account when it comes to assessments and degree classifications:  during the coronavirus pandemic, the University has undertaken significant work to address the many challenges associated with COVID for learning, teaching and assessment. All possible steps have been taken to protect student progression, achievement and completion, and to ensure that students are not disadvantaged by necessary adjustments to programme delivery or assessment.  It is with this firmly in mind, and with the support of the Students’ Union, that our Student Experience Committee recommended at its meeting on 17 February that the current version of the emergency regulations, which took effect on 1 October 2020, should continue for the remainder of academic session 2020/21. <a rel=\"noopener\" href=\"/{localLink:umb://document/e9f078ecf44140bda12e1de86b67d0a5}\" target=\"_blank\" title=\"Updated Assessment Regulations\" data-auth=\"NotApplicable\">These regulations can be found on our website</a>.  This recommendation will be put to the University Senate when it meets on 17 March. Students with individual extenuating circumstances should continue to follow the usual process for requesting extensions via the Student Portal.</p>\n<p class=\"x_MsoListParagraphCxSpMiddle\">· COVID asymptomatic testing on campus for students: our testing centre is open (for one day) on Monday from 11am to 3pm. You can <a rel=\"noopener noreferrer\" href=\"/coronavirus/test/\" target=\"_blank\" data-auth=\"NotApplicable\">book online</a>. Walk-up appointments will also be available.</p>\n<p class=\"x_MsoListParagraphCxSpMiddle\">· Coronavirus Discretionary Fund: the University has received a substantial addition to our funds to help upport any student, regardless of their fee category, who faces financial difficulties caused by COVID. The reasons could include being unable to secure rent rebates from landlords and difficulties in finding part-time employment, but all reasons for applying will be considered. For more information, see the separate Moderator message being issued today then <a rel=\"noopener\" href=\"/{localLink:umb://document/8289ea3f25cd4651a34f61302879db16}\" target=\"_blank\" title=\"Application for Financial Assistance\" data-auth=\"NotApplicable\">apply on our website</a><span> (before 25 March).</span><span></span></p>\n<p class=\"x_MsoNormal\">Thank you for your continued patience with the ongoing restrictions, and their impacts on your lives. Rest assured you have our unwavering commitment to addressing your needs at this time and do remember that staff are here to help you.  In particular, remember that you can call on our <a rel=\"noopener\" href=\"/{localLink:umb://document/a33d92be97574482967def19ff8a302f}\" target=\"_blank\" title=\"Student Services\" data-auth=\"NotApplicable\">Student Services</a> team, and do check out our <a rel=\"noopener\" href=\"/{localLink:umb://document/a33d92be97574482967def19ff8a302f}\" target=\"_blank\" title=\"Student Services\" data-auth=\"NotApplicable\">wellbeing resources</a>.</p>\n<p class=\"x_MsoNormal\">Malcolm G Cutt</p>\n<p class=\"x_MsoNormal\">Director of Operations and Finance</p>"
    },
    {
      "contentTypeKey": "216ea22b-01af-4645-8972-5766bbd75b6c",
      "udi": "umb://element/aa86a376e3624a15aa9f8c3158600a3e",
      "title": "12 February 2021",
      "content": "<p>12 February 2021</p>\n<p>For Students and Staff:</p>\n<p><strong>UPDATE ON STAGGERED RETURN OF UNDERGRADUATE IN-PERSON TEACHING</strong></p>\n<p>It is expected that the First Minister will give an update in parliament on the Scottish Government’s position on the staggered return of in-person undergraduate teaching this coming Tuesday. Alongside this, universities have been liaising with Scottish Government officials on the detail of the arrangements for the staggered return.  We will update you on our plans as soon as we can after Tuesday, informed by what the First Minister says.  We do understand that you will be finding the uncertainty frustrating, and thank you for your patience.</p>\n<p><strong>AVAILABILITY OF ASYMPTOMATIC COVID TESTING</strong></p>\n<p>Any student (without COVID symptoms) who needs to return to term-time accommodation just now can arrange a COVID test through the University of Edinburgh, with information on this available on the <a href=\"https://u.qmu.ac.uk/live/sits.urd/run/siw_lgn\">QMU student portal</a>.  If you do believe that you need to return to term-time accommodation, remember, of course, to take full account of the rules associated with such a move.  You can find the rules and guidance on the Scottish Government’s <a href=\"https://www.studentinformation.gov.scot/coronavirus/term-two\">Student Information Scotland website</a>.  We will announce further dates for the operation of our own testing centre in due course, in line with demand and the staggered return.</p>\n<p><strong>NEW INTERNATIONAL QUARANTINE REQUIREMENTS</strong></p>\n<p>Earlier this week, the Scottish Government advised that all international travellers coming directly into Scotland will have to go into managed isolation, ie quarantining in specified hotels near their arrival airport for 10 days, with travellers bearing the cost. We are conscious that this announcement will be causing concern for international students, and indeed all QMU students currently overseas.  We expect to receive more information from government soon, including information on whether there will be any special arrangements for students. When we do have more information, we will post it on our <a href=\"/{localLink:umb://document/4da50204dcaa4c608ee3d0a49f0438c5}\" title=\"International\">coronavirus FAQS for international students</a>, and share it in our next COVID update.  </p>\n<p><strong>VACCINATION CENTRE OPEN</strong></p>\n<p>Everyone on campus will have been cheered by seeing the NHS-operated vaccination centre open on Wednesday.  Everything seems to be going very smoothly, with lots of smiling faces amongst NHS and facilities staff, and those taking up vaccination appointments, on what was a very cold and snowy opening day.  Our own Campus Services staff were on the scene before dawn, clearing the access routes of snow.  On behalf of the Senior Leadership Team, I thank all the QMU staff involved in helping to set up the centre.   This project has been a wonderful example of partnership work.</p>\n<p>If any member of the public on campus asks you about the vaccination centre, we would ask you to direct questions to the vaccination centre staff (all of whom wear hi-vis jackets) rather than to try to answer questions yourself.  More generally, you can direct questions to the NHS’s COVID-19 vaccination helpline on 0800 030 8013 or NHS Lothian’s ‘<a href=\"https://www.nhslothian.scot/Coronavirus/Vaccine/Pages/default.aspx\"><strong>Vaccine Hub</strong></a>’ website.</p>\n<p><strong>REMINDER TO WEAR FACE COVERINGS</strong></p>\n<p>If you do need to be on campus, please remember that, as required by Scottish Government regulations, face coverings must now be worn in classrooms and other teaching spaces, in addition to all other communal spaces, including the LRC, except by those who are legally exempt for medical reasons. Face coverings will continue to be required in classrooms and other teaching spaces until we return to the Scottish Government’s COVID Level 3 or lower. The requirement to wear face coverings applies at all times, except when you are eating or drinking. As we all struggle to remember the rules from time to time, none of us should feel hesitant about reminding anyone else to wear a face covering, or to keep their distance.</p>\n<p><strong>For Staff:</strong></p>\n<p>And a final note to staff – as you will know from my last update, there is now an online ‘Working Safely on Campus’ e-learning module to be completed by all staff who currently attend campus and those who are planning to return to campus. It takes just 10 minutes to complete and is designed to ensure that you are familiar with the COVID workplace adaptations we have implemented to keep you safe, and your role and responsibilities while on campus.  An email containing all the necessary log in details is being sent to all staff who are required to complete the training. If you are required to attend campus, look out for this email.  If you haven’t received this email and think you should have done, please contact the Health &amp; Safety Adviser (<a href=\"mailto:MKennedy1@qmu.ac.uk\">MKennedy1@qmu.ac.uk</a>).</p>\n<p>Malcolm G Cutt</p>\n<p>Director of Operations and Finance</p>"
    },
    {
      "contentTypeKey": "216ea22b-01af-4645-8972-5766bbd75b6c",
      "udi": "umb://element/f74e91dee4da4b3ea5d0962d221d6f46",
      "title": "4 February 2021",
      "content": "<p>4 February 2021</p>\n<p>For students:</p>\n<p><strong>Update on current restrictions</strong></p>\n<p>On Tuesday, <a href=\"https://www.gov.scot/news/new-measures-to-tackle-virus/\">the First Minister indicated that the current COVID restrictions will continue at least to the end of February</a>. However, in encouraging news for students that are parents, she said that that nurseries and primaries 1 to 3 are now scheduled to return full-time on 22 February, with some provision for senior pupils too (S4 to S6), all subject to confirmation around 16 February that sufficient progress in tackling the virus has been achieved.  The First Minister also indicated that she would give an update on the staggered return of students to university campuses around that same time, which will in turn inform our own plans. She also said that the Scottish Government would be introducing a managed quarantine model for flights into Scotland as soon as possible, with details to be confirmed shortly.</p>\n<p><strong>Mass vaccination centre on campus</strong></p>\n<p>On campus, the mass vaccination centre is set to open on 10 February.  It is important to note that the centre is run by NHS Lothian, not the University.   NHS clinical, administrative and support staff are managing all details of centre set up and operation, working with the University and with external partners, for example with traffic management consultants.</p>\n<p>The vaccination centre will occupy about 50% of our car park.  Please rest assured that, based on analysis of car park usage from last semester, we are confident that there will be plenty of parking space for QMU car park users while the vaccination centre is running. As you would expect, we will retain accessible parking spaces, in front of Accommodation Block A.</p>\n<p>Alterations are being made to the car park entrance to allow separation of QMU car park and vaccination centre traffic. Incoming vaccination centre traffic will be directed past the car park into the bus turning circle for check-in procedures, before being fed into the car park in a controlled manner.  There will be signage and marshalls on campus directing traffic. Off campus, there will be directional signage on main access routes including the A1 and the city bypass. Very soon, there will be communication to students and staff by Moderator on car park access changes, with these changes effective from 8 February.</p>\n<p>The centre will operate from 8.30am to 6.30pm, seven days a week.  It will be drive-through only. It is anticipated that it will be at peak capacity by the end of March or early April, with operations continuing until the end of May, based on current agreements.</p>\n<p>If anyone asks you about the vaccination centre, please direct them to the NHS’s COVID-19 vaccination helpline on 0800 030 8013. They might also like to check out NHS Lothian’s ‘<a href=\"https://www.nhslothian.scot/Coronavirus/Vaccine/Pages/default.aspx\">Vaccine Hub</a>’ website. We also provide some <a href=\"/{localLink:umb://document/6ce876bba0f84252817f35afd53b4057}\" title=\"NHS COVID-19 Drive-Through Vaccination Centre at Queen Margaret University\">information for the general public on our websit</a>e, accessible from our home page.</p>\n<p><strong>Thinking ahead to assessments</strong></p>\n<p>We are conscious that some students might be concerned about how the University will take into account COVID when it comes to assessments and degree classifications later this semester. Our Student Experience Committee will be discussing this issue on 17 February, with a view to Senate considering any appropriate amendments to our extenuating circumstances processes and assessment regulations, at its meeting on 17 March. You will be able to find details of existing adjustments to our regulations in our <a href=\"/{localLink:umb://document/2d74bbbb94e34467ab39bb1f82a83b2e}\" title=\"Students\">student coronavirus FAQs</a>.</p>\n<p><strong>Other work supporting students</strong></p>\n<p>You might like to know that a <a href=\"https://www.gov.scot/news/focus-on-completing-courses/\">task force </a> comprising representatives of colleges, universities, students, trade unions and government has been set up to support students with issues arising from the COVID restrictions, with the immediate focus on helping students to complete their courses and move into further study or employment.  The group met for the first time this week, with QMU’s Principal representing universities on the group.</p>\n<p><strong>QMUYou Move</strong></p>\n<p>Already, around 160 people have signed up on <a href=\"https://www.strava.com/clubs/qmyou-move-842405\">Strava</a> for ‘QMYou Move’, the six week activity challenge for students, staff and the wider QMU community, organised by the Students’ Union.   You can also find QMYou Move on <a href=\"https://www.facebook.com/QMYouMove\">Facebook</a>.   The aim is to get the QMU community moving – whether you walk, run, do yoga, or even just hoover!</p>\n<p> </p>\n<p>Malcolm G Cutt</p>\n<p>Director of Operations and Finance</p>\n<p> </p>\n<p>For staff:</p>\n<p><strong>Update on current restrictions</strong></p>\n<p>On Tuesday, <a href=\"https://www.gov.scot/news/new-measures-to-tackle-virus/\">the First Minister indicated that the current COVID restrictions will continue at least to the end of February</a>. However, in encouraging news for students and staff that are parents, she said that that nurseries and primaries 1 to 3 are now scheduled to return full-time on 22 February, with some provision for senior pupils too (S4 to S6), subject to final confirmation around 16 February that sufficient progress in tackling the virus has been achieved.   She indicated that she would give an update on the staggered return of students to university campuses around that same time, which will in turn inform our own plans. She also said that the Scottish Government would be introducing a managed quarantine model for flights into Scotland as soon as possible, with details to be confirmed.</p>\n<p><strong>Mass vaccination centre on campus</strong></p>\n<p>On campus, the mass vaccination centre is set to open on 10 February.  It is important to note that the centre is run by NHS Lothian not the University.   NHS clinical, administrative and support staff are managing all details of centre set up and operation, working with the University and with external partners, for example with traffic management consultants.</p>\n<p>The vaccination centre will occupy about 50% of our car park.  Please rest assured that, based on analysis of car park usage from last semester, we are confident that there will be plenty of parking space for QMU car park users while the vaccination centre is running. As you would expect, we will retain accessible parking spaces, in front of Accommodation Block A.</p>\n<p>Alterations are being made to the car park entrance to allow separation of QMU car park and vaccination centre traffic. Incoming vaccination centre traffic will be directed past the car park into the bus turning circle for check-in procedures before being fed into the car park in a controlled manner.  There will be signage and marshalls on campus directing traffic. Off campus, there will be directional signage on main access routes including the A1 and the city bypass. Very soon, there will be communication to students and staff by Moderator on car park access changes, with these changes effective from 8 February.</p>\n<p>The centre will operate from 8.30am to 6.30pm, seven days a week.  It will be drive-through only. It is anticipated that it will be at peak capacity by the end of March or early April, with operations continuing until the end of May, based on current agreements.</p>\n<p>If anyone asks you about the vaccination centre, please direct them to the NHS’s COVID-19 vaccination helpline on 0800 030 8013. They might also like to check out NHS Lothian’s ‘<a href=\"https://www.nhslothian.scot/Coronavirus/Vaccine/Pages/default.aspx\">Vaccine Hub</a>’ website. We also provide some <a href=\"/{localLink:umb://document/6ce876bba0f84252817f35afd53b4057}\" title=\"NHS COVID-19 Drive-Through Vaccination Centre at Queen Margaret University\">information for the general public on our websit</a>e, accessible from our home page.</p>\n<p>You can find a brief presentation on the plans for the vaccine centre on the <a rel=\"noopener\" href=\"https://myshare.qmu.ac.uk/services/campus-commercial-services/covid19/_layouts/15/WopiFrame2.aspx?sourcedoc=%7b7021178B-AE6F-4A8C-AB71-73397EB6C536%7d&amp;file=Vaccination%20Centre%20Presentation%20for%20intranet.pptx&amp;action=default?sourcedoc=%7b7021178B-AE6F-4A8C-AB71-73397EB6C536%7d&amp;file=Vaccination%20Centre%20Presentation%20for%20intranet.pptx&amp;action=default\" target=\"_blank\" data-anchor=\"?sourcedoc=%7b7021178B-AE6F-4A8C-AB71-73397EB6C536%7d&amp;file=Vaccination%20Centre%20Presentation%20for%20intranet.pptx&amp;action=default\">COVID intranet site</a>.</p>\n<p><strong>Thinking ahead to assessments</strong></p>\n<p>We are conscious that some students might be concerned about how the University will take into account COVID when it comes to assessments and degree classifications later this semester. Our Student Experience Committee will be discussing this issue on 17 February, with a view to Senate considering any appropriate amendments to our extenuating circumstances processes and assessment regulations, at its meeting on 17 March. You will be able to find details of existing adjustments to our regulations in our <a href=\"/coronavirus/faqs/students/\">student coronavirus FAQs</a>.</p>\n<p><strong>Other work supporting students</strong></p>\n<p>You might like to know that a <a href=\"https://www.gov.scot/news/focus-on-completing-courses/\">task force </a> comprising representatives of colleges, universities, students, trade unions and government has been set up to support students with issues arising from the COVID restrictions, with the immediate focus on helping students to complete their courses and move into further study or employment.  The group met for the first time this week, with Sir Paul representing universities on the group.</p>\n<p><strong>Online ‘Working Safely on Campus’ e-learning module</strong></p>\n<p>There is now an online ‘Working Safely on Campus’ e-learning module to be completed by all staff who currently attend campus and those who are planning to return to campus. It takes just 10 minutes to complete and is designed to ensure you are familiar with the COVID workplace adaptations we have implemented to keep you safe, and your role and responsibilities while on campus. An email containing all the necessary log in details will be sent to all staff who are required to complete the training. Alongside this, we have updated the process for requesting office and IT equipment. The form is available on the <a href=\"https://myshare.qmu.ac.uk/services/campus-commercial-services/covid19/SitePages/Home%20Working.aspx\">COVID section of the intranet</a>.  Any questions or difficulties accessing this training should be sent to the QMU Health and Safety Team @ <a href=\"mailto:HS-Staff@qmu.ac.uk\">HS-Staff@qmu.ac.uk</a></p>\n<p><strong>QMUYou Move</strong></p>\n<p>Already, around 160 people have signed up on <a href=\"https://www.strava.com/clubs/qmyou-move-842405\">Strava</a> for ‘QMYou Move’, the six week activity challenge for students, staff and the wider QMU community, organised by the Students’ Union.    You can also find QMYou Move on <a href=\"https://www.facebook.com/QMYouMove\">Facebook</a>.   The aim is to get the QMU community moving – whether you walk, run, do yoga, or even just hoover!</p>\n<p> </p>\n<p>Malcolm G Cutt</p>\n<p>Director of Operations and Finance</p>\n<p> </p>"
