    {
      "contentTypeKey": "216ea22b-01af-4645-8972-5766bbd75b6c",
      "udi": "umb://element/872ff332a0b64db2a174a3710138c3c8",
      "title": "29 January 2021",
      "content": "<p>29 January 2021</p>\n<p> </p>\n<p>For students:</p>\n<p>Dear students</p>\n<p><strong>Scottish Government Q&amp;As for students</strong></p>\n<p>The <a href=\"https://www.studentinformation.gov.scot/coronavirus/term-two\">Scottish Government has now published Q&amp;As for students on semester two</a>. The Q&amp;As include advice on when you can return, student accommodation and travel. As you will know from my <a href=\"/{localLink:umb://document/655742a31f25458f96f2d67439fb297a}\" title=\"Updates\">last update</a> (22 January), we can’t yet confirm details of the staggered return to face to face teaching from 22 February for those currently studying online, but I can reassure you that we will give you as much notice as possible.</p>\n<p><strong>On-campus COVID testing</strong></p>\n<p>Today is the last asymptomatic student testing session on campus for the moment. In due course, we will announce further testing dates, aligned with the staggered return to in-person teaching and demand levels.</p>\n<p><strong>Update on the full range of student services available to you</strong></p>\n<p>Also today, you will have received a Moderator message with an updated summary of the full range of support services for students across the University and how to access them. Each support service is committed to helping you navigate this uncertain time. From Monday 25 January some of the service reception points have been temporarily closed or are operating on reduced opening hours. However, each support service remains open and accessible to all students, whether studying on campus or remotely. See the foot of this update for a copy of that message.</p>\n<p><strong>Advice for students who need to come to the campus</strong></p>\n<p>If you are one of the students who has been advised that you need to be on campus for in-person teaching just now, you can, if you wish, request through the School Office an official letter from the University confirming that you have classes on campus. If you are travelling to campus for a welfare appointment or to use the library, remember that you can show the authorities your online booking in the event that you are challenged.</p>\n<p><strong>QMYouMove </strong></p>\n<p>In the course of today, the Students’ Union will share details of ‘QMYouMove’, a six week activity challenge for students, staff and the wider QMU community, which will start next week. I know there is already quite a lot of interest in this initiative, as we all try to keep ourselves motivated to get fresh air and exercise during the current COVID restrictions. </p>\n<p><strong>Interesting research going on at QMU</strong></p>\n<p>You might also find it cheering to read about some of the fascinating and highly relevant research projects going on right now within the University, including projects directly associated with COVID.  We’ve created a section of our website bringing together <a href=\"/{localLink:umb://document/cc05e446ed6542dd99cfa00599b78d88}\" title=\"Covid-19\">projects funded by the Scottish Government to help mitigate of effects of the pandemic on research</a>.  There, you can learn, for example, how we are exploring ‘<a href=\"/{localLink:umb://document/665c1315ef6046b69232a8220bfe694c}\" title=\"Film festivals, audiences and Covid-19; Crisis, community and digital comeback.\">Film festivals, audiences and Covid-19; crisis, community and digital comeback.’</a> and ‘<a href=\"/{localLink:umb://document/665c1315ef6046b69232a8220bfe694c}\" title=\"Film festivals, audiences and Covid-19; Crisis, community and digital comeback.\">Community, health and social care system stressors and coping mechanisms during COVID-19’</a>.</p>\n<p>Malcolm G Cutt</p>\n<p>Director of Operations and Finance</p>\n<p>Moderator Message on Student Services</p>\n<p><strong>From:</strong> Moderator &lt;Moderator@qmu.ac.uk&gt; <br /><strong>Sent:</strong> 29 January 2021 09:08<br /><strong>Subject:</strong> Student Support Services- UPDATE</p>\n<p>Dear Students and Staff</p>\n<p>Please see the following information about the full range of support services for students across the University and how to contact them. <strong>Catering provision has been included.</strong> Each support service is committed to helping you navigate this uncertain time. From Monday 25 January some of the service receptions will be temporarily closed or operate on reduced opening hours. However, each support service remains open and accessible to all students, whether studying on campus or remotely.</p>\n<p>Each of the services has provided the details below.</p>\n<p><strong>Accommodation Services &amp; ResLife</strong></p>\n<p>If you have any questions or concerns relating to accommodation on campus then you can get in touch with the Accommodation Services team by email <a href=\"mailto:accommodation@qmu.ac.uk\">accommodation@qmu.ac.uk</a>. You can also speak to us at Accommodation Reception which remains open from 9am – 8pm Monday to Friday and 12pm – 4pm on weekends.</p>\n<p>The <a href=\"https://www.facebook.com/qmureslife/\">ResLife</a> team are continuing to support students living campus so please do get in touch with the <a href=\"mailto:reslife@qmu.ac.uk\">Residence Life Coordinator</a> if you need advice or support. The ResLife team have lots of upcoming activities planned, including virtual quizzes, vegan food giveaways, online bingo, book club and baking competitions. You can keep up to date with what’s on via the ResLife <a href=\"https://www.facebook.com/groups/634782686973720/?fref=nf\">Facebook Group</a>. If you have any questions about the events on offer, or if you have an idea for a future event then let us know and we’ll see what we can do!</p>\n<p>If you are living on campus and require urgent help when the Accommodation Reception is closed, then be reassured that the Security team are on duty 24/7 keeping you safe. You can contact them by calling 0131 474 0000 and asking for Security, or via one of the intercom points across campus.</p>\n<p><strong>ASSIST</strong></p>\n<p>The Helpdesk team continue to be your one-stop shop for reporting any faults or problems with Accommodation, Facilities, IT and Library Services. To log a job with the team, please drop them an email at <a href=\"mailto:assist@qmu.ac.uk\">assist@qmu.ac.uk</a>  and a member of the team will be happy to help. The team are working remotely from 8am – 7pm Monday to Friday. For library queries email <a href=\"mailto:LRCHelp@qmu.ac.uk\">LRCHelp@qmu.ac.uk</a></p>\n<p><strong>Careers and Employability</strong></p>\n<p>The Careers and Employability service is available to all students, providing support with your career from help with applications and CV, to interview skills and support to find work. The service delivers a range of webinars on various topics relating to your career and the world of work. We are also currently preparing for a festival of careers to be delivered in February. You can use <a href=\"https://studentcentral.qmu.ac.uk\" title=\"Student Central\"><em>Student Central</em></a> to view current vacancies, book appointments and view the resources.  </p>\n<p>Email <a href=\"mailto:careers@qmu.ac.uk\">careers@qmu.ac.uk</a> or <a href=\"mailto:employability@qmu.ac.uk\">employability@qmu.ac.uk</a> for help and support or visit our <a href=\"/campus-life/careers-and-employability/\" title=\"Careers and employability\">careers and employability page</a> to find out more.</p>\n<p>The Catering team continue to work onsite running a take-away and delivery service from Maggie’s.   Please continue to use the <a href=\"https://round.app/\">'Round' app</a> for pre-orders and deliveries to keep yourself and our team safe.  If you are unable to use Round, you are still able to order in person outside Maggie’s – but we will not be allowing anyone access to the building.  We also have various options for ‘Isolation Packages’ which can be delivered to your flat on campus.  Please contact our Catering Manager <a href=\"mailto:jsmith3@qmu.ac.uk\">Julie Smith</a> for more details.</p>\n<p><strong>Counselling Service</strong> </p>\n<p>The <a href=\"/study-here/student-services/counselling-service/\" title=\"QMU Counselling Service\">Counselling service</a> continues to provide counselling online and in person. You can book appointments through student central or by emailing the service on <a href=\"mailto:counselling@qmu.ac.uk\">counselling@qmu.ac.uk</a> . These sessions can be used to start talking about what’s going on for you, strategies and ways forward. You can have a one off appointment or a series of sessions, whatever suits you.</p>\n<p>Please don’t hesitate to email <a href=\"mailto:counselling@qmu.ac.uk\">counselling@qmu.ac.uk</a>  for further information. </p>\n<p><strong>Disability Service</strong> </p>\n<p>You can book an appointment with a Disability Adviser to have an assessment or to discuss any questions you might have. We support students with a variety of needs and if you have questions about what support is available to you,do not hesitate to get in touch. We also offer training on Assistive Technology if this is something that might be of use to you.</p>\n<p>You can book in with us via Student central <a href=\"https://studentcentral.qmu.ac.uk/s/disability\">Disability Service – Student Central</a> or by emailing us on <a href=\"mailto:%20disabilityadvisers@qmu.ac.uk\">disabilityadvisers@qmu.ac.uk</a> To find out more about the support available please visit our <a href=\"/study-here/student-services/disability-service\" title=\"Disability Service\">Disability Service page</a>.</p>\n<p><strong>Effective Learning Service</strong></p>\n<p>The Effective Learning Service continues to offer appointments to students, which can be booked on Student Central. The appointments take the form of email advice and guidance on writing assignments and developing academic skills, and discussion via email of any queries arising from this feedback. Students can see availability and <a href=\"https://studentcentral.qmu.ac.uk/s/els\" title=\"Student Central : Effective Learning Service\">book an appointment slot on Student Central</a>.</p>\n<p>For any brief queries, the ELS team can be contacted on <a href=\"mailto:els@qmu.ac.uk\">els@qmu.ac.uk</a> for students who have English as their first language, and <a href=\"mailto:elsinternational@qmu.ac.uk\">elsinternational@qmu.ac.uk</a>  for students who don’t have English as their first language.</p>\n<p><strong>Finance Office</strong></p>\n<p>The Finance Office supports students paying for tuition and accommodation fees. If you experience any difficulties with payments then please email <a href=\"mailto:creditcontroller@qmu.ac.uk\">creditcontroller@qmu.ac.uk</a></p>\n<p>Finance Office Reception will be open Mondays and Tuesdays 9.00am to 5.00pm. Outwith these times they can be contacted via email at <a href=\"mailto:financeoffice@qmu.ac.uk\">financeoffice@qmu.ac.uk</a></p>\n<p><strong>International Student Support</strong></p>\n<p>Online drop in sessions are taking place on a Monday, Wednesday and Friday. If you are an exchange student, or an international student, joining instructions and dates and times of sessions will be sent to you at your QMU student email.  These details will also be published on our QMU International Facebook page. Please know that you can reach out to us with any questions at <a href=\"mailto:International@qmu.ac.uk\">International@qmu.ac.uk</a>.</p>\n<p><strong>Library</strong></p>\n<p>Our Liaison Librarians are working from home, but available to help you with any queries you might have via email in the first instance. Helpdesk staff are available for contact by email. For Library queries, please contact <a href=\"mailto:lrchelp@qmu.ac.uk\">lrchelp@qmu.ac.uk</a>, and for all other enquiries please <a href=\"mailto:assist@qmu.ac.uk\">assist@qmu.ac.uk</a>.</p>\n<p>Find more information on <a href=\"/study-here/learning-facilities/library/coronavirus-updates-lrc-11th-january-2021/\" title=\"Library operations\">Library operations during the pandemic.</a></p>\n<p><strong>QM Cares – support for Care Experienced, Carers and Estranged Students</strong></p>\n<p>Callum Maguire, our Head of Widening Participation and Outreach, will be continuing to offer care experienced, student carers and estranged students support, advice and guidance. Please visit the following dedicated support website pages for more information:</p>\n<p><a href=\"/study-here/student-services/support-for-care-leavers/\" title=\"Care leaver support\">Support for care leavers</a></p>\n<p><a href=\"/study-here/student-services/support-for-student-carers/\" title=\"Student carer support\">Support for student carers</a></p>\n<p><a href=\"/study-here/student-services/support-for-estranged-students/\" title=\"Estranged student support\">Support for estranged students</a></p>\n<p>Please do not hesitate to email Callum directly via: <a href=\"mailto:cmaguire@qmu.ac.uk\">cmaguire@qmu.ac.uk</a></p>\n<p><strong>School Office and Registry</strong></p>\n<p>The pop-up reception desk currently located in the LRC will be suspended with effect from Monday 25<sup>th</sup> January 2021.</p>\n<p>School Office and Registry staff continue to be on hand via email to answer your queries.</p>\n<p>Please contact <a href=\"mailto:schooloffice@qmu.ac.uk\">schooloffice@qmu.ac.uk</a> for queries relating to module registration, student status letters, extenuating circumstances, assessment, feedback and module results.</p>\n<p>Registry staff can be contacted at <a href=\"mailto:registry@qmu.ac.uk\">registry@qmu.ac.uk</a> for queries about matriculation, student cards, tuition fees, funding, graduation and Boards of Examiners decisions.</p>\n<p>Whilst we may not be able to provide you with hard copy documentation at this time, we will make every effort to provide you with an alternative version by email.</p>\n<p><strong>Uniforms, badges &amp; other placement-related requirements for Health Sciences students</strong></p>\n<p>Uniforms, badges, and other pre-placement and placement interactions are ongoing for relevant Health Sciences students.</p>\n<p>Uniforms and badges are being delivered from external suppliers, in time for students’ first placements. You will be contacted as a cohort, when these are available.</p>\n<p>Should you require to make an appointment to see one of the Pre-Placement/Placement Team to collect any of these items outwith your cohort, you can do this on a Monday or Wednesday afternoon, <a href=\"https://calendly.com/qmu-ppso/ppso-1-1\" title=\"Calendly appointment booking\">via this Calendly link</a>, which allows us to make appointments to manage numbers in line with Covid-19 safety requirements for students and staff.</p>\n<p>Should you be unable to attend at any of these times, please contact <a href=\"mailto:PPSO@qmu.ac.uk\">PPSO@qmu.ac.uk</a> , where it may be possible to arrange another time, with prior notice.  </p>\n<p><strong>Sports Centre </strong></p>\n<p>The Sports Centre will be closed while the East Lothian area remains in level 4 restrictions.  We can’t wait to welcome you back into the Centre, but in the meantime, please visit our <a href=\"https://en-gb.facebook.com/pages/category/Fitness-Trainer/Queen-Margaret-University-Sports-Centre-162366163800862/\">Facebook page</a> for relevant information, fitness challenges and our ‘Workout of the Week’ to help inspire you to continue your fitness training.  Information is also available on <a href=\"https://www.browzer.co.uk/qmu/tag/sports\">Browzer</a>.</p>\n<p>General information about the Sports Centre and our latest updates relating to Covid 19 is available on the <a href=\"/campus-life/qmu-sports-centre/\" title=\"QMU Sports Centre\">Sports Centre section</a> of our website.</p>\n<p>The Sports Team can be contacted at <a href=\"mailto:sportsreception@qmu.ac.uk\">sportsreception@qmu.ac.uk</a> should you have any other fitness related queries.</p>\n<p><strong>Student Funding Advice</strong></p>\n<p>The Student Funding Adviser is available to answer questions that you may have regarding your current financial situation. Please book an appointment via student central or email <a href=\"mailto:studentfunding@qmu.ac.uk\">studentfunding@qmu.ac.uk</a>. The <a href=\"/study-here/student-services/student-funding-service/\" title=\"Student Funding Service\">Student Funding service</a> also administers a variety of grant funds to support students who are experiencing financial hardship.</p>\n<p>In addition, this year we have a technology support fund which supports students who does not have access to a computer. The fund provides laptops to those students who are in need and who qualify. To apply email <a href=\"mailto:technologysupportfund@qmu.ac.uk\">technologysupportfund@qmu.ac.uk</a> </p>\n<p><strong>Students’ Union (HelpZone)</strong> </p>\n<p>Your Students’ Union (SU) provides independent and confidential support. The SU team remains available for general student queries and for support with academic related issues. The Help Zone specialises in supporting academic related issues, including Extenuating Circumstances, Academic Appeals, Complaints, Disciplinary processes and Fitness to Practice. There’s information on the <a href=\"https://www.qmusu.org.uk/\" title=\"QMU Student Union\">QMU Students' Union website</a>. </p>\n<p>The SU Office and C-Card service is open from 10am – 2pm Monday to Friday.  The best way to contact us is by e-mailing <a href=\"mailto:union@qmu.ac.uk\">union@qmu.ac.uk</a> or you can <a href=\"https://outlook.office365.com/owa/calendar/StudentUnionQMU@qmu.onmicrosoft.com/bookings/\" title=\"Student Union appointment booking\">book an appointment online</a>. </p>\n<p><strong>Studiosity</strong></p>\n<p>For all level one students, and students at other levels on selected programmes, QMU has partnered with <a href=\"/study-here/learning-facilities/it-services/learning-and-technologies/studiosity-academic-writing-feedback-queen-margaret-university/\"><strong>Studiosity</strong></a>, an external online service accessed via the Hub, to provide 24/7 constructive feedback on key elements of academic writing. Studiosity will review your draft work and give you quick feedback about how to improve your academic writing style.</p>\n<p><strong>Togetherall</strong></p>\n<p>QMU is working with <a href=\"https://togetherall.com/en-gb/\" title=\"togetherall\"><strong>togetherall</strong></a> (previously Big White Wall) to provide a supportive online community. <strong>togetherall</strong> is a free digital mental health support service which is available online, 24/7, and is completely anonymous so you can express yourself freely and openly. togetherall is available to all students at QMU and you can sign up using your QMU email address.</p>\n<p><strong>Wellbeing Service</strong> </p>\n<p>Our Wellbeing Adviser offers students wellbeing support through appointments online and in person. The <a href=\"http://www.qmu.ac.uk/study-here/student-services/wellbeing-service\" title=\"Wellbeing Service\">Wellbeing service</a> supports students with their mental health and wellbeing and provides support for a variety of issues such as anxiety and stress, worries about your studies, drugs and alcohol issues etc.</p>\n<p>You can book an appointment with the wellbeing advisor via Student Central or by emailing the service on <a href=\"mailto:wellbeing@qmu.ac.uk\">wellbeing@qmu.ac.uk</a> </p>\n<p>Irene Hynd</p>\n<p>University Secretary</p>\n<p>22 January 2021</p>\n<p> </p>\n<p>For staff:</p>\n<p>Dear staff</p>\n<p><strong>Chat with the Principal</strong></p>\n<p>Thank you to everyone who attended Monday’s Chat with the Principal session. For those who couldn’t attend, there is an <a href=\"https://myshare.qmu.ac.uk/news/Lists/Posts/Post.aspx?ID=1755\">audio recording (intranet link)</a>.</p>\n<p><strong>Scottish Government Q&amp;As for students</strong></p>\n<p>The <a href=\"https://www.studentinformation.gov.scot/coronavirus/term-two\">Scottish Government has now published Q&amp;As for students on semester two</a>. The Q&amp;As include advice on when students can return, student accommodation and travel.  Key points are reflected in our own coronavirus FAQs. As you will know from my <a href=\"/coronavirus/updates/\">last update</a> (22 January), we can’t yet confirm details of the staggered return to in-person teaching from 22 February for those currently studying online, but I can reassure you that we will give you as much notice as possible.</p>\n<p><strong>Other updates from the Scottish Government</strong></p>\n<p>Earlier this week, the Scottish Government announced an additional £30m funding for the higher education sector, including £20 million for additional student support and £10 million to universities to mitigate the additional costs of refunding student accommodation fees.  It will be a little time before we know what this means specifically for QMU.</p>\n<p><strong>On-campus COVID testing</strong></p>\n<p>Today is the last asymptomatic student testing session on campus for the moment. In due course, we will announce further testing dates, aligned with the staggered return to face to face teaching and demand levels.</p>\n<p><strong>Vaccination centre on campus</strong></p>\n<p>There is growing interest in the vaccination centre on campus, now that construction is well underway and the authorities have issued the first invitations to appointments.  As you will appreciate, this centre is being run by NHS Lothian, and not the University. If any member of the community has questions about the virus or the vaccination centre based at QMU, we would ask that you direct them to the NHS’s COVID vaccination helpline on 0800 030 8013.</p>\n<p><strong>Update on the full range of student services available at this time</strong></p>\n<p>Also today, you will have received a Moderator message with an updated summary of the full range of support services for students across the University and how to contact them. From Monday 25 January some of the service reception points have been temporarily closed or are operating on reduced opening hours. However, each support service remains open and accessible to all students, whether studying on campus or remotely.  You can find a copy of the message on the <a href=\"https://myshare.qmu.ac.uk/services/campus-commercial-services/covid19/SitePages/Home.aspx?RootFolder=%2Fservices%2Fcampus%2Dcommercial%2Dservices%2Fcovid19%2FShared%20Documents%2FStaff%2DSpecific%20Communications%20%28see%20also%20staff%20and%20student%20updates%20on%20the%20coronavirus%20web%20pages%29&amp;FolderCTID=0x012000C1132186DEE92D428CC43D5EFC1B31AF&amp;View=%7B9840A612%2D80E9%2D4272%2D941B%2DEB989655D2B1%7D\">COVID section of the intranet</a> (in the documents folder on that site, under staff messages).</p>\n<p><strong>Advice for students who need to come to the campus</strong></p>\n<p>We are aware of a small number of students who have been challenged by the authorities when travelling to campus to attend face-to-face classes.  Any student who is challenged in this way and who needs to attend campus for face-to-face teaching can request an official letter from the University confirming that they have classes on campus. To do so, they should contact the School Office. If a student is travelling to campus for a welfare appointment or to use the library, they can show the authorities their online booking. </p>\n<p><strong>QMYouMove </strong></p>\n<p>In the course of today, the Students’ Union will share details of ‘QMYouMove’, a six week activity challenge for students, staff and the wider QMU community, which will start next week. I know there is already quite a lot of interest in this initiative, as we all try to keep ourselves motivated to get fresh air and exercise during the current COVID restrictions. </p>\n<p><strong>Interesting research going on at QMU</strong></p>\n<p>You might also find it cheering to read about some of the fascinating and highly relevant research projects going on right now within the University, including projects directly associated with COVID.  We’ve created a section of our website bringing together <a href=\"/{localLink:umb://document/cc05e446ed6542dd99cfa00599b78d88}\" title=\"Covid-19\">projects funded by the Scottish Government to help mitigate of effects of the pandemic on research</a>.  There, you can learn, for example, how we are exploring ‘<a href=\"/{localLink:umb://document/665c1315ef6046b69232a8220bfe694c}\" title=\"Film festivals, audiences and Covid-19; Crisis, community and digital comeback.\">Film festivals, audiences and Covid-19; crisis, community and digital comeback.’</a> and ‘<a href=\"/{localLink:umb://document/adc523e1b7a7459589679d1a88599ac1}\" title=\"Community, health and social care system stressors and coping mechanisms during  COVID 19 in Edinburgh, Scotland\">Community, health and social care system stressors and coping mechanisms during COVID-19’</a>. Congratulations to all the staff whose projects are being supported by this Scottish Government funding.</p>\n<p>Malcolm G Cutt</p>\n<p>Director of Operations and Finance</p>\n<p> </p>\n<p> </p>"
    },
    {
      "contentTypeKey": "216ea22b-01af-4645-8972-5766bbd75b6c",
      "udi": "umb://element/210061870f914c4094588af15deb8da8",
      "title": "22 January 2021",
      "content": "<p>22 January 2021</p>\n<p>Students</p>\n<p>Latest update from the Scottish Government</p>\n<p>Since my last update, the First Minister has announced that <a rel=\"noopener\" href=\"https://www.gov.scot/news/review-of-restrictions/\" target=\"_blank\">current coronavirus restrictions will continue until at least the middle of February. A review of the position will be undertaken by the Cabinet in early February.</a></p>\n<p><strong>Update on our plans for the staggered return to teaching</strong></p>\n<p>As you know from my previous updates, we are planning for a staggered return of students who are currently studying entirely online to a blend of on-campus and online delivery, starting from 22 February, in line with Scottish Government guidance. You will appreciate that as the timing of this staggered return will be affected by Scottish Government restrictions, we can’t confirm details of it as yet, but I can reassure you that we will give you as much notice as possible.</p>\n<p>Online teaching for many students began this week. On campus, our pre-placement essential clinical skills sessions for Health Sciences students have started. These sessions have been going very well, with meticulously planned COVID adaptations, thanks to great efforts of academic and professional services staff across the University, and the cheerful support of students involved. Sessions have been running in the sports hall and other spaces to allow for physical distancing.</p>\n<p>Student Services and LRC updates</p>\n<p>We continue to provide student services based on the current restrictions and demand. Today you will receive a Moderator message with updates on how and when you can access student services.</p>\n<p>Earlier in the week, we announced some changes to the LRC ‘click and collect’ system. The ‘Click’ process remains the same but books for collection are now available during opening hours (8am-9pm, 7 days a week) from a trolley placed at the Helpdesk. After collection, you should still issue the books, using the self-service machines in the usual way.</p>\n<p>Online events to entertain and inform you</p>\n<p>As part of its work to provide opportunities for social engagement and interaction outside of your studies, and to help minimise social isolation, the Students’ Union has signed up to an <a rel=\"noopener\" href=\"https://qmusuevents.native.fm/\" target=\"_blank\">online events platform</a> and has been delighted with the uptake to the events so far. All events are live, and most have an interactive element, ranging from a virtual Korean cookery workshop to ‘Dick and Dom Go Virtual’.</p>\n<p>The Students’ Union-hosted online Q&amp;A session this week went very well too. You can find the <a rel=\"noopener\" href=\"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=3f29av9tK3A.&amp;feature=youtu.be\" target=\"_blank\" data-anchor=\"?v=3f29av9tK3A.&amp;feature=youtu.be\">recording of this event online</a>, and also a recording of the <a rel=\"noopener\" href=\"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=bbu_JKcL3jw.&amp;feature=youtu.be\" target=\"_blank\" data-anchor=\"?v=bbu_JKcL3jw.&amp;feature=youtu.be\">Q&amp;A focused specifically on placements for Health Sciences students.</a></p>\n<p>Funds supporting students in financial difficulty</p>\n<p>We are conscious that the current restrictions may be exacerbating financial issues for some students. Do remember that the University has <a href=\"/{localLink:umb://document/ad8fc076737d4365941e1ad4c0445c77}\" title=\"Student Funding Service\" data-udi=\"umb://document/8d1cc8b1998a4458850dee94d77906fa\">several funds that support students who find themselves in financial difficulties</a> during their studies. These are the Discretionary Fund (formerly the Hardship Fund) which covers all UK students, the Nursing Discretionary Fund</p>\n<p>covering Nursing students and the International Hardship Fund to which students from outside the UK can apply. The Childcare Fund can support students who have registered childcare costs. In addition, the University has received funding from the Scottish Government to support students that find themselves in ‘digital poverty’. This means that through our Technology Support Fund we can loan laptops to students that cannot afford to purchase a device, in order to support online learning. For further information please <a rel=\"noopener\" href=\"mailto:technologysupportfund@qmu.ac.uk\" target=\"_blank\">email technologysupportfund@qmu.ac.uk.</a></p>\n<p>Remember FACTS</p>\n<p>Sincere thanks for your continued patience and forbearance at this time; and for remembering FACTS: face coverings; avoid crowded places, clean your hands and surfaces regularly; two metre social distancing; and self-isolate and<a rel=\"noopener\" href=\"https://www.nhsinform.scot/campaigns/test-and-protect#:~:text=Test%20and%20Protect%20is%20Scotland%27s%20approach%20to%20preventing,into%20practice%20the%20test%2C%20trace%2C%20isolate%2C%20support%20strategy.#:~:text=Test%20and%20Protect%20is%20Scotland%27s%20approach%20to%20preventing,into%20practice%20the%20test%2C%20trace%2C%20isolate%2C%20support%20strategy.\" target=\"_blank\"> book a test if you develop coronavirus symptoms.</a></p>\n<p>Staff</p>\n<p>Latest update from the Scottish Government</p>\n<p>Since my last update, the First Minister has announced that <a rel=\"noopener\" href=\"https://www.gov.scot/news/review-of-restrictions/\" target=\"_blank\">current coronavirus restrictions will continue until at least the middle of February. A review of the position will be undertaken by the Cabinet in early February.</a></p>\n<p>Update on our plans for the staggered return to teaching</p>\n<p>As you know from my previous updates, we are planning for a staggered return of students who are currently studying entirely online to a blend of on-campus and online delivery, starting from 22 February, in line with Scottish Government guidance. Although the Scottish Government have now provided <a rel=\"noopener\" href=\"https://www.gov.scot/publications/coronavirus-covid-19-universities-colleges-and-student-accommodation-providers/pages/temporary-lockdown-guidance/\" target=\"_blank\">updated coronavirus guidance for higher education</a> (with FAQs for students expected to follow), we can’t confirm details of the staggered return as yet, as our plans are affected by evolving Scottish Government restrictions. However, in my COVID update to students today, I have reassured them that we will give them as much notice as possible of any changes.</p>\n<p>As those of you involved will know, online teaching for many students began this week. Sincere thanks to all staff involved in moving classes online, and to the TEL staff for their technical advice and support.</p>\n<p>On campus, our pre-placement essential clinical skills sessions have started. These sessions have been going very well, with meticulously planned COVID adaptations, thanks to great efforts of academic and professional services staff across the University, and the cheerful support of students involved. Sessions have been running in the sports hall and other spaces to allow for physical distancing.</p>\n<p>Chat with the Principal session</p>\n<p>I will take this opportunity to remind you of this coming <a rel=\"noopener\" href=\"https://myshare.qmu.ac.uk/news/Lists/Posts/Post.aspx?ID=1728\" target=\"_blank\" data-anchor=\"?ID=1728\">Monday’s Chat with the Principal session,</a> details of which you can find on the intranet.</p>\n<p>Supporting students</p>\n<p>We continue to provide student services based on the current restrictions and demand. Today you will receive a Moderator message with updates on student services, and, earlier in the week, we announced some changes to the LRC ‘click and collect’ system.</p>\n<p>As part of its work to provide opportunities for social engagement and interaction outside of students’ studies, and to help minimise the social isolation many students will be experiencing as a result of the current restrictions, the Students’ Union has signed up to an <a rel=\"noopener\" href=\"https://qmusuevents.native.fm/\" target=\"_blank\">online events platform</a> and has been delighted with the uptake to the events so far. All events are live and most have an interactive element.</p>\n<p>The Students’ Union-hosted online student Q&amp;A session this week went very well too. You can find the<a rel=\"noopener\" href=\"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=3f29av9tK3A.&amp;feature=youtu.be\" target=\"_blank\" data-anchor=\"?v=3f29av9tK3A.&amp;feature=youtu.be\"> recording of this event online,</a> and also a recording of the<a rel=\"noopener\" href=\"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=bbu_JKcL3jw.&amp;feature=youtu.be\" target=\"_blank\" data-anchor=\"?v=bbu_JKcL3jw.&amp;feature=youtu.be\"> Q&amp;A focused specifically on placements for Health Sciences students.</a></p>\n<p>We are conscious that the current restrictions may be exacerbating financial issues for some students. In my update to students, I remind them that the University has several funds that support students who find themselves in financial difficulties during their studies. These are the Discretionary Fund (formerly the Hardship Fund) which covers all UK students, the Nursing Discretionary Fund covering Nursing students and the International Hardship Fund to which students from outside the UK can apply. The Childcare Fund can support students who have registered childcare costs. In addition, the University has received funding from the Scottish Government to support students that find themselves in ‘digital poverty’. This means that through our Technology Support Fund we can loan laptops to students that cannot afford to purchase a device, in order to support online learning. For further information please <a href=\"mailto:technologysupportfund@qmu.ac.uk%20&lt;technologysupportfund@qmu.ac.uk&gt;;\">email technologysupportfund@qmu.ac.uk</a></p>\n<p>Updated risk assessment</p>\n<p>As you will know from previous updates, we have undertaken a full review of our University-wide risk assessment and various local risk assessments, to take account of the new restrictions and the potential risks posed by the new strain of coronavirus. <a rel=\"noopener\" href=\"https://myshare.qmu.ac.uk/services/campus-commercial-services/covid19/SitePages/Risk%20Assessments.aspx\" target=\"_blank\">The updated University-wide risk assessment is now published on the intranet.</a></p>\n<p>Many thanks again for all you are doing for the University, and in particular for our students, when many of you are facing challenges at work and in your personal lives.</p>\n<p> </p>"
    },
    {
      "contentTypeKey": "216ea22b-01af-4645-8972-5766bbd75b6c",
      "udi": "umb://element/514deef203f5445d89b230871c784555",
      "title": "15 January 2021",
      "content": "<p>Students</p>\n<p>I’ll begin this message by saying again, on behalf of all the Senior Leadership Team, that we understand how tough the heightened COVID restrictions are for you all, and that they are affecting every aspect of your lives. You have our commitment that we will continue to do everything we can to minimise the negative impact of the current situation on you, and we really are grateful for the positive way in which you are responding to what is required of you at this time.</p>\n<p>Since my last update, <a rel=\"noopener\" href=\"https://www.gov.scot/news/strengthening-lockdown-restrictions/\" target=\"_blank\">First Minister has announced further tightening of restrictions</a>.</p>\n<p>Current status of face to face teaching</p>\n<p>Decisions on the mode of course delivery remain as set out in the email from the Principal on 8 January. In summary, with the exception of essential face-to-face sessions for pre-registration Health Sciences courses and time-critical practical sessions for a very small number of courses in the School of Arts, Social Sciences and Management, all undergraduate course delivery is currently online. Scottish Government guidance indicates that this will continue to be the case until 22 February at the earliest, from which point there will be a staggered return to face-to-face delivery. Programme teams have been advising students where classes previously planned for face-to-face delivery have moved to online. All such changes are reflected in the published timetable.</p>\n<p>Delivery of teaching for the School of Health Sciences remains the same as that indicated in your updated timetables issued this week (week commencing 11 January). Delivery of teaching for the School of Arts Social Sciences and Management is detailed on the website.</p>\n<p>In line with the further tightening of Scottish Government guidance to universities, postgraduate provision will continue to be offered through blended provision, but until at least the end of January face-to-face teaching will only be scheduled for essential, time-critical activities that cannot be moved online. The balance between online and face-to-face teaching will depend on your programme. For postgraduate students in both schools, any further necessary changes will be communicated to affected students by the programme teams and reflected in your timetable. If, after consulting your timetable you are still unsure as to the current mode of delivery of your programme, please contact your programme leader for guidance.</p>\n<p>When to travel and return to term-time accommodation</p>\n<p>We are still planning on a staggered return of students who are currently studying entirely online to a blend of on-campus and online delivery from 22 February. This return will be based on evolving government guidance, and on prioritising those modules where in-person teaching is most essential and time critical. As I said in my last update, we suggest that you do not arrange travel to return to campus until details of this staggered return are published.</p>\n<p>As set out in my last update, and based on Scottish Government guidance, we advise that you should not return to your term-time accommodation more than 48 hours before your first face-to-face class. For international students and students travelling back to University from outside the UK, you should consider, if you are not already in the UK and have not yet booked your travel, staying in your home country and accessing your learning from home to start with. When you do return to your term-time accommodation, you must follow the <a rel=\"noopener\" href=\"https://www.gov.scot/publications/coronavirus-covid-19-student-home-visits/pages/students-returning-after-the-winter-break/\" target=\"_blank\">guidance on international travel, including COVID testing pre-travel, and quarantine requirements.</a> We are, of course, supporting students during quarantine as set out in our coronavirus <a href=\"/{localLink:umb://document/8b50dee69adb4c65a6b2b361f6f4244d}\" title=\"International\" data-udi=\"umb://document/8b50dee69adb4c65a6b2b361f6f4244d\">FAQs for international students</a>.</p>\n<p>Things to consider before you return to term-time accommodation</p>\n<p>When you know when you are returning, please <a href=\"/{localLink:umb://document/cea350dc0ea8419584357d9503e1a8a9}\" title=\"Student (COVID-19 Test) Booking\" data-udi=\"umb://document/cea350dc0ea8419584357d9503e1a8a9\">book a COVID test</a> (tests are also available to students who have stayed on campus over the winter break). We have announced testing dates up until the end of January and will add further dates based on demand.</p>\n<p><a rel=\"noopener\" href=\"https://www.studentinformation.gov.scot/coronavirus/students-returning-home\" target=\"_blank\">Before travelling, you should also look up travel advice found on Scottish Government’s Student Information Scotland website</a>, and the links from that site to <a rel=\"noopener\" href=\"https://www.gov.scot/publications/coronavirus-covid-19-guidance-on-travel-and-transport/\" target=\"_blank\">further travel advice.</a> As well as information for students in Scotland, that site includes links to <a rel=\"noopener\" href=\"https://www.gov.scot/publications/coronavirus-covid-19-public-health-checks-at-borders/\" target=\"_blank\">guidance on international travel and quarantine requirements</a>. Students travelling from England might find<a rel=\"noopener\" href=\"https://assets.publishing.service.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/950583/Students_returning_to_and_starting_higher_education_in_Spring_Term_2021_FINAL_v3.pdf\" target=\"_blank\"> travel guidance from the UK Government’s Department for Education useful.</a></p>\n<p>Social distancing and use of face coverings on campus</p>\n<p>Health Sciences students will be attending essential pre-placement sessions on campus from next week. If you are one of these students, please resist the temptation to gather in groups with your friends to chat before and after the sessions. We know it is hard, but we must all observe the rules on social gatherings at all times.</p>\n<p>Please remember that, as required by Scottish Government regulations, face coverings must now be worn in classrooms and other teaching spaces, in addition to all other communal spaces, including the LRC, except by those who are legally exempt for medical reasons. Face coverings will continue to be required in classrooms and other teaching spaces until we return to the Scottish Government’s COVID Level 3 or lower.</p>\n<p>The requirement to wear face coverings applies at all times, except when you are eating or drinking</p>\n<p>Reporting self-isolation and coronavirus</p>\n<p>Please also remember that you need to tell us if you are self-isolating, suspect you have coronavirus or have been diagnosed with coronavirus. Please: (1) Tell Security (0131 474 0000 ext 2222) - and also Accommodation (0131 474 0000 x 4902) if you live on campus; (2) Contact the School Office - <a rel=\"noopener\" href=\"mailto:schooloffice@qmu.ac.uk.\" target=\"_blank\">schooloffice@qmu.ac.uk.</a></p>\n<p>Online Q&amp;A sessions</p>\n<p>Today, the Students’ Union hosted a Q&amp;A on the subject of Health Sciences placements. Professor Fiona Coutts, the Dean of the School of Health Sciences, answered questions along with other Health Sciences staff. We will publish a link to the recording of that session as soon as possible.</p>\n<p>There will be a more general student Q&amp;A, again hosted by the Students’ Union, on 19 January at 3pm. This is an opportunity to put your questions about QMU, accommodation and student support to the Principal, the Head of Accommodation and the Head of Student Services. The session will take place online over<a rel=\"noopener\" href=\"https://eu.bbcollab.com/collab/ui/session/guest/489235f422cd4927b693dfeeab6bb34c\" target=\"_blank\"> Blackboard Collaborate.</a></p>\n<p>Access to the LRC</p>\n<p>Earlier this week, we published information on changes to how we are operating the LRC during the current COVID restrictions, including access arrangements, helpdesk hours and Effective Learning Service provision. You can find full details on the <a href=\"/{localLink:umb://document/f08ac065377b4acb8756163c9edb68d0}\" title=\"Coronavirus updates – LRC 11th January 2021\" data-udi=\"umb://document/f08ac065377b4acb8756163c9edb68d0\">library website.</a> In short, the Learning Resource Centre continues to be open to QMU staff and students from 8am to 9pm Monday to Friday with study spaces accessible during these periods. Please note that you need to book a study space, rather than simply arrive and find yourself a space.</p>\n<p>Student Services</p>\n<p>I will take this opportunity to remind you Student Services and Registry reception desks are staffed face to face daily between 10am and 2pm, as is Students’ Union reception desk. Face to face appointments are available with Student Services and the Students’ Union where this appropriate, as well as online appointments, of course.</p>\n<p>Catering</p>\n<p>As you know, our catering and shop services are limited to takeaway or delivery only right now. In light of the tighter COVID restrictions announced by the Scottish Government this week, Maggie's will still be open for pre-orders and deliveries across campus through the 'Round' app. If you are unable to use Round you will be able to order in person from outside Maggie’s – but we will not be allowing anyone access to the building. We continue to provide a wide range of menu items, and you will find the menu on the <a rel=\"noopener\" href=\"https://round.app/\" target=\"_blank\">Round app.</a></p>\n<p>Vaccine centre</p>\n<p>As previously communicated, <a href=\"/{localLink:umb://document/08ce3b2f6ef343d091f9cf342d6105c9}\" title=\"2020.12.24 - Queen Margaret University set to be one of the first venues in Lothian for the mass COVID-19 vaccination programme\" data-udi=\"umb://document/08ce3b2f6ef343d091f9cf342d6105c9\">part of our car park will be used as a NHS COVID vaccine centre from February.</a> The centre will be operated by NHS Lothian as part of the national community vaccination programme. In our role facilitating use of the car park for this centre, our first priority is the health and safety of the QMU community. We will therefore be communicating with you over the coming weeks to inform you of changes to the car park and to the flow of traffic coming into and out of the campus, as described in the Moderator message issued earlier this week. Please rest assured that, based on analysis of car park usage from last semester, we are confident that there will be plenty of parking space for QMU car park users while the vaccine centre is running.</p>\n<p>Please note too that there is currently some construction work ongoing around the campus, involving bus diversions as communicated by Moderator. This is to improve a cycle path and is not connected with the vaccine centre.</p>\n<p>Apologies for the length of this message, but there is quite a lot of information to share with you just now. Thank you again for your support.</p>\n<p>Staff</p>\n<p>Please may I ask you to read today’s COVID update to students (below) which includes an update on the position on online versus face-to-face class delivery, a reminder of the guidance on when students should return to their term-time address, and updates on library and student services.</p>\n<p>The Senior Leadership Team and Business Continuity Group have been struck by how well colleagues have been coping with the fast moving situation, and dealing with its impact on your working and home lives. Thank you to each and every one of you for all that you are doing at this challenging time.</p>\n<p>There are a few other things that I should highlight at this point.</p>\n<p>Staff with caring responsibilities: we are conscious that many of you are juggling work with caring responsibilities and home schooling. Our HR team has provided line managers with advice and guidance on how to support their team members in this situation along with links to useful external resources. Staff with caring responsibilities should not hesitate to share concerns with their line manager or HR partner. See also our updated <a rel=\"noopener\" href=\"/{localLink:umb://media/679aebfbaf6c46f88f05b9d4aeceff90}\" target=\"_blank\" title=\"Caring Responsibilities\">guidance for staff on caring responsibilities at home.</a></p>\n<p>Work on our COVID risk assessments: we hope that you will be reassured to hear that we have now made revisions to our COVID risk assessments taking account of the latest developments, and that we have received very helpful feedback on these revisions from trade union representatives. Work arising from this feedback is ongoing, focusing particularly on supporting staff who are carrying out essential on-campus activity and on the use of public transport for travel to work.</p>\n<p>Chat with the Principal event: we hope too that you can join this event on 25 January, as per the email invitation that you will have received. You can find the invitation on the <a rel=\"noopener\" href=\"https://www.gov.scot/publications/coronavirus-covid-19-guidance-for-laboratories-and-research-facilities/pages/where-we-are-now/\" target=\"_blank\">intranet.</a></p>\n<p>Catering on campus: As you know, our catering and shop services are limited to takeaway or delivery only right now. In light of the tighter COVID restrictions announced by the Scottish Government this week, Maggie's will still be open for pre-orders and deliveries across campus through the 'Round' app. If you are unable to use Round you will be able to order in person from outside Maggie’s – but we will not be allowing anyone access to the building. We continue to provide a wide range of menu items, and you will find the menu on the<a rel=\"noopener\" href=\"https://round.app/\" target=\"_blank\"> Round app</a>.</p>\n<p>Vaccine centre update: As previously communicated, <a href=\"/{localLink:umb://document/08ce3b2f6ef343d091f9cf342d6105c9}\" title=\"2020.12.24 - Queen Margaret University set to be one of the first venues in Lothian for the mass COVID-19 vaccination programme\" data-udi=\"umb://document/08ce3b2f6ef343d091f9cf342d6105c9\">part of our car park will be used as a NHS COVID vaccine centre from February</a>. The centre will be operated by NHS Lothian as part of the national community vaccination programme. In our role facilitating use of the car park for this centre, our first priority is the health and safety of the QMU community. We will therefore be communicating with you over the coming weeks to inform you of changes to the car park and to the flow of traffic coming into and out of the campus, as described in the Moderator message issued earlier this week. Please rest assured that, based on analysis of car park usage from last semester, we are confident that there will be plenty of parking space for QMU car park users while the vaccine centre is running.</p>\n<p>Please note too that there is currently some construction work ongoing around the campus, involving bus diversions as communicated by Moderator. This is to improve a cycle path and is not connected with the vaccine centre.</p>\n<p>Reporting self-isolation and coronavirus: if you are self-isolating or suspect you have coronavirus or have been diagnosed with coronavirus, it is important that you tell us. Please: (1) Tell Security (tel 0131 474 0000 ext 2222); (2) email the Head of Human Resources at <a rel=\"noopener\" href=\"mailto:nmackie@qmu.ac.uk\" target=\"_blank\">nmackie@qmu.ac.uk</a> (3) advise your line manager.</p>\n<p>Updated guidance for laboratories and research facilities: the Scottish Government has updated its <a rel=\"noopener\" href=\"https://www.gov.scot/publications/coronavirus-covid-19-guidance-for-laboratories-and-research-facilities/pages/where-we-are-now/\" target=\"_blank\">guidance for laboratories and research facilities.</a> The key changes include additional advice for those going to work, which came into force on 5 January, and reinforcing the message that for those in level 4 protection areas, or lockdown, only essential work should be carried out in labs and research facilities. The definition of what is deemed essential research is also set out - but definition of essential research and permissible activities has not been changed since the previous version of the guidance.</p>\n<p>I know that I speak for all the Senior Leadership Team when I say that you should not hesitate in approaching your SLT member, or a member of the Business Continuity Group, if you have any particular concerns about COVID that you feel you should draw to our attention at this time. Thank you for all your support.</p>\n<p> </p>\n<p> </p>\n<p> </p>\n<p> </p>\n<p> </p>\n<p> </p>"
    },
    {
      "contentTypeKey": "216ea22b-01af-4645-8972-5766bbd75b6c",
      "udi": "umb://element/d6dc00f80dcd413fae6710e2122f99aa",
      "title": "8 January 2021",
      "content": "<p>Dear students and staff</p>\n<p>First of all, thank you for your patience and forbearance as we work to resolve and clarify the issues arising out of the tighter national COVID restrictions. As I’m sure you can imagine, since the First Minister’s announcement on Monday of this week of a further temporary period of lockdown, a significant amount of effort has gone in to reassessing our arrangements to ensure the health, safety and wellbeing of our students and staff. We have also undertaken a full review of our University-wide risk assessment and various local risk assessments, to take account of the new restrictions and the potential risks posed by the new strain of coronavirus. </p>\n<p>As you know, these new restrictions are designed to help limit the spread of the new variant of the virus, and will be supported by the national vaccination programme that is currently being rolled out across the UK, including a <a href=\"/{localLink:umb://document/45682b7463bd406b850e359eb18dc4ab}\" title=\"2020.12.24 - Queen Margaret University set to be one of the first venues in Lothian for the mass COVID-19 vaccination programme\">planned vaccination centre on our own campus</a>. </p>\n<p>We do appreciate that the current situation may be causing you frustration and worry, whatever your personal circumstances, so we will attempt to provide answers to as many questions as we can, based on current information.</p>\n<p>We worked extensively with Universities Scotland and the Scottish Government before the Christmas break to implement a staggered return to on-campus teaching, to limit the numbers of students and staff that require to be on campus in the early stages of the second semester.  We have made arrangements for programmes which involve essential practical learning, including pre-placement practical skills for health students, to re-commence on campus. </p>\n<p>Following the First Minister’s statement earlier today and the publication of a statement from the Minister for Higher Education, we have made some further decisions on the mode of course delivery, to help provide as many of you as possible with greater certainty. I set out details of these decisions below and I would like to emphasise that semester two is starting on 11 January as planned, although the mode of delivery will be different from that initially planned in some cases. All adaptations to course delivery are designed to address the tighter national COVID restrictions introduced at the start of January and subsequent advice from government.</p>\n<p><strong>Decisions made on mode of course delivery</strong></p>\n<p>For those undergraduate students in the School of Arts, Social Sciences and Management (ASSaM) timetabled to begin face-to face-classes before 25th January, some of that delivery will now be moved online, and this will initially be communicated to you by the programme teams.  Any changes will also be reflected in your timetable shortly.</p>\n<p>For all other undergraduate students in ASSaM, ie those timetabled to return to face-to-face classes on or after 25th January, all teaching will now be online until after the timetabled reading week, which begins on 15<sup>th</sup> February. There will be a few changes to the advertised mode of delivery for undergraduate Health Sciences programmes. In due course, and informed by government guidance, we will provide details of a staggered return to face to face teaching for these students from week commencing 22nd February, prioritising those modules where in-person teaching is most essential. We suggest you do not arrange travel to return to campus until details of this staggered return are published. Your programme team will advise you of any changes and, as ever, please keep checking your timetable for any changes.  </p>\n<p>Whilst we do not anticipate any substantial changes to the mode of delivery of postgraduate level courses, some of that delivery may now be moved online, and this will initially be communicated to you by the programme teams.  Any changes will also shortly be reflected in your timetable.</p>\n<p><strong>Campus services</strong></p>\n<p>As previously communicated, l<a href=\"/study-here/learning-facilities/library/\">ibrary services</a> are operational, with some adaptation (details to be published on the <a href=\"/study-here/learning-facilities/library/\">library website</a> later today), and <a href=\"/campus-life/eat-and-shop-on-campus/\">catering</a> is available, on a takeaway basis. The atrium tiers and 1875 have been designated as a workplace canteen under the COVID regulations and so can be used by students and staff so long as they observe 2m social distancing. Face coverings should only be removed when eating and drinking.</p>\n<p><strong>When to return to term-time accommodation</strong></p>\n<p>Based on the latest government advice, we advise that you should not return to your term-time accommodation more than 48 hours before your first face-to-face class. Indeed in her media briefing today, the First Minister reiterated her message that the vast majority of students should stay at home just now. The exception to this is international students and students travelling back to university from outside the UK. These students can return to their term-time accommodation as they had already planned prior to the staggering of the resumption of face-to-face classes, as long as they follow the <a href=\"https://www.gov.scot/publications/coronavirus-covid-19-student-home-visits/pages/students-returning-after-the-winter-break/\">guidance on international travel, including COVID testing pre-travel, and quarantine requirements</a>.</p>\n<p><strong>COVID testing when returning to campus</strong></p>\n<p>If you are a student returning to term-time accommodation, you should, before you travel, book your first COVID test for as soon as possible after your return to term-time accommodation, via our <a href=\"/coronavirus/test/student-covid-19-test-booking/\">booking tool</a>.</p>\n<p>Please note that if you are travelling from overseas, this service does not remove your need to self-isolate (quarantine) on entry to the UK; and you should not have a test at the centre during your isolation period.</p>\n<p><strong>More on travel</strong></p>\n<p>We know that the advice on travel can appear confusing.  If you have questions, we recommend that you look up the travel advice found on <a href=\"https://www.studentinformation.gov.scot/coronavirus/students-returning-home\">Scottish Government’s Student Information Scotland website</a>, and the links from that site to <a href=\"https://www.gov.scot/publications/coronavirus-covid-19-guidance-on-travel-and-transport/\">further travel advice</a>. As well as information for students in Scotland, that site includes links to guidance on <a href=\"https://www.gov.scot/publications/coronavirus-covid-19-public-health-checks-at-borders/\">international travel and quarantine requirements</a>. Students travelling from England might find <a href=\"https://assets.publishing.service.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/950583/Students_returning_to_and_starting_higher_education_in_Spring_Term_2021_FINAL_v3.pdf\">travel guidance from the UK Government’s Department for Education</a> useful.</p>\n<p><strong>Information for students living in campus accommodation </strong></p>\n<p>If you are a student who has been asked to delay your return because the resumption of your face to face teaching has been postponed, you will be eligible for a rent reduction for the period of the delayed start, providing you do not actually return to your accommodation beforehand. Additional detail on how to apply for a rent reduction will be provided to students in campus accommodation directly by the accommodation team.</p>\n<p>Although we are advising that students should not return to their term-time accommodation until 48 hours before their first face to face class, students currently staying in University accommodation will of course continue to be supported and international students with pre-arranged travel may still arrive as they planned. Students unable to study at home can return to on-campus accommodation so long as that is permissible within the <a href=\"https://www.gov.scot/publications/coronavirus-covid-19-stay-at-home-guidance/\">exemptions to  the national regulations on travel at this time</a>  (such as if the return to term-time accommodation is to address mental health concerns or parental estrangement).</p>\n<p><strong>Wellbeing advice</strong></p>\n<p>Students, please do remember that staff are here to help you.  If you need support, do call on our <a href=\"/study-here/student-services/\">Student Services</a> team, or check out our <a href=\"/study-here/student-services/wellbeing-service/\">wellbeing resources</a>. We also plan to hold online question &amp; answer sessions for students in the next few days – please keep an eye on Moderator messages for more information about this. Also, from next week, the Student Services and Registry reception desks will be open daily between 10am and 2pm, as will the Students’ Union reception desk. Information on LRC helpdesk hours will be published soon on the <a href=\"/study-here/learning-facilities/library/\">Library</a> website and shared by the Library team on social media.  </p>\n<p>We are running induction sessions for new postgraduate students. Information can be found on the <a href=\"/{localLink:umb://document/a0f618c6732c488dac61072f7ee9aa8a}\" title=\"Induction for New Students\">induction programme list section of the induction website</a>. You can find the recording of the first of these sessions (a Health Sciences induction), which has already taken place, on the <a href=\"/{localLink:umb://document/a0f618c6732c488dac61072f7ee9aa8a}\" title=\"Induction for New Students\">induction website landing page</a>.</p>\n<p>Staff can find advice and support on working at home on our <a href=\"/at-home/\">QMU@Home</a> website.</p>\n<p>Please continue to look after yourself and those around you.  Thank you again for your understanding at this time.</p>\n<p>Paul</p>\n<p>Sir Paul Grice, FRSE, FAcSS, Principal and Vice-Chancellor</p>"
    },
    {
      "contentTypeKey": "216ea22b-01af-4645-8972-5766bbd75b6c",
      "udi": "umb://element/a516322edfc6405fa4fcdde31e776721",
      "title": "5 January 2021",
      "content": "<p>5 January 2021</p>\n<p>STUDENTS</p>\n<p>Dear students</p>\n<p>As mentioned in yesterday’s message, here is a further update, following the Senior Leadership Team’s review today of the First Minister’s announcement of tighter COVID restrictions, which apply from today.</p>\n<p>The campus remains open, and will remain open to all those who need to attend. Core face-to-face services to students and staff remain in place as per last semester, but the new restrictions mean that we can only offer a takeaway service in our catering outlets, and that changes are required to how our Learning Resource Centre operates (details will be published on the <a href=\"/{localLink:umb://document/71b99825061d4a2e8bd48daeb9d7cfe2}\" title=\"Library\">Library website</a>).  Face coverings are now required in all communal spaces on campus, including in classrooms, and will continue to be required until we return to the Scottish Government’s COVID Level 3 or lower.</p>\n<p>As you would expect, we are updating our risk assessments and processes to take into account the increased transmissibility of new variant of COVID.</p>\n<p>Where the new restrictions require us to make any changes to the delivery of teaching scheduled to begin <em>before</em> 25 January, we will endeavour to keep such changes to a minimum. Any changes will be communicated to you by your programme leader.  We also encourage you to continue to check your timetable. Programme start dates remain as previously advised.</p>\n<p>The Scottish Government Minister for Further Education, Higher Education and Science has written to University principals, indicating that those students set to return to face-to-face classes <em>on or after </em>25 January “should expect their return to be delayed, hopefully to a minimum”. We expect to receive more detailed guidance from the government on this in the next few days, and we plan to provide you with any updates to start dates within the next week, based on that guidance.  If your programme is scheduled to start on or after 25 January and you have yet to book your travel, you may wish to hold off from doing so until you receive our update. Otherwise, the advice on planning travel and your return to campus remains as per our update of <a href=\"/{localLink:umb://document/655742a31f25458f96f2d67439fb297a}\" title=\"Updates\">30 December</a>.</p>\n<p>Students who are shielding or who are unable to attend face to face lectures for other COVID-related reasons will be able to undertake their studies online. If you are in this situation, please contact Registry at registry@qmu.ac.uk. The exception to this is postgraduate pre-registration health care students who need to attend mandatory pre-placement face to face practical sessions by 25 January to be able to complete their programme of study within the required timeframe. If you have further questions about this, please contact Registry.</p>\n<p>As we have said before, international students and students travelling back to university from outside the UK can return to their term-time accommodation as planned, as long as they follow the <a href=\"https://www.gov.scot/publications/coronavirus-covid-19-student-home-visits/pages/students-returning-after-the-winter-break/\"><strong>guidance on international travel and quarantine requirements</strong></a>.  The international team will be pleased to help with any queries (<a href=\"mailto:international@qmu.ac.uk\">international@qmu.ac.uk</a>).</p>\n<p>We are conscious that students with children may have concerns about the impact of managing their studies alongside their childcare responsibilities. You will find guidance on this and other topics in our <a href=\"/{localLink:umb://document/2d74bbbb94e34467ab39bb1f82a83b2e}\" title=\"Students\">student coronavirus FAQs</a>.</p>\n<p>Thank you for your patience and understanding at this time. We do understand that you will have concerns and frustrations, and we are doing everything possible to resolve issues as quickly as possible.</p>\n<p>Malcolm G Cutt</p>\n<p>Director of Operations and Finance</p>\n<p>STAFF</p>\n<p>Dear colleagues</p>\n<p>Please see above for the message issued to students today, which is also relevant to you. </p>\n<p>As I said in my message yesterday, staff should work from home from except where their presence on campus is essential. The exception to this is that anyone who is ‘shielding’ should not attend the campus.</p>\n<p>As a reminder, there is a clear expectation that those members of staff whose role involves face-to-face interaction with students, and those members of staff whose presence on campus is required to enable that interaction, will be present on campus on those days when that presence is required. This will apply to all members of academic staff involved in teaching, to members of staff in professional services areas who provide a face-to-face service to students, and to those staff whose role is such that their presence on campus is required for them to perform it. By way of contrast, those members of staff whose role does not involve any direct face-to-face contact with students, and who are able to carry out the duties of their role remotely, are expected to continue to work from home for the time being.</p>\n<p>If you are not sure whether you presence is deemed essential on campus, please ask your Head of Division or Service for advice. In turn, and if required, they can seek advice from their SLT member as appropriate.</p>\n<p>As I said in my update last week, the Senior Leadership Team is conscious that some colleagues with younger school age children may have concerns associated with delivering face-to-face or synchronous teaching when schools are still closed/only delivering teaching online. Staff in this situation should contact their Head of Division.</p>\n<p>Staff members who consider that their home situation is such that they cannot work from home should speak to their Head of Division or Service in the first instance. Please remember that advice on working from home is available on the <a href=\"/{localLink:umb://document/5c334dbad1fc4fd298200b477c4b3a79}\" title=\"At Home\">QMU@Home section of the University website</a>.</p>\n<p>Thank you for your patience and understanding at this time.</p>\n<p>Malcolm G Cutt</p>\n<p>Director of Operations and Finance</p>"
    },
    {
      "contentTypeKey": "216ea22b-01af-4645-8972-5766bbd75b6c",
      "udi": "umb://element/fc4aa1b75fcf4235bf04966e49747d69",
      "title": "4 January 2021",
      "content": "<p>4 January 2021</p>\n<p>Dear staff and students</p>\n<p>We note the <a href=\"https://www.gov.scot/publications/coronavirus-covid-19-stay-at-home-guidance/\">First Minister’s announcement</a> of tighter COVID restrictions from midnight tonight until the end of January. The University’s Senior Leadership Team will meet tomorrow (Tuesday), and we will communicate with you more fully after that meeting.</p>\n<p>It is important to note that the First Minister said in her announcement that the Scottish Government will decide later this week whether to make any changes to the existing plan for the staggered return to higher education. In the meantime, the previously announced arrangements will continue to apply. Also, please note that travel for educational purposes is permitted, as it remains a valid exception to the more general travel restrictions.</p>\n<p>As staff are currently working from home except where their presence on campus is essential, we do not anticipate that today’s announcement will affect where staff will work from tomorrow, when the campus reopens. The one exception to this is that anyone who is ‘shielding’ should not attend the campus.</p>\n<p> </p>\n<p style=\"margin-bottom: .0001pt; line-height: normal;\">Malcolm G Cutt</p>\n<p style=\"margin-bottom: .0001pt; line-height: normal;\">Director of Operations and Finance</p>"
    },
    {
      "contentTypeKey": "216ea22b-01af-4645-8972-5766bbd75b6c",
      "udi": "umb://element/2fb03bf2e845484abd08ada49f4bf8fb",
      "title": "30 December 2020",
      "content": "<p style=\"color: #000000; font-family: Verdana,Arial,Helvetica,sans-serif; font-size: 14px; font-style: normal; font-variant: normal; font-weight: 400; letter-spacing: normal; orphans: 2; text-align: left; text-decoration: none; text-indent: 0px; text-transform: none; -webkit-text-stroke-width: 0px; white-space: normal; word-spacing: 0px;\">30 December 2020</p>\n<p style=\"color: #000000; font-family: Verdana,Arial,Helvetica,sans-serif; font-size: 14px; font-style: normal; font-variant: normal; font-weight: 400; letter-spacing: normal; orphans: 2; text-align: left; text-decoration: none; text-indent: 0px; text-transform: none; -webkit-text-stroke-width: 0px; white-space: normal; word-spacing: 0px;\"><strong>MESSAGE TO STUDENTS</strong></p>\n<p style=\"color: #000000; font-family: Verdana,Arial,Helvetica,sans-serif; font-size: 14px; font-style: normal; font-variant: normal; font-weight: 400; letter-spacing: normal; orphans: 2; text-align: left; text-decoration: none; text-indent: 0px; text-transform: none; -webkit-text-stroke-width: 0px; white-space: normal; word-spacing: 0px;\">Dear students</p>\n<p style=\"color: #000000; font-family: Verdana,Arial,Helvetica,sans-serif; font-size: 14px; font-style: normal; font-variant: normal; font-weight: 400; letter-spacing: normal; orphans: 2; text-align: left; text-decoration: none; text-indent: 0px; text-transform: none; -webkit-text-stroke-width: 0px; white-space: normal; word-spacing: 0px;\">Following on from my message of 22 December, I can confirm that arrangements for the start of teaching in semester two remain as published. If there are any changes, we will communicate these by Moderator, Facebook and our website.</p>\n<p style=\"color: #000000; font-family: Verdana,Arial,Helvetica,sans-serif; font-size: 14px; font-style: normal; font-variant: normal; font-weight: 400; letter-spacing: normal; orphans: 2; text-align: left; text-decoration: none; text-indent: 0px; text-transform: none; -webkit-text-stroke-width: 0px; white-space: normal; word-spacing: 0px;\">If you changed household over the winter break, guidance from the Scottish Government asks you not to return to your term-time accommodation until in-person (face-to-face) teaching for your course commences. This will help minimise the risk of transmission across the country and in the student community and make it easier for everyone to get tested quickly when they do return to university. </p>\n<p style=\"color: #000000; font-family: Verdana,Arial,Helvetica,sans-serif; font-size: 14px; font-style: normal; font-variant: normal; font-weight: 400; letter-spacing: normal; orphans: 2; text-align: left; text-decoration: none; text-indent: 0px; text-transform: none; -webkit-text-stroke-width: 0px; white-space: normal; word-spacing: 0px;\">We therefore suggest you take the following steps:</p>\n<ol style=\"color: #000000; font-family: Verdana,Arial,Helvetica,sans-serif; font-size: 14px; font-style: normal; font-variant: normal; font-weight: 400; letter-spacing: normal; orphans: 2; text-align: left; text-decoration: none; text-indent: 0px; text-transform: none; -webkit-text-stroke-width: 0px; white-space: normal; word-spacing: 0px;\">\n<li>Work out when your first face-to-face class is due to take place, by referring to your timetable. More general outline on start dates for face-to-face teaching is available on our website.  We recommend that you do not return to campus more than 48 hours before your first face-to-face class*.</li>\n<li>Plan your travel. The section of the <a href=\"https://www.studentinformation.gov.scot/coronavirus/students-returning-home\">Scottish Government’s Student Information Scotland website</a> concerned with the winter break includes advice on safe travel.</li>\n<li>Before you travel, book your first COVID test for as soon as possible after your return to term-time accommodation. The <a href=\"/{localLink:umb://document/44a5a8829d584640a662ba4a61848096}\" title=\"Student (COVID-19 Test) Booking\">booking tool</a> for our on-campus testing centre remains open through the festive period.</li>\n</ol>\n<p style=\"color: #000000; font-family: Verdana,Arial,Helvetica,sans-serif; font-size: 14px; font-style: normal; font-variant: normal; font-weight: 400; letter-spacing: normal; orphans: 2; text-align: left; text-decoration: none; text-indent: 0px; text-transform: none; -webkit-text-stroke-width: 0px; white-space: normal; word-spacing: 0px;\">*International students and students travelling back to university from outside the UK can return to their term-time accommodation in whatever way they planned prior to the staggering of the resumption of face-to-face classes, as long as they follow the <a href=\"https://www.gov.scot/publications/coronavirus-covid-19-student-home-visits/pages/students-returning-after-the-winter-break/\">guidance on international travel and quarantine requirements</a>. International students experiencing any problems with travel should see the advice on our <a href=\"/{localLink:umb://document/2d74bbbb94e34467ab39bb1f82a83b2e}\" title=\"Students\">international student coronavirus FAQs</a>.</p>\n<p style=\"color: #000000; font-family: Verdana,Arial,Helvetica,sans-serif; font-size: 14px; font-style: normal; font-variant: normal; font-weight: 400; letter-spacing: normal; orphans: 2; text-align: left; text-decoration: none; text-indent: 0px; text-transform: none; -webkit-text-stroke-width: 0px; white-space: normal; word-spacing: 0px;\">Please remember that the <a href=\"https://www.gov.scot/publications/coronavirus-covid-19-student-home-visits/pages/students-returning-after-the-winter-break/\">Scottish Government is asking that you voluntarily reduce your social mixing for 10 days before, and 10 days after, returning to university</a>. This means going out only for essential reasons including learning, food shopping and exercise. You should continue to do this after receiving negative COVID test results.</p>\n<p style=\"color: #000000; font-family: Verdana,Arial,Helvetica,sans-serif; font-size: 14px; font-style: normal; font-variant: normal; font-weight: 400; letter-spacing: normal; orphans: 2; text-align: left; text-decoration: none; text-indent: 0px; text-transform: none; -webkit-text-stroke-width: 0px; white-space: normal; word-spacing: 0px;\">Do remember that <strong>key facilities and support services remain available to students over Christmas</strong>. You can find a link to information on these services on our website homepage.</p>\n<p style=\"color: #000000; font-family: Verdana,Arial,Helvetica,sans-serif; font-size: 14px; font-style: normal; font-variant: normal; font-weight: 400; letter-spacing: normal; orphans: 2; text-align: left; text-decoration: none; text-indent: 0px; text-transform: none; -webkit-text-stroke-width: 0px; white-space: normal; word-spacing: 0px;\">I will take this opportunity to wish you a happy new year, though I do appreciate that our celebrations this year will be very different to the norm, and that we will all want to heed the First Minister’s message to stay at home for Hogmanay. If you need a reminder of the current rules, visit the <a href=\"https://www.gov.scot/coronavirus-covid-19/\" title=\"Scottish Government - Covid information\">Covid section of the Scottish Government's website</a>. Also on that site, you will find a link to <a href=\"https://clearyourhead.scot/\" title=\"Clear Your Head\">Clear Your Head</a>, which features practical tips on how to look after yourself and to connect with others just now.</p>\n<p style=\"color: #000000; font-family: Verdana,Arial,Helvetica,sans-serif; font-size: 14px; font-style: normal; font-variant: normal; font-weight: 400; letter-spacing: normal; orphans: 2; text-align: left; text-decoration: none; text-indent: 0px; text-transform: none; -webkit-text-stroke-width: 0px; white-space: normal; word-spacing: 0px;\">Malcolm G Cutt</p>\n<p style=\"color: #000000; font-family: Verdana,Arial,Helvetica,sans-serif; font-size: 14px; font-style: normal; font-variant: normal; font-weight: 400; letter-spacing: normal; orphans: 2; text-align: left; text-decoration: none; text-indent: 0px; text-transform: none; -webkit-text-stroke-width: 0px; white-space: normal; word-spacing: 0px;\">Director of Operations and Financ</p>\n<p style=\"color: #000000; font-family: Verdana,Arial,Helvetica,sans-serif; font-size: 14px; font-style: normal; font-variant: normal; font-weight: 400; letter-spacing: normal; orphans: 2; text-align: left; text-decoration: none; text-indent: 0px; text-transform: none; -webkit-text-stroke-width: 0px; white-space: normal; word-spacing: 0px;\"><strong>MESSAGE TO STAFF</strong></p>\n<p style=\"color: #000000; font-family: Verdana,Arial,Helvetica,sans-serif; font-size: 14px; font-style: normal; font-variant: normal; font-weight: 400; letter-spacing: normal; orphans: 2; text-align: left; text-decoration: none; text-indent: 0px; text-transform: none; -webkit-text-stroke-width: 0px; white-space: normal; word-spacing: 0px;\">Dear Colleagues</p>\n<p style=\"color: #000000; font-family: Verdana,Arial,Helvetica,sans-serif; font-size: 14px; font-style: normal; font-variant: normal; font-weight: 400; letter-spacing: normal; orphans: 2; text-align: left; text-decoration: none; text-indent: 0px; text-transform: none; -webkit-text-stroke-width: 0px; white-space: normal; word-spacing: 0px;\">Please see above the message that we sent to students today. We hope you find this update useful too.</p>\n<p style=\"color: #000000; font-family: Verdana,Arial,Helvetica,sans-serif; font-size: 14px; font-style: normal; font-variant: normal; font-weight: 400; letter-spacing: normal; orphans: 2; text-align: left; text-decoration: none; text-indent: 0px; text-transform: none; -webkit-text-stroke-width: 0px; white-space: normal; word-spacing: 0px;\">I will take this opportunity to highlight a few things of particular interest to staff:</p>\n<ul style=\"color: #000000; font-family: Verdana,Arial,Helvetica,sans-serif; font-size: 14px; font-style: normal; font-variant: normal; font-weight: 400; letter-spacing: normal; orphans: 2; text-align: left; text-decoration: none; text-indent: 0px; text-transform: none; -webkit-text-stroke-width: 0px; white-space: normal; word-spacing: 0px;\">\n<li>The Senior Leadership Team is aware that some colleagues with younger school age children may have concerns if they are scheduled to deliver face-to-face or synchronous teaching early in the semester, when schools are still closed/only delivering teaching online. We will deal with this on a case by case basis, after the campus re-opens on 5 January.</li>\n<li>We have every expectation that this upcoming semester our students will continue to take the responsible, community-focused approach to COVID restrictions that they demonstrated so strongly last semester. Around the time of the start of the new semester, we will, of course, be reminding them of key rules and restrictions, via social media etc. In addition, we are requiring our new students to sign up to our responsibility agreement, just as we did for all students joining or re-joining us in September.</li>\n<li>As you might have seen in the media or from our <a href=\"/{localLink:umb://document/45682b7463bd406b850e359eb18dc4ab}\" title=\"2020.12.24 - Queen Margaret University set to be one of the first venues in Lothian for the mass COVID-19 vaccination programme\">press release</a>, our campus is set to be one of the first venues in Lothian for the mass COVID-19 vaccination programme. It is expected that a section of the University’s car park will be used as a drive-through vaccination centre, capable of vaccinating up to 8,000 people a week at around 12 vaccination stations.</li>\n</ul>\n<p style=\"color: #000000; font-family: Verdana,Arial,Helvetica,sans-serif; font-size: 14px; font-style: normal; font-variant: normal; font-weight: 400; letter-spacing: normal; orphans: 2; text-align: left; text-decoration: none; text-indent: 0px; text-transform: none; -webkit-text-stroke-width: 0px; white-space: normal; word-spacing: 0px;\">Wishing you a happy Hogmanay, albeit a much less social occasion this year than usual!</p>\n<p style=\"color: #000000; font-family: Verdana,Arial,Helvetica,sans-serif; font-size: 14px; font-style: normal; font-variant: normal; font-weight: 400; letter-spacing: normal; orphans: 2; text-align: left; text-decoration: none; text-indent: 0px; text-transform: none; -webkit-text-stroke-width: 0px; white-space: normal; word-spacing: 0px;\"> </p>\n<p style=\"color: #000000; font-family: Verdana,Arial,Helvetica,sans-serif; font-size: 14px; font-style: normal; font-variant: normal; font-weight: 400; letter-spacing: normal; orphans: 2; text-align: left; text-decoration: none; text-indent: 0px; text-transform: none; -webkit-text-stroke-width: 0px; white-space: normal; word-spacing: 0px;\">Malcolm G Cutt</p>\n<p style=\"color: #000000; font-family: Verdana,Arial,Helvetica,sans-serif; font-size: 14px; font-style: normal; font-variant: normal; font-weight: 400; letter-spacing: normal; orphans: 2; text-align: left; text-decoration: none; text-indent: 0px; text-transform: none; -webkit-text-stroke-width: 0px; white-space: normal; word-spacing: 0px;\">Director of Operations and Finance</p>"
    },
    {
      "contentTypeKey": "216ea22b-01af-4645-8972-5766bbd75b6c",
      "udi": "umb://element/e648d67c64ba4a26b5d27f2e5d949185",
      "title": "22 December 2020",
      "content": "<p style=\"color: #000000; font-family: Verdana,Arial,Helvetica,sans-serif; font-size: 14px; font-style: normal; font-variant: normal; font-weight: 400; letter-spacing: normal; orphans: 2; text-align: left; text-decoration: none; text-indent: 0px; text-transform: none; -webkit-text-stroke-width: 0px; white-space: normal; word-spacing: 0px;\">22 December 2020</p>\n<p style=\"color: #000000; font-family: Verdana,Arial,Helvetica,sans-serif; font-size: 14px; font-style: normal; font-variant: normal; font-weight: 400; letter-spacing: normal; orphans: 2; text-align: left; text-decoration: none; text-indent: 0px; text-transform: none; -webkit-text-stroke-width: 0px; white-space: normal; word-spacing: 0px;\">Dear students and staff</p>\n<p style=\"color: #000000; font-family: Verdana,Arial,Helvetica,sans-serif; font-size: 14px; font-style: normal; font-variant: normal; font-weight: 400; letter-spacing: normal; orphans: 2; text-align: left; text-decoration: none; text-indent: 0px; text-transform: none; -webkit-text-stroke-width: 0px; white-space: normal; word-spacing: 0px;\">We have noted the changes announced by the Prime Minister and First Minister over the weekend. At the moment, please note that arrangements for the start of teaching in semester 2 remain as published, although these may change if there are any further changes to government guidance. As ever, we will update you on any significant changes through Moderator, Facebook and our website. We are also keeping our <a href=\"/{localLink:umb://document/2903c860f28b4ce5a34a763573cd0783}\" title=\"FAQs\">FAQs</a> updated as appropriate. Please keep checking for updates.  You will also find useful the Scottish Government’s updated advice for  <a href=\"https://www.studentinformation.gov.scot/coronavirus/students-returning-home\">students going home for the winter break and returning in the New Year</a>.</p>\n<p style=\"color: #000000; font-family: Verdana,Arial,Helvetica,sans-serif; font-size: 14px; font-style: normal; font-variant: normal; font-weight: 400; letter-spacing: normal; orphans: 2; text-align: left; text-decoration: none; text-indent: 0px; text-transform: none; -webkit-text-stroke-width: 0px; white-space: normal; word-spacing: 0px;\">Students continue to be permitted to travel home over the festive period, provided they only move once and stay in the same household until they return to their term-time household after the festive break. Travel for educational purposes continues to be an exception to general travel restrictions within the UK (although again this may change before January, in which case we would update you via Moderator, the website and Facebook).  We recognise that travel restrictions may also affect some students returning to QMU from outwith the UK. Students are advised to check the particular restrictions relating to travel from their home country to the UK. International students might also find our coronavirus <a href=\"/coronavirus/faqs/international/\">FAQs</a> for them useful.</p>\n<p style=\"color: #000000; font-family: Verdana,Arial,Helvetica,sans-serif; font-size: 14px; font-style: normal; font-variant: normal; font-weight: 400; letter-spacing: normal; orphans: 2; text-align: left; text-decoration: none; text-indent: 0px; text-transform: none; -webkit-text-stroke-width: 0px; white-space: normal; word-spacing: 0px;\">I will take this opportunity to remind you that key facilities and support services remain available to students over Christmas. </p>\n<p style=\"color: #000000; font-family: Verdana,Arial,Helvetica,sans-serif; font-size: 14px; font-style: normal; font-variant: normal; font-weight: 400; letter-spacing: normal; orphans: 2; text-align: left; text-decoration: none; text-indent: 0px; text-transform: none; -webkit-text-stroke-width: 0px; white-space: normal; word-spacing: 0px;\">Malcolm G Cutt</p>\n<p style=\"color: #000000; font-family: Verdana,Arial,Helvetica,sans-serif; font-size: 14px; font-style: normal; font-variant: normal; font-weight: 400; letter-spacing: normal; orphans: 2; text-align: left; text-decoration: none; text-indent: 0px; text-transform: none; -webkit-text-stroke-width: 0px; white-space: normal; word-spacing: 0px;\">Director of Operations and Finance</p>"
    },
    {
      "contentTypeKey": "216ea22b-01af-4645-8972-5766bbd75b6c",
      "udi": "umb://element/10383ebf68d74d7186a282ff7473cb47",
      "title": "19 December 2020",
      "content": "<p>19 December 2020</p>\n<p>Students </p>\n<p>As announced in the message from the University Secretary this morning, we are pleased to confirm that the University’s Asymptomatic Testing Centre will be up and running again in the New Year. On 7, 10, 11 and 15 January, the centre will offer student testing between 12 noon and 3pm, with extended time slots and dates to be announced in due course in line with demand. <a href=\"/{localLink:umb://document/44a5a8829d584640a662ba4a61848096}\" title=\"Student (COVID-19 Test) Booking\" data-udi=\"umb://document/cea350dc0ea8419584357d9503e1a8a9\">Booking is available via our website.</a></p>\n<p>The Scottish Government has issued new FAQs on semester two return – found in the ‘semester 2’ section of their <a rel=\"noopener\" href=\"https://www.studentinformation.gov.scot/coronavirus/students-returning-home\" target=\"_blank\">guidance on returning home</a>. You might like to note that the advice as to how long students should minimise social mingling before and after changing household at the start of next semester has changed; the advice now is that you should do so for ten days before and after your change of household (previously it was two weeks).</p>\n<p>Please note that, following Scottish Government guidance we have, in the last few days, revised some of the on campus in-person start times for undergraduate programmes in the School of Arts Social Sciences and Management. As ever, please check your timetable before making any travel plans.</p>\n<p><a href=\"/{localLink:umb://document/7ac62a9a0ac442c78ae93816a9e60377}\" title=\"Eat and Shop on Campus\" data-udi=\"umb://document/325db7270a194934b880113516c94538\">As of tonight, East Lothian moves into coronavirus level 3 again. This will have some impacts on campus catering, reflected in our Eat and Shop on Campus webpage.</a></p>\n<p>In the unlikely event that during the Christmas closure period there were to be any significant changes to Scottish Government advice affecting campus operations, we would update students and staff via the website, Facebook and Moderator.</p>\n<p>From today, a link to <a href=\"/{localLink:umb://document/4a7d426476164663ae5b9495f09d54a6}\" title=\"Christmas and New Year Arrangements\" data-udi=\"umb://document/4a7d426476164663ae5b9495f09d54a6\">information on facilities and support for student over the festive period appears on our website home page.</a> This is the same information that you have previously received by Moderator, and we hope you find it useful.</p>\n<p>I’ll take this opportunity to wish you all a very happy, peaceful and safe festive season, whatever your plans.</p>\n<p>Staff</p>\n<p>As announced in the message from the University Secretary this morning, we are pleased to confirm that the University’s Asymptomatic Testing Centre will be up and running again in the New Year. On 7, 10, 11 and 15 January, the centre will offer student testing between 12 noon and 3pm, with extended time slots and dates to be announced in due course in line with demand. <a href=\"/{localLink:umb://document/44a5a8829d584640a662ba4a61848096}\" title=\"Student (COVID-19 Test) Booking\" data-udi=\"umb://document/cea350dc0ea8419584357d9503e1a8a9\">Booking is available via our website.</a></p>\n<p>The Scottish Government has issued new FAQs on semester two return – found in the ‘semester 2’ section of their<a rel=\"noopener\" href=\"https://www.studentinformation.gov.scot/coronavirus/students-returning-home\" target=\"_blank\"> guidance on returning home.</a> You might like to note that the advice as to how long students should minimise social mingling before and after changing</p>\n<p>household at the start of next semester has changed; the advice now is that they should do so for ten days before and after their change of household (previously it was two weeks).</p>\n<p>As of tonight, East Lothian moves into coronavirus level 3 again. This will have some impacts on campus catering, reflected in our<a href=\"/{localLink:umb://document/7ac62a9a0ac442c78ae93816a9e60377}\" title=\"Eat and Shop on Campus\" data-udi=\"umb://document/325db7270a194934b880113516c94538\"> Eat and Shop on Campus webpage.</a></p>\n<p>Based on updated Scottish Government guidance, we have made some further changes to start dates of face to face undergraduate teaching in the School of Arts, Social Sciences and Management. The updated table of start dates is on the intranet. Students have received the <a rel=\"noopener\" href=\"https://myshare.qmu.ac.uk/services/campus-commercial-services/covid19/_layouts/15/WopiFrame2.aspx?sourcedoc=%7b61DE3CC3-D89D-41F0-A7B6-88A54B2A9A7B%7d&amp;file=Sem%202%20On%20Campus%20Start%20dates%202021%20final%20(revised%2016-12-20).docx&amp;action=default\" target=\"_blank\" data-anchor=\"?sourcedoc=%7b61DE3CC3-D89D-41F0-A7B6-88A54B2A9A7B%7d&amp;file=Sem%202%20On%20Campus%20Start%20dates%202021%20final%20(revised%2016-12-20).docx&amp;action=default\">updated timetable information.</a></p>\n<p>In addition, you might find it useful to know that, earlier this week, Scottish Government updated their <a rel=\"noopener\" href=\"https://www.gov.scot/publications/coronavirus-covid-19-guidance-for-laboratories-and-research-facilities/\" target=\"_blank\">guidance for laboratories and research facilities,</a> including those on university campuses, on safer working during the coronavirus pandemic.</p>\n<p>In the unlikely event that during the Christmas closure period there were to be any significant changes to Scottish Government advice affecting campus operations, we would update students and staff via the website, Facebook and Moderator.</p>\n<p>From today, a link to <a href=\"/{localLink:umb://document/4a7d426476164663ae5b9495f09d54a6}\" title=\"Christmas and New Year Arrangements\" data-udi=\"umb://document/4a7d426476164663ae5b9495f09d54a6\">information on facilities and support for student over the festive period</a> appears on our website home page. This is the same information that you have previously received by Moderator.</p>\n<p>Last week we published further information about the <a rel=\"noopener\" href=\"https://myshare.qmu.ac.uk/services/campus-commercial-services/covid19/_layouts/15/WopiFrame2.aspx?sourcedoc=%7b6BA46E74-CD75-4663-BCCA-747AC9976B9B%7d&amp;file=Wellbeing%20Survey%20Results%20presentation%20FINAL.pptx&amp;action=default\" target=\"_blank\" data-anchor=\"?sourcedoc=%7b6BA46E74-CD75-4663-BCCA-747AC9976B9B%7d&amp;file=Wellbeing%20Survey%20Results%20presentation%20FINAL.pptx&amp;action=default\">actions we have taken to address the feedback that you gave us in the Staff Wellbeing Survey which we ran earlier this year.</a> We have also published helpful guidance and supporting documents for staff who continue to work from home:Home Working</p>\n<p>I’ll take this opportunity to wish you all a very happy, peaceful and safe festive season, whatever your plans.</p>"
    },
    {
      "contentTypeKey": "216ea22b-01af-4645-8972-5766bbd75b6c",
      "udi": "umb://element/f4fbd2c320f544fa967de144ce4b0b4e",
      "title": "11 December 2020",
      "content": "<p>Staff</p>\n<p>You will want to see the full text of today’s COVID update to students, which appears below. As well as giving more detail on the Scottish Government’s guidance for the start of semester two, we provide reassurance that in the unlikely event that there were any changes to the guidance during the Christmas closure period, we would update students and staff via the website, Facebook and Moderator.</p>\n<p>Given the need to provide students certainty regarding semester two arrangements, it is imperative that the resumption of on campus teaching reflects the timing detailed in the information previously provided by the schools <a rel=\"noopener\" href=\"https://myshare.qmu.ac.uk/services/campus-commercial-services/covid19/_layouts/15/WopiFrame2.aspx?sourcedoc=%7bD9C55AA9-5EF5-435D-86B6-AB9075DFF1B9%7d&amp;file=Sem%202%20On%20Campus%20Start%20dates%202021%20final.docx&amp;action=default\" target=\"_blank\" data-anchor=\"?sourcedoc=%7bD9C55AA9-5EF5-435D-86B6-AB9075DFF1B9%7d&amp;file=Sem%202%20On%20Campus%20Start%20dates%202021%20final.docx&amp;action=default\">(link to detailed timetable information for staff on the COVID intranet site).</a></p>\n<p>In terms of updates for staff specifically, there is just one thing to note, as below.</p>\n<ul>\n<li>TEL training: <a href=\"/{localLink:umb://document/b5dc5187da8e4698964b4f7de87bb1a3}\" title=\"Module Preparation\" data-udi=\"umb://document/1db4c0dd811d4f3596ccd02ff5f4c725\">the winter TEL training programme has been launched,</a> enhancing and extending the training already provided over the summer, covering the HUB, Panopto and Collaborate, and now extending to supplier driven days from PebblePad, Turnitin and Blackboard. There is a<a rel=\"noopener\" href=\"https://outlook.office365.com/owa/calendar/QueenMargaretUniversity2@qmu.onmicrosoft.com/bookings/\" target=\"_blank\"> booking tool</a>.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Students</p>\n<p>The latest guidance from the Scottish Government</p>\n<p>As you will know from our email on Tuesday, the Scottish Government has asked all universities to make arrangements to stagger the date of return of UK undergraduate students to campuses at the start of the new semester in January. This is intended to reduce the risks of the transmission of COVID.</p>\n<p>In addition, the Scottish Government has asked that undergraduate students only return to university when their in-person teaching is scheduled to resume. However, if you need to come back to the university for health or wellbeing reasons, or because your home environment makes study difficult, or because you lack access to the technology you need to learn, you can return to your term-time address as you had planned.</p>\n<p>Furthermore, the Scottish Government asks students, on a voluntary basis, to reduce social mixing for two weeks before returning to University, and for two weeks afterwards.</p>\n<p>It is important to stress that only undergraduate students from Scotland and the rest of the United Kingdom are being asked to delay their return to campus. International students and students travelling back to university from outside the UK can return to their term-time accommodation as planned, as long as they follow the <a rel=\"noopener\" href=\"https://www.gov.scot/publications/coronavirus-covid-19-student-home-visits/pages/students-returning-after-the-winter-break/\" target=\"_blank\">guidance on international travel and quarantine requirements</a>.</p>\n<p>Postgraduate students should return to university as normal, and teaching will resume as currently planned.</p>\n<p>These new guidelines are neither rules nor laws, but they are requests from government designed to minimise the increased risks of the spread of COVID at the start of the semester. Wherever possible, we should do what we can to support them. <a rel=\"noopener\" href=\"https://www.gov.scot/publications/coronavirus-covid-19-student-home-visits/pages/students-returning-after-the-winter-break/\" target=\"_blank\">The full Scottish Government guidance is available on their website (and they plan to provide Q&amp;As for students).</a></p>\n<p>What will this mean at QMU</p>\n<p>If you are an undergraduate student, when you receive your timetable, (as some of you will already have done) you might find that, depending on your programme and level, your earlier classes in January might be delivered online rather than in person. This is to allow for the staggered return to campus in January for those studying at undergraduate level.</p>\n<p>Many of our undergraduate programmes are practical in nature, and include placement and other practical activity at the start of semester two, a significant volume of which is a prerequisite to subsequent placement activity. As a result, a high proportion of our delivery falls within the activity exempted under the Scottish Government guidance i.e. critical and time-sensitive learning, and work placements that cannot be delivered remotely or postponed.</p>\n<p>Postgraduate students will be unaffected by any changes.</p>\n<p><a href=\"/{localLink:umb://document/d1ff6c6ae4d64b76b0389621aa9718bf}\" title=\"Christmas Closure Dates\" data-udi=\"umb://document/4a7d426476164663ae5b9495f09d54a6\">All University services and facilities will be open from the very start of the semester, with special arrangements in place for the Christmas closure period as previously advised.</a></p>\n<p>We don’t expect the advice or guidance to change, but were it do so over the Christmas closure period, rest assured we would update you via Moderator, Facebook and our website.</p>\n<p>Students living in University accommodation</p>\n<p>A separate message will be sent out shortly from our Accommodation Office to students living in our on campus University accommodation which will address the implications of the Scottish Government request that some students delay their return to campus after the winter break.</p>\n<p>COVID testing</p>\n<p>As communicated earlier in the week, we will be offering asymptomatic COVID testing on campus in the new year for students returning to term-time accommodation. We will update you on the details as soon as we can. Please note that taking a COVID test will not exempt you from the general request to all students to reduce social mixing during the first two weeks you are back on campus.</p>\n<p>Thank you for your cooperation and understanding.</p>\n<p> </p>"
    },
    {
      "contentTypeKey": "216ea22b-01af-4645-8972-5766bbd75b6c",
      "udi": "umb://element/df2fb7d479b34b8c86edc11bf95da2c2",
      "title": "04 December 2020",
      "content": "<p><span class=\"lead\">Student COVID testing on campus</span></p>\n<p>Students now have just six more days to take advantage of our asymptomatic testing centre before it closes. Students and staff have reported being very impressed with the professional, friendly and efficient service on offer from our wonderful student testing team led by Nursing Senior Lecturer Ruth Magowan. The team came over very well in the STV TV coverage of its work. Thank you again for everyone involved in establishing and running the centre, staff and students. Thank you too to all the students who have taken up the opportunity to be tested, helping to protect their family, friends and the wider community.</p>\n<p>Students looking to book a place can do so on our testing website. There are also walk up appointments available before 4pm each weekday, and between 12 noon and 3pm at the weekend.</p>\n<p><span class=\"lead\">Planning for the start of the next semester</span></p>\n<p>With teaching drawing to a close for this semester, and with many students starting to return to their family home for the Christmas break, you will also be thinking ahead to the start of next semester. Early next week, we are expecting the Scottish Government to announce details of its approach to the return of students to campuses in the new year. As we have advised already, it seems likely that student testing will form part of the government’s plans. You will no doubt have seen that the UK Government has already announced its approach to the resumption of teaching next semester in England.</p>\n<p>We also recognise that some students will wish to remain on campus over the Christmas and new year period. You will have seen the separate message issued earlier today, which sets out the arrangements we are putting in place to support those students in particular, and also the support services which will be available to all students over the winter break period.</p>\n<p><span class=\"lead\">Laptop loans for students: a reminder</span></p>\n<p>I will remind you that the University has received funding from the Scottish Government to support students who do not have the funds available to buy a device that allows them to study online during the pandemic. Under the regulations of the scheme the University has purchased laptops which can be loaned out to students for the duration of their course.</p>\n<p>We realise that some students face particular financial difficulties and priority will be given to the same group that are a priority for the Discretionary (Hardship) Funds. These will be students who are care experienced, carers, estranged, single parents, young students in receipt of the young student bursary, and mature students in receipt of the mature student bursary. But applications are not limited to these students, and all applications will be looked at on a case by case basis.</p>\n<p>Please email <a rel=\"noopener\" href=\"mailto:technologysupportfund@qmu.ac.uk\" target=\"_blank\">technologysupportfund@qmu.ac.uk</a> if you wish to apply for the long term loan of a laptop, giving a brief explanation of your circumstances. You will then be sent the link to the short online application form along with information about the evidence you will need to submit to support your application. This will normally be evidence of funding from your funding authority (eg SAAS) and a recent bank statement.</p>"
    },
    {
      "contentTypeKey": "216ea22b-01af-4645-8972-5766bbd75b6c",
      "udi": "umb://element/560a2cef97304f0f8b64930b659e7a79",
      "title": "27th November 2020 ",
      "content": "<p>STUDENTS</p>\n<p>Our Asymptomatic Testing Centre will open on Monday 30 November. We are offering voluntary testing for those students who are not currently displaying any COVID symptoms, and who are planning to move home or to a different household over the winter break period. There has been a great uptake so far. <a href=\"/{localLink:umb://document/ce8c5f4b067647529811fd507b9beadb}\" title=\"Test\" data-udi=\"umb://document/76ac1807ad8a46a6967561f0dd7e94c6\">For more information on testing or to book, please visit our testing website.</a> Thank you to all the students who will be supporting the operation of the centre under the supervision of Senior Nursing Lecturer, Ruth Magowan.</p>\n<p>You might be interested in accessing the recording of the student questions and answers on the subject of testing (<a rel=\"noopener\" href=\"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=7Mom3mQywDg&amp;feature=youtu.be\" target=\"_blank\" data-anchor=\"?v=7Mom3mQywDg&amp;feature=youtu.be\">link to the Q&amp;A recording</a>).</p>\n<p>You will have seen the Moderator message of Tuesday (24 November) with information on Christmas closure and hand-in arrangements. As soon as we can, we will issue a message confirming the facilities and support services that will remain available to you over the festive break. In the meantime, you can find outline information in our <a href=\"/{localLink:umb://document/ce8c5f4b067647529811fd507b9beadb}\" title=\"Test\" data-udi=\"umb://document/df16ed2c10f94d29bc901be143733ee3\">coronavirus FAQs.</a> We continue to update the FAQs more generally as and when we have updated information to share.</p>\n<p>The Scottish Government has issued updated <a rel=\"noopener\" href=\"https://www.gov.scot/publications/coronavirus-covid-19-student-home-visits/pages/end-of-term-2020/\" target=\"_blank\">guidance on home visits, including returning home at the end of semester.</a> Included in this information is <a rel=\"noopener\" href=\"https://www.transport.gov.scot/coronavirus-covid-19/transport-transition-plan/advice-on-how-to-travel-safely/\" target=\"_blank\">guidance on travelling safely.</a> Again, we are reflecting this information in our FAQs.</p>\n<p>Thanks again to all of you who have downloaded the <a rel=\"noopener\" href=\"https://play.google.com/store/apps/details?id=gov.scot.covidtracker&amp;hl=en_GB&amp;gl=US\" target=\"_blank\" data-anchor=\"?id=gov.scot.covidtracker&amp;hl=en_GB&amp;gl=US\">Protect Scotland app.</a> A study by the Office for National Statistics across four sample universities (not including QMU) indicates that 67% of students have downloaded either this or the app used in England. These tracing apps are a really useful tool in reducing the spread of the virus.</p>\n<p>Looking ahead to the start of next semester, the Scottish Government has indicated that student testing is likely to form part of its plan for the return to campus in the new year. We await further details on this, and will let you know as soon as we know more.</p>\n<p>As we move towards the end of the semester and the shortest days of the year, tiredness and lack of daylight can take their toll on your wellbeing. Don’t forget the wellbeing resources available to you at the University. Our <a href=\"/{localLink:umb://document/35f6be9d3cfe4664b7ffe6d54165c449}\" title=\"Counselling Service\" data-udi=\"umb://document/bf2ecab16270469e9ff6df9417a4e9c5\">Counselling</a> and <a href=\"/{localLink:umb://document/8d2f92c8533d41ec9baa7182c2a76a9b}\" title=\"Wellbeing Service\" data-udi=\"umb://document/8ff9e5f46427448fbc4ef037e0c9e1e9\">Wellbeing</a> teams are providing both face-to-face support sessions and online/phone support. You can book an appointment either through <a rel=\"noopener\" href=\"https://studentcentral.qmu.ac.uk/students/login?ReturnUrl=%2f\" target=\"_blank\" data-anchor=\"?ReturnUrl=%2f\">Student Central</a> or by sending us an email. You can also contact your Personal Academic Tutor (names on the Student Portal). You might also want to sign up for <a href=\"/{localLink:umb://document/9577ea21bc8a4d63b2b403325b73943c}\" title=\"togetherall\" data-udi=\"umb://document/9577ea21bc8a4d63b2b403325b73943c\">Togetherall</a> which is available to you through the University. This is a digital mental health support service which is available online, 24/7, and is completely anonymous so you can express yourself freely and openly.</p>\n<p>Staff</p>\n<p>Our Asymptomatic Testing Centre will open on Monday. We are offering voluntary testing for those students who are not currently displaying any Covid symptoms, and who are planning to move home or to a different household over the winter break period. Pleasingly, there has been a great uptake so far. Many thanks indeed to everyone involved in setting up this centre at very short notice. It has been a huge undertaking, but, through everyone’s efforts, we are all set to go live.</p>\n<p>In our COVID update to students today, we confirmed that we will soon issue a message confirming the facilities and support services that will remain available to them over the festive break. In the meantime, they (and you) can find outline information on our plans in our<a href=\"/{localLink:umb://document/df16ed2c10f94d29bc901be143733ee3}\" title=\"FAQs\" data-udi=\"umb://document/df16ed2c10f94d29bc901be143733ee3\"> coronavirus FAQs</a>. We continue to update the FAQS more generally as and when we have updated information to share.</p>\n<p>We have also shared with students updated <a rel=\"noopener\" href=\"https://www.gov.scot/publications/coronavirus-covid-19-student-home-visits/pages/end-of-term-2020/\" target=\"_blank\">guidance from the Scottish Government on home visits, including returning home at the end of semester</a>. Included in this information is <a rel=\"noopener\" href=\"https://www.transport.gov.scot/coronavirus-covid-19/transport-transition-plan/advice-on-how-to-travel-safely/\" target=\"_blank\">guidance on travelling safely.</a></p>\n<p>We have also updated the <a href=\"/{localLink:umb://document/84daaed5f3d04cd09566859f91fb8d90}\" title=\"Applicants\" data-udi=\"umb://document/696372f9e70d444cbc31bf3cbebeb5da\">section of the coronavirus website aimed at applicants and offer-holders</a>, so that the information is more focused on January starts. Included in the new content are updates of the videos we launched in September on our campus adaptations and on the steps students need to take to keep safe.</p>\n<p>Looking ahead to the start of next semester, the Scottish Government has indicated that student testing is likely to form part of its plan for the return to campus in the new year. We await further details on this, and will let you know as soon as we know more.</p>\n<p>Thank you again for your contribution to the University at this time.</p>"
    },
    {
      "contentTypeKey": "216ea22b-01af-4645-8972-5766bbd75b6c",
      "udi": "umb://element/2dadd4d2e8a34393841fdaf113c8d986",
      "title": "20 November",
      "content": "<p><span class=\"lead\">STUDENTS</span></p>\n<p>We are making good progress on developing our COVID-19 testing site for asymptomatic students, which will be based in 1875 (food court) on campus. We will share more information on the arrangements shortly, including a number of job opportunities for students over the period of testing. In the meantime, a message for international students who are being asked to take a COVID test before they fly home for the Christmas break: please be aware that your airline might require a PCR test (available privately through a number of local pharmacies) rather than the lateral flow test variant being used for the student asymptomatic testing scheme.</p>\n<p>Alongside this, I will remind you of the request in the recent letter to you from the Scottish Government Minister for Further Education, Higher Education and Science that, if you are changing household over Christmas, you should voluntarily reduce your social mixing for two weeks before going home or changing household. This means going out only for essential reasons, such as for classes, shopping for food, and exercise. This is the advice for all of us in Scotland at this time, but it is most vital to those of you changing residence from a high COVID protection level area to a lower level, and those who are returning to households with vulnerable family members. The minister’s letter also highlighted the <a rel=\"noopener\" href=\"https://www.gov.scot/publications/coronavirus-covid-19-student-home-visits/\" target=\"_blank\">Scottish Government’s guidance on visiting home</a>. We are expecting “questions and answers” from the government on safe travel home for students, which we will of course share with you.</p>\n<p>I will also take this opportunity to highlight an amendment to the information on modes of delivery for next semester. The amendment is that IGHD courses will be delivered by blended learning, rather than fully face to face.</p>\n<p>We will be in touch as soon as we have more information on testing on campus. In the meantime, thank you for your continued patience.</p>\n<p><span class=\"lead\">STAFF</span></p>\n<p>Dear colleagues</p>\n<p>We are making good progress on developing our COVID-19 testing site for asymptomatic students, which will be based in 1875 (food court) on campus. The University Secretary, Irene Hynd, is leading a rapid action task force, with clinical support from Ruth Magowan, that is working at pace through all the legal, logistical, communication and compliance and staff resourcing issues. We will share more information on the arrangements shortly, including a number of job opportunities for students over the period of testing.</p>\n<p><a rel=\"noopener\" href=\"/{localLink:umb://media/3c9d6bfdb2d44bd3b0698bc6d2db5685}\" target=\"_blank\" title=\"Minister Letter To Students Strategic Framework And New Protection Levels\"> Earlier this week, we shared with students a letter to them from the Scottish Government Minister for Further Education,</a> Higher Education and Science. The letter provided a summary of the Scottish Government’s strategic approach to higher education at this time, a reminder of the<a rel=\"noopener\" href=\"https://www.gov.scot/publications/coronavirus-covid-19-student-home-visits/\" target=\"_blank\"> guidance for students on visiting home,</a> and advice to them on how to avoid spreading the risk if they are changing households over the winter break, with reference to the plans for offering COVID testing to students.</p>\n<p>I will also take this opportunity to highlight an amendment to the information on modes of delivery for next semester. The amendment is that IGHD courses will be delivered by blended learning rather than purely face to face.</p>\n<p>It has been some time since I highlighted the opportunity for staff to request equipment to enable safe working at home. You can find <a rel=\"noopener\" href=\"https://myshare.qmu.ac.uk/services/campus-commercial-services/covid19/SitePages/QMU%20Route%20Map.aspx\" target=\"_blank\">information on the process for requesting equipment here</a>. If you think you need equipment not available from the campus, please speak to your line manager or the Health and Safety Adviser (mkennedy1@qmu.ac.uk) for advice, as there is a process to enable such purchases. Please don’t order equipment yourself because we may not be able to refund you.</p>\n<p>We will be in touch as soon as we have more information on student testing on campus. In the meantime, thank you for your continued patience.</p>"
    },
    {
      "contentTypeKey": "216ea22b-01af-4645-8972-5766bbd75b6c",
      "udi": "umb://element/40c68233a60346e084f9cd36fa314a74",
      "title": "17 November 2020",
      "content": "<p><span class=\"lead\">FOR STUDENTS AND STAFF </span></p>\n<p class=\"x_MsoNormal\"><span class=\"lead\">Update on coronavirus protection levels</span></p>\n<p class=\"x_MsoNormal\">Today, the First Minister gave an <a rel=\"noopener noreferrer\" href=\"https://news.gov.scot/news/updates-to-covid-19-protection-levels\" target=\"_blank\" data-auth=\"NotApplicable\">update on the coronavirus protection levels</a>.</p>\n<p class=\"x_MsoNormal\">The City of Edinburgh will remain in level 3. East Lothian and Midlothian will move down from level 3 to level 2 from Tuesday 24 November.</p>\n<p class=\"x_MsoNormal\">A number of central belt council areas, including West Lothian, will move up to level 4 (ie tighter restrictions) this Friday because infection rates there remain worryingly high, but schools will remain open in level 4 areas. Whilst the requirement that people do not travel out of level 3 or 4 areas except for essential purposes will come into law on Friday, travel for work and education purposes is still permitted. </p>\n<p class=\"x_MsoNormal\">With restrictions in East Lothian easing a little, we will consider the implications for the campus, particularly our catering services and Students’ Union activities, whilst being mindful of the need not to do anything to risk an increase in cases. </p>\n<p class=\"x_MsoNormal\">The First Minister briefly touched on planning for vaccine implementation and for mass asymptomatic testing saying that the end of the pandemic is ‘now within our grasp’. In the meantime, she urged us to remember FACTS.</p>\n<p class=\"x_MsoNormal\"><span class=\"lead\">Plans for COVID testing on campus</span></p>\n<p class=\"x_MsoNormal\">Following the Scottish Government’s announcement of <a rel=\"noopener noreferrer\" href=\"https://www.gov.scot/publications/ministerial-statement-universities-colleges-supporting-students-return-home-safely-end-term/\" target=\"_blank\" data-auth=\"NotApplicable\">measures to support students changing household for the winter break</a>, we can confirm that the University will be participating in the national scheme for COVID testing of asymptomatic students.  We are working at a very rapid pace to ensure that testing of asymptomatic students is available from 30 November for those students who wish to take up the opportunity to be tested. Full information, including how to book a test, will be published just as soon as we have final confirmation of all the important safeguards we need to put in place to deliver the testing, and we will update you as soon as we have finalised details. In the meantime, thank you for your patience and co-operation.</p>\n<p> </p>"
    },
    {
      "contentTypeKey": "216ea22b-01af-4645-8972-5766bbd75b6c",
      "udi": "umb://element/3ec9d3dd97b74e5d99ec2a0c751610ad",
      "title": "13 November 2020",
      "content": "<p><strong>13 November</strong></p>\n<p><strong>FOR STUDENTS</strong></p>\n<p>Dear students</p>\n<p>Following Wednesday’s announcement from the Scottish Government on <a href=\"https://www.gov.scot/publications/ministerial-statement-universities-colleges-supporting-students-return-home-safely-end-term/\">measures to support students changing household for the winter break</a>, we are making good progress on our response, including provision of voluntary testing, and support for students who choose not to return home or change household. We will share more information as soon as we can, including the Q&amp;A’s for students that the government plan to issue.</p>\n<p>As you will know from our update of 6th November, we are planning on maintaining our current approach to learning and teaching into semester two.  Personalised timetables for students in the School of Arts, Social Sciences and Management will be available on December 9<sup>th</sup>, while programme level timetables will be available for students in the School of Health Sciences on December 16<sup>th</sup>, with fuller details to follow.  This difference between the two schools is due to the additional complexity of managing the safe delivery of pre-placement essential skills sessions, and programme specific practical sessions, but we apologise for this delay nonetheless. </p>\n<p>In advance of the provision of that timetable information, we can confirm the following modes of delivery for programmes in semester two: </p>\n<table border=\"0\">\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<th width=\"239\" style=\"width: 243px; text-align: left;\">\n<p>All Arts, Social Sciences and Management undergraduate and postgraduate programmes </p>\n</th>\n<td width=\"231\" style=\"width: 235px;\">\n<p>Blended learning – a mixture of face to face teaching (and practical sessions, where applicable) and online learning </p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<th width=\"239\" style=\"width: 243px; text-align: left;\">\n<p>All Health Sciences undergraduate programmes </p>\n</th>\n<td width=\"231\" style=\"width: 235px;\">\n<p>Blended learning – a mixture of face to face practical sessions and online learning </p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<th width=\"239\" style=\"width: 243px; text-align: left;\">\n<p>All IGHD postgraduate programmes  </p>\n</th>\n<td width=\"231\" style=\"width: 235px;\">\n<p>Blended learning  </p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<th width=\"239\" style=\"width: 243px; text-align: left;\">\n<p>All pre-registration postgraduate Health Sciences programmes (1<sup>st</sup> &amp; 2<sup>nd</sup> years) </p>\n</th>\n<td width=\"231\" style=\"width: 235px;\">\n<p>Blended learning – a mixture of face to face practical and some theory and online learning </p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<th width=\"239\" style=\"width: 243px; text-align: left;\">\n<p>All post-registration postgraduate Health Sciences programmes </p>\n</th>\n<td width=\"231\" style=\"width: 235px;\">\n<p> Fully online</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n<p> </p>\n<p>Please note that for those students with blended learning programmes, while some of your individual <em>modules</em> may be entirely online, your <em>programme</em> will nonetheless be delivered through a mix of face to face and online learning.</p>\n<p>On Tuesday, the First Minister announced an <a href=\"https://news.gov.scot/news/changes-to-covid-19-protection-levels\">update to COVID protection levels</a>. Three council areas moved up a level (to level 3). Edinburgh City and East Lothian remain in level 3.</p>\n<p>We will update you as soon as we have more information to share.  In the meantime, thank you for your continued support, and I hope you feel supported as we work towards preparing for the winter break and the return in the New Year.   As ever, please don’t hesitate to call on the <a href=\"/{localLink:umb://document/a33d92be97574482967def19ff8a302f}\" title=\"Student Services\">support services</a> available in the University if you need any particular help.</p>\n<p><strong>FOR STAFF</strong></p>\n<p>Following Wednesday’s announcement from the Scottish Government on <a href=\"https://www.gov.scot/publications/ministerial-statement-universities-colleges-supporting-students-return-home-safely-end-term/\">measures to support students changing household for the winter break</a>, we are making good progress on our response, including provision of voluntary testing, and support for students who choose not to return home or change household. We will share more information as soon as we can, including the Q&amp;A’s for students that the government plan to issue.</p>\n<p>As you will know from our update of 6th November, we are planning on maintaining our current blended approach to learning and teaching into semester two. Personalised timetables for students in the School of Arts, Social Sciences and Management will be available on December 9<sup>th</sup>, while programme level timetables will be available for students in the School of Health Sciences on December 16<sup>th</sup>, with fuller details to follow.  This difference between the two schools is due to the additional complexity of managing the safe delivery of pre-placement essential skills sessions, and programme specific practical sessions. On Tuesday, the First Minister announced an <a href=\"https://news.gov.scot/news/changes-to-covid-19-protection-levels\">update to COVID protection levels</a>. Three council areas moved up a level (to level 3). Edinburgh City and East Lothian remain in level 3. </p>\n<p>We will update you as soon as we have more information to share.  In the meantime, thank you for your continued support, which really is appreciated.</p>"
    },
    {
      "contentTypeKey": "216ea22b-01af-4645-8972-5766bbd75b6c",
      "udi": "umb://element/aebcf59deeb6448bb9cb5daa93bfa63b",
      "title": "25 September 2020: Important update",
      "content": "<p><span class=\"lead\">COVID-19 (coronavirus) – important update </span></p>\n<p>The University is aware of a small cluster of COVID-19 cases in the halls of residence. We are working with NHS Lothian’s Health Protection Team to address the situation. </p>\n<p><strong>Thanks to the vigilance of students and staff, who have been following the advice and control measures in place, the cluster remains small.</strong> </p>\n<p>The University and the Health Protection Team are in contact with all of the close contacts and advising them to self-isolate for 14 days and providing all necessary guidance and advice. </p>\n<p>The campus remains open for business as usual, with sensible precautions in place. <strong>Unless you have been contacted or you know you have been in close contact with someone that has been symptomatic, e.g. through living in a household or socialising, you should continue to attend classes and work as normal</strong>. We would like to reassure staff and students that the risk of transmission in classrooms is low due to robust social distancing measures, the wearing of face coverings, regular hand washing and cleaning measures already in place. </p>\n<p>We understand that this news may cause concern but please rest assured that the University has a robust approach in place to monitor and mitigate the impact of coronavirus, as set out in our <a href=\"http://www.qmu.ac.uk/coronavirus/covid-19-incident-management-plan/\">incident management plan.</a> </p>\n<p><span class=\"lead\">How you can help </span></p>\n<p>Each of us can help reduce the spread of the virus by:   </p>\n<ul>\n<li>remaining vigilant and aware of the symptoms of COVID-19;</li>\n<li>maintaining social distancing; </li>\n<li>regular handwashing; </li>\n<li>observing the rules prohibiting household visits and social gatherings; </li>\n<li>wearing a face covering in communal areas</li>\n</ul>\n<p><span class=\"lead\">What to do if you develop symptoms </span></p>\n<p>If you have developed symptoms (high temperature, a new continuous cough and/or a loss or change in sense of smell or taste) please follow these steps: </p>\n<ol>\n<li>Self-isolate in your room, do not mix with others in your flat, sleep alone, and do not have any visitors</li>\n<li>Wear a face covering if you have to use the communal areas and ensure you are washing your hands frequently </li>\n<li>You should inform the University (see below for details on how to do this)</li>\n<li>Arrange a COVID-19 test by going to the NHS Inform website. Students requiring assistance in arranging transport to a testing site should contact either Accommodation Services or Security for assistance.</li>\n</ol>\n<p> If you have any other concerns please visit the <a href=\"https://www.nhsinform.scot/illnesses-and-conditions/infections-and-poisoning/coronavirus-covid-19\">NHS Inform</a> website or for non-clinical advice call 0800 028 2816.  </p>\n<p>Remember to stay at home if anyone in your household has symptoms of COVID-19. </p>\n<p>Reporting if you are self-isolating, have symptoms or have a positive test result </p>\n<p>If they are self-isolating, have symptoms of coronavirus, or have coronavirus, students need to: (1) tell Security (0131 474 0000 ext 2222) - and also Accommodation (0131 474 0000 x 4902) if they live on campus; (2) Contact the School Office (<a href=\"mailto:schooloffice@qmu.ac.uk\">schooloffice@qmu.ac.uk</a>).  Staff should contact Security, tell their line manager and email the Head of HR (<a href=\"mailto:nmackie@qmu.ac.uk\">nmackie@qmu.ac.uk</a>) </p>\n<p>Thank you for your support at this time. By working together and following government advice, we can help keep our community safe.</p>"
    },
